[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Welcome and thank you for purchasing Part 2 of my Lifetime Repertoires series on 1.e4. You’ve made a great decision!  In this course we are going to cover 1.e4 and all the Black first move responses apart from  1…e5  which is covered in Part 1, and  1…c5  , which will be covered in part 3.  But before we delve into the chess, my name is Anish Giri, I am a top ten grandmaster, Dutch number one, and by now a many-time Chessable author! I have enjoyed engaging with the Chessable community and learning to understand it better and better for each course I make, and the accumulated experience is put to use in this present course.  My mission has always been to produce courses that I will both personally be proud of, which even my professional colleagues can take a serious look at, and which at the same time are also suited for a broad chess audience, including club players and amateurs. That sounds like a mission impossible, but I think while chess is very hard to play, it is actually much easier to explain and understand. We can build an understanding of what good moves are and why already from a decent entry level.   I believe this repertoire is suited for player of all levels. The aim has been to offer a sound repertoire with the following approach:    we develop our pieces quickly   we take control of the center   we get our king to safety  then slowly but surely we build up an attacking position.
  We don’t rush, we don’t go for early gambits, unprepared attacks, or cheap traps. Sound, principled, and ambitious, with long-term pressure is what we are going for.   Now lets quickly take a look at the major lines covered in the course.  Against  1...e6  , the French Defense, I have gone for  2.d4  d5  3.e5  , the Advance Variation. Grabbing space and embarrassing Black's light-squared bishop. You can see the recommendations more specifically in the French Overview chapter.   The Caro-Kann Defense, is another major opening I devote several chapters to, and here too we go for the Advance Variation  1...c6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  . But as you can see in the Caro-Kann Overview we employ a clever move order which allows us to play largely the same system against both  3...Bf5  and  3...c5  , thereby greatly reducing our workload!   Against  1...d6  , the Pirc Defense, I chose the very solid  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Be2  O-O  6.O-O  which also works equally well against the Modern move order  1...g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nc3  d6  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Be2  O-O  6.O-O  More on this in Chapter 13.   Against the Scandinavian Defense, after  1...d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.Nc3  we cover all the mainline queen moves ...Qd8, ...Qa5, ...Qd6 but some of the sidelines too.   Against  1...Nf6  , the Alekhine Defense, we go for the most ambitious option, the four pawns attack:  2.e5  Nd5  3.c4  Nb6  4.d4  d6  5.f4    This is not completely in the spirit of the rest of the repertoire, we usually start off a bit more reserved. But against the Alekhine I think we can afford to take this approach and will easily manage to back up our powerful pawns with piece development just in time. Black has simply wasted too many tempi with the knight, so I am recommending what is both the most principled and most aggressive approach in Chapter 14.   We also cover complete sidelines like  1…b6  ,  1…a6  , which surprisingly can be difficult to handle if your opponents know the plans and you don’t. But you can rest assured, I have analyzed these lines and after studying this course you will face them with confidence.  I have deliberately kept the number of lines in the course relatively low. We cover what is important to know, but I have tried very hard to not clutter the course with unnecessary material. The specific choices of lines also keep this repertoire very practical and easy to pick up in that sense, and I hope you will take advantage of the carefully curated lines and make it past just the quickstarter guides.   Now go on, get started! See you in the next chapter! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: French Defense"]
[Black "French Advance 6.a3 Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  4...Qb6  or  4...Bd7  and only then follow up with  5.--  Nc6  , but this natural knight development is the most common move order.   4...Qb6  This move can be played with the intention to transpose back to 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 system, but in this move order we look at 4...Qb6 with the intention of going for the Bd7-Bb5 plan.  5.Nf3  Developing the knight is self explanatory.  5...Bd7  Intending to get rid of the bad bishop with Bb5.   As a kid @@StartBracket@@I used to be a French player myself!@@EndBracket@@ I was very attracted to this positional idea, but in this modern day and age, a maneuver this slow looks somewhat artificial. It is important to understand that while it solves the problem of the bad bishop, the issue of the lack of space remains. Taking all this time to trade the bishops takes away from the development of Black's kingside.   4...Ne7  A fancy looking idea, but it looks too good to be true. }
5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 Bd7
{ One of the big moves, Black develops the bishop, then usually also the a8-rook, and only then starts thinking about his kingside development. }
7. b4
{ We continue with the plan, releasing the b-pawn from the attack and forcing Black to clarify the tension in the center. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8
{ An important move, preventing the b1-knight from developing to c3.   Now there are two big moves here,  9.Bb2  and  9.Be3  . I tried  9.Bb2  against Abdusattorov in the World Cup, but I didn't get much going there and for this course I am switching to  9.Be3  . }
9. Be3
{ The bishop defends the d4-pawn and we are ready to develop with Bd3 next. The bishop on e3 is vulnerable to Nh6-Ng4, but on b2 it is also not ideal, as there it would allow Na5!? tricks. }
9... Nh6
{ A better path than  9...Nge7  , because now after  9...Nh6  10.Bd3  besides  10...Nf5?!  Black also gets  10...Ng4! }
10. Bd3
{ We get to develop the bishop to its ideal square. Now Black should go after our e3-bishop sooner or later, so  10...Ng4  and  10...Be7  are interchangeable, while  10...Nf5  is less accurate because it allows the  11.Bxf5  option. }
10... Ng4
{ Black can also start with  10...Be7  11.Nbd2  Ng4  , we go  12.Nb3  and basically, it comes down to the same thing as  12...Nxe3  has to happen. }
11. Nbd2
{ This is a fancy fresh idea, played by Nils Grandelius in 2021. White wants to quickly get Nbd2-Nb3 in before the natural short castle, because after  11.O-O  , Black has a plan of going  11...Nb8  followed by Rc3 or Ba4, preventing our regrouping with Nb3. }
11... Nxe3
{ The immediate  11...Be7  will transpose after  12.Nb3  , while @@StartFEN@@2r1kb1r/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/1P1P2n1/P2BBN2/3N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQk - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f6  has never been played so far as it feels too risky. }
12. fxe3 Be7
{ Now after  13.O-O  we would transpose to hundreds of games, but we go for the rare early  13.Nb3  idea instead. }
13. Nb3 Nb8 { This gives Black a few more options than castling would. } 14.
Qe2 { We prevent Bb5 for now. } 14... Rc3
{ This can be well met with Nfd2, but nonetheless, it's not a bad idea to activate the rook! }
15. Nfd2 Na6
{ A weird looking computer suggestion that has never been played before so far, but Black wants to prepare against Nc5. }
16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. dxc5
{ Black's rook is short of squares inside our camp and as we intend O-O and Nf3, Black needs to come up with some good moves to make sense of this position. }
