[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: French Defense"]
[Black "French Advance 4...Qb6/5...Bd7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 Bb5
{ Offering the trade right away is the most popular way to play, naturally. It does allow some dxc5!? ideas. }
7. Bxb5+
{ This is a simple line, not entering the complications after  7.dxc5!?  Bxc5  8.b4  Bxf2+  9.Kf1  .  The resulting position is crazy and even though the computer likes White, if you dig deeper, it seems to be far from easy. }
7... Qxb5 8. Na3 Qa6
{ Keeping White away from castling, but in the end we will gain some time on the queen. In case of a simple  8...Qd7  we can play  9.Nc2  followed by O-O with a familiar type of position, where we might go for h4-h5 and some slow kingside build up in the long term. We also get such positions in our Caro-Kann repertoire. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 { Kicking the bishop back. } 10... Be7 11. Nd4
{ Intending Nab5, which not only lets us castle but also starts initiative of our own. }
11... Nd7 12. Nab5 Qb6 { Returning to d8 is the best Black has. } 13. Be3
{ Natural. } 13... Qd8
{ Here we should play energetic chess to make use of our lead in development. }
14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh3 { Eyeing the e6-pawn. A sac is coming. } 15... Nxe5 16. Bf4
{ The more things we tie down, the more likely something will get overloaded. }
16... Bf6 17. O-O { The calm before the storm. } 17... a6
{ Black can't stop the inevitable anyway. } 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Nd4
{ We keep e6 alive for now. } 19... Ne7 20. Rae1
{ A correspondence game from 2017 continued  20.Qxe6  , but Black held in the end. We can deviate here and get an advantage. We look at this position in more depth in the main course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3...c5 with 5...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ This is pretty automatic. Next Black is hoping to develop his c8-bishop. } 5.
Be2
{ This is a very clever move order, not allowing Black  5.Nf3  Bg4!  in one go. The bishop on f5 is slightly less well placed than on g4 and that little detail is the difference between Black equalizing comfortably and White being able to put some pressure in the opening.   After  5.Be2  ,  5...Bf5  is the most played move. An alternative would be  5...cxd4!?  first, avoiding the  5...Bf5  6.Nf3  cxd4  7.Nxd4!?  option, and there is also the computer suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6!?  , trying to keep the flexibility and get that Bg4 move in one go after all in case of  6.Nf3  . }
5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Qb6
{ This move has been played quite a few times. Black is hoping for  7.Nf3  Bg4!  but misses our strong reply. }
7. Nc3
{ We don't defend, we attack. Now  7...e6?  would lead to a terrible French after  8.Nf3  , so Black has to trade the central pawns. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nxd5 Qxd1+ 9. Bxd1
{ Black faces a very annoying issue of Nc7+ and that is a serious problem. }
9... Rb8 { Black has to waste time instead of developing. } 10. Nf3
{ We can just develop.  10.e6!?  ,  by the way, is an interesting alternative, trying to spice things up. }
10... e6 11. Nc7+ { Dislodging the black king as well. } 11... Kd8 12. Nb5
{ We want to continue developing, while Black has a much harder task doing that. The pawn structure is fine for Black @@StartBracket@@in fact in some endgames our e5-pawn could be a weakness@@EndBracket@@, but with so many pieces on the board and Black lacking development and coordination, we can use that extra space to our advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3...c5 with 5...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ This is pretty automatic. Next Black is hoping to develop his c8-bishop. } 5.
Be2
{ This is a very clever move order, not allowing Black  5.Nf3  Bg4!  in one go. The bishop on f5 is slightly less well placed than on g4 and that little detail is the difference between Black equalizing comfortably and White being able to put some pressure in the opening.   After  5.Be2  ,  5...Bf5  is the most played move. An alternative would be  5...cxd4!?  first, avoiding the  5...Bf5  6.Nf3  cxd4  7.Nxd4!?  option, and there is also the computer suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6!?  , trying to keep the flexibility and get that Bg4 move in one go after all in case of  6.Nf3  . }
5... Bf5
{ By far the most natural move and the one I would be expecting to face in most of the games. After  5...cxd4  6.cxd4  Bf5  7.Nf3  e6  8.O-O  we transpose to one of my two recommended lines in the 3... Bf5 with 5... c5 chapter. There we also had the option of taking on d4 with the knight, but via the current move order, we have a possible alternative in 7. Nc3 and 8. Be3. }
6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O
{ And suddenly we are back to the 3...Bf5 with 5...c5 main-line, which is extensively covered in the 3...Bf5/5...c5 chapter. }
