{ The third most played move after  5...Nd7  and  5...c5  , but  5...Nd7  will in many cases transpose to 5...Ne7 as well. Generally there are many transpositions as Black, for example, can play Ne7, Nd7 and h6 in any of the orders.   Essentially, in this  5...Ne7  chapter, I would like to look at all the critical variations that can arise when the knight gets developed to e7 @@StartBracket@@before the f8-bishop comes out onto the f8-a3 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. Lines where Black plays without the early Ne7, such as for example the rare Nd7 Be7 setup, will be looked at in the next chapter which covers all the sidelines.I hope that makes sense! }
6. c3
{ With the move orders @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3!?  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.c3!?  , we essentially avoid a large system - @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.O-O  c5  .  This system is not such a problem for White, but it just saves us extra work, since we can place the pawn on c3 against pretty much all of the setups with Ne7. }
6... Nd7
{ This is the main move. Black develops both the knights for now and wants to decide on the future of the f5 and f8-bishops later. }
7. O-O
{ Going for the bishop with  7.Nh4  is possible, but Black seems to be doing fine in the complications after  7...Be4  8.Nd2  c5  .  If Black wants to play the 7. O-O h6 variation, it is also possible for him to start with another move order, for example 5...Ne7 6.c3 h6 7.O-O Nd7. }
7... h6
{ This is a mega super duper tabiya of the entire Advance Caro-Kann and can be reached by all sorts of move orders. It occurs a lot at high level, low level, correspondence, over the board, online and what not. Black is very flexible in his plans. It is still possible to play the position quietly with the bishop dropping back to h7 and so on, but it's also possible to go for the much sharper plans with long castle and/ or g5.I selected a plan that I find quite effective against all of those setups, but in particular against the sharper ones with O-O-O and g5, because these are the things I expect one is mainly concerned about when entering this line with White. The sharp setups are also the ones that I have personally faced in my own experience in this line as well. }
8. Na3
{ The knight is extremely well placed on e3 against the g5 setups and this route is much more efficient than going Nbd2 Re1 Nf1 or Nbd2 and then take the other knight with Ne1-Nc2-Ne3. It is also pretty decent against the plans with c5, since from c2 the knight is contributing well to the fight for the d4-square. Black does have a lot of options here, and we'll consider them one by one. }
8... g5
{ The plans with g5 are exactly what we were hoping for when we sent the b1-knight on a journey. }
9. Nc2
{ The knight is perfect on e3 now, hitting the f5-bishop and controlling the g4-square. }
9... Bg7
{ Black completes development, which makes sense if our knight was on b3 @@StartBracket@@which most white players do, by the way, as they play Nbd2-Nb3 instead of Na3-Nc2@@EndBracket@@, but now our knight is coming to e3, discouraging all the funky business on the kingside and also not being in the way of the b-pawn. }
10. Ne3 Bg6 11. b4
{ Black's king will find safety nowhere, for on the kingside it shall be hit with h4 and on the queenside with a4-b5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 4.Nf3 e6 5.Be2 Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7
{ This move can often transpose to systems looked under 5...Ne7 move order, especially if Black follows this up with h6 and Ne7, but it can also lead to independent lines, if Black chooses not to develop the knight on e7 just yet. }
6. O-O c5 { There are many games, but here this move is absolutely terrible. }
7. c4 Ne7 8. Nc3
{ We have a much better version of many similar lines in this and the 5...Ne7 chapter. This particular variation is kind of winning for White already. }
8... dxc4 9. Bg5
{ Suddenly there is trouble, as  9...h6  is met with  10.Nb5!  and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1nnppp/4p3/2p1PbB1/2pP4/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...a6  with  10.Nd2! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Philidor 3...Nbd7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ This is what they do when they want to play the Philidor, but want to avoid the unpleasant endgame after  3...e5  4.dxe5!? }
4. f4 { The most principled response is to grab more space in the center. }
4... e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ As a rule, a queen is good in the center when it can't be attack with Nc6. I made up this rule at some point and I think it works really well. }
6... c6
{ Black now has to play extremely accurately in order not to get blown away by our impressive central presence. }
7. Bd2
{ The other major move is  7.Be3  , which is more logical and somewhat more popular, but Black is actually getting some play there after  7...d5!  8.e5  Ng4!  when things are far from simple. I like the text move more. }
7... d5 { This works less well here than after 7. Be3. } 8. O-O-O Bc5 9. Qd3
O-O { Black has to sacrifice the pawn, but there isn't enough compensation. }
10. exd5 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5
{ There is no compensation for the pawn here either. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Philidor Endgame 6...Be6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the modern Philidor, which is quite different from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Philidor covered in Part 1 of my 1.e4 LTR. In the old Philidor Black is practically forced to give up the center and then we go for the Bf4 O-O-O setup and get a very sharp position.   Here, Black intends to keep the central tension, which is not possible after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  because after  3.d4  Nd7?  4.Bc4!  there are concrete issues with the f7-pawn. The issue with the 1... d6 move order for Black is that we can trade on e5 and get a better endgame, since Black loses some time moving his king back and forth. }
4. dxe5
{ The mainline continues  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  ,  but then Black gets what he wants: a passive but super solid position full of counter-attacking chances. From my vast experience of playing these Philidor guys, the best way to chase them out of their opening, is to play  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  . In the following game they'll switch to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  and then we hit them with  4.f4  .  The game after that they abandon the Philidor and play some other opening which they like less. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black's king lost the right to castle which can be a factor, especially once the position opens up and many pieces stay on the board. }
6. Bc4
{ I once mixed up the move order in a blitz game and played  6.f4?!  I won anyway, but it is apparently really important to only go for f4 after  6.Bc4  Ke8  . After  6.Bc4  Black has three ways to defend.  6...Ke8  ,  6...Be6  and the rare but decent  6...Bb4!? }
6... Be6
{ This used to be considered really smart back when I was a kid and I remember somehow getting outplayed here with White, but I can really no longer understand how that happened.I think an important idea that White must be aware of and probably what I didn't know as a kid, is that what White will often need to do is remove the knight from c3 and place a pawn there, dominating the c6-knight. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3
{ We have to solidify our e4-pawn and develop a little bit, but in the long run, we need to remove the c3-knight and place the pawn there, not allowing Nc6-Nd4 jumps. }
8... Bd6 9. Be3 { The ideal square for the bishop. } 9... Ke7 10. Nh3
{ The knight on f2 is really weall placed, anticipating g5-g4 ideas. } 10... a6
11. Nf2 Nc6 12. Nb1
{ This is the key idea to remember. We go c3, kill the c6-knight @@StartBracket@@if  12...Nd4  now we have  13.Kd1!  @@EndBracket@@  then go Nd2 Ke2 and once Black has no more constructive ideas, we can start thinking of queenside play with a4-b4 etc. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Pirc with 6...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ The Pirc is a major opening, known for being somewhat dubious but at the same time perhaps the most fighting of all the weapons Black has at his disposal against 1. e4. Black gives up the fight for the center for now, thus avoiding complications and any direct clashes, postponing the fight for a murky middlegame.Indeed, if you outclass your opponent by a ton of rating points or if your opponent has no clue about what he is supposed to do, the Pirc @@StartBracket@@or the Modern defense for that matter, which is another move order to get to very similar positions@@EndBracket@@ is an excellent choice. In case of our opponents, however, they are going to be disappointed, as we have prepared a cold shower for them in this chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ I am going for the Be2 and O-O setup. I have played the more aggressive Be3 system a lot myself and I seriously considered building a repertoire based on even more aggressive setups, but after going over all the options and seeing the tree of my recommendations grow exponentially, I realized that this is just not practical. If we'd play a very sharp line, we would give Black exactly what they want, which is a sharp double-edged position. No matter how well you will remember your lines, they are rarely all too clear in the end and Black always has some room for a surprise or a tricky move order to get us confused.Instead, I think my recommendation of Be2 and O-O is not only objectively very challenging, but is also very clever from the psychological viewpoint. We immediately show Black that today is not going to be about fun for him, as there are no attacks or crazy tactics. All Black gets today is a near symmetrical position, but with Black being more passive and having less space. }
4... Bg7
{ There is something to be said for delaying Bg7 in systems where White goes for Be3-Qd2-Bh6 setups, but when we want to go for Be2 and O-O there isn't much point to that.   4...c6  5.Be2  b5  is just outright absurd due to  6.e5!  dxe5  7.Nxe5  when the c6-pawn is terribly weak. }
5. Be2 { Our modest but efficient development scheme, intending short castle. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... Nc6
{ This provocative move is very trendy. The position can also arise from the wacky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nc6  2.Nf3  d6  system-  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  5.Be2  Bg7  6.O-O  O-O  . Black claims that us losing the flexibility of our pawn structure with  7.d5  is worth spending two tempi for. I'm not sure if that's true. }
7. d5
{ Black doesn't have a good square for the knight, so we should go for it. }
7... Nb8
{ The most common reply. Black lost two tempi to provoke d4-d5 and we lost some of out flexibility in the center, but the time we gained for development will prove quite valuable. }
8. Be3
{ It's also possible to develop with  8.Re1  or  8.Bg5  ,  but I like this basic development move. We don't need to do anything odd here. Just standard moves should give us a good position, as Black has played rather provocatively in the opening.   Now after  8.Be3  Black has various options, but essentially he has to decide how to undermine our d5-pawn, with either  8...e6  which will be met with  9.dxe6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/3P4/4P3/2N1BN2/PPP1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c6  ,  which will be met with us further solidifying our d5-pawn. }
8... c6
{ The most common way to play. Black wants to at some point utilize the c-file. }
9. a4 { The b5-square requires some overprotection. } 9... a5
{ This makes sense, but it weakens the b6-square, where our knight will be headed right away. Also, once Black has played a5, now whenever he takes on d5, he will have a huge issue due to the weakened b5-square. }
10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 { Black simply lacks moves here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Pirc with 6...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ The Pirc is a major opening, known for being somewhat dubious but at the same time perhaps the most fighting of all the weapons Black has at his disposal against 1. e4. Black gives up the fight for the center for now, thus avoiding complications and any direct clashes, postponing the fight for a murky middlegame.Indeed, if you outclass your opponent by a ton of rating points or if your opponent has no clue about what he is supposed to do, the Pirc @@StartBracket@@or the Modern defense for that matter, which is another move order to get to very similar positions@@EndBracket@@ is an excellent choice. In case of our opponents, however, they are going to be disappointed, as we have prepared a cold shower for them in this chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ I am going for the Be2 and O-O setup. I have played the more aggressive Be3 system a lot myself and I seriously considered building a repertoire based on even more aggressive setups, but after going over all the options and seeing the tree of my recommendations grow exponentially, I realized that this is just not practical. If we'd play a very sharp line, we would give Black exactly what they want, which is a sharp double-edged position. No matter how well you will remember your lines, they are rarely all too clear in the end and Black always has some room for a surprise or a tricky move order to get us confused.Instead, I think my recommendation of Be2 and O-O is not only objectively very challenging, but is also very clever from the psychological viewpoint. We immediately show Black that today is not going to be about fun for him, as there are no attacks or crazy tactics. All Black gets today is a near symmetrical position, but with Black being more passive and having less space. }
4... Bg7
{ There is something to be said for delaying Bg7 in systems where White goes for Be3-Qd2-Bh6 setups, but when we want to go for Be2 and O-O there isn't much point to that.   4...c6  5.Be2  b5  is just outright absurd due to  6.e5!  dxe5  7.Nxe5  when the c6-pawn is terribly weak. }
5. Be2 { Our modest but efficient development scheme, intending short castle. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... c6
{ This is a hugely popular move, intending to either slowly prepare b5 with c6 b6 a6 Bb7 @@StartBracket@@because White will obviously play  7.a4!  next@@EndBracket@@,  or e5 with Qc7 and/or Nbd7. However, the first plan is too slow, while the second is not a panacea, since the combo of having a pawn on e5 and having the bishop on g7 is not ideal. }
7. a4 Nbd7 8. h3
{ Perhaps more principled is to push 8. a5, but I like the fact that the simple, most often played setup also gives us a clear advantage. }
8... e5 { For  8...Qc7  see the line 7...Qc7 8. h3 Nbd7. } 9. dxe5
{ A standard reaction. We make sure the bishop on g7 is staring into the e5-pawn. }
9... dxe5 10. Bc4
{ This is stronger than the more popular move 10.Be3. We should remain flexible with the c1-bishop, hoping for Qe7. }
10... Qe7 11. b3
{ This is very nasty, pointing out that the queen on e7 is misplaced. Black is doing terribly here. At the risk of repeating myself, the combination of having a pawn on e5 and the bishop on g7 is generally not a great thing. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Scandinavian with 3...Qd8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian.  The Gambit  2...c6  is not really correct, but  2...Nf6  is somewhat of a legitimate alternative as we've seen. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qd8
{ This modest move is really not so bad and it's quite popular especially in online play, or at least that's my own experience. Black just wants to get the queen out of harms way and finish his development. We did gain some tempi, though, and so can pose problems to Black if we develop aggressively enough. }
4. d4 { As usual, the moves d4 and Nf3 are no-brainers. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ Black has a few setups here, but each has some flaws. } 5... Bg4
{ The most popular move. Black wants to give up the bishop and get a solid position with no weaknesses. This would be a decent plan, if we were to castle short and leave Black alone, but we have aggressive intentions. }
6. h3
{ I have discovered that I apparently once played  6.Be2?!  in an online blitz game here against Bartel. What a miserable move. What a shame! Of course we should go for the most challenging continuation. }
6... Bxf3
{ Obviously  6...Bh5  is a disaster after  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  ,  when the bishop is in big trouble, with h4 coming.  8...Nbd7  9.Qe2!  puts the dot on the i. }
7. Qxf3 c6
{ Here we have to go for long castle plans and the natural way to do it is  8.Be3  ,  which is perfectly reasonable and very strong too, but I propose to do it the most aggressive way possible here. }
8. g4 { Going for the throat. } 8... e6 { It's too late to be solid. } 9. g5
Nd5 10. Ne4 { Intending Bd2 and O-O-O. White is way ahead with the attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Scandinavian with 3...Qd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian.  The Gambit  2...c6  is not really correct, but  2...Nf6  is somewhat of a legitimate alternative as we've seen. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qd6
{ This was very trendy at some point at a reasonably high level, as it even started featuring in some top events, around 10 years ago. Ever since, though, White has found ways to gain an opening edge. Still, an occasional Scandi-fan can throw this one out. The queen is more centralized than in the Qa5 system, but is still quite vulnerable, which we can exploit to our advantage. }
4. d4 { Pawn to d4 and knight to f3 are pretty much the automatic moves. } 4...
Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is a sub-tabiya. Black has a few options and we should know how to respond to each and one of them. }
5... a6
{ This is the old main-line. Black intends to develop with Bg4 and Nc6 and eventually castle long. However, White has quickly found a way to put this old setup out of business, with some accurate dynamic play. }
6. g3
{ This is not just to fianchetto the bishop, but also to prepare an outpost for the other bishop on f4. }
6... Bg4
{ The most critical. Against any other setup, we follow up with the Bg2 and Bf4 plan. }
7. h3 { Asking the bishop to clarify its intentions. } 7... Bh5
{ If Black gives up the bishop, we get easy play with Be3 and O-O-O, enjoying our extra space, development and the bishop pair advantage as well. }
8. Bg2 { We finish our kingside development before going on the offensive. }
8... Nc6
{ Black's play can be annoying if we start playing defensively here, but if we know what we are doing, we can pretty much get a winning advantage at this point already. }
9. d5 { Only forward. } 9... Nb4 10. Bf4 { Finally using the platform on f4. }
10... Qc5 11. Be3
{ Essentially we got a free tempo for the development of the bishop. } 11...
Qa5
{ This is often played as well, but it's also pretty much losing for Black. }
12. O-O
{ We can give up the d5-pawn, being way ahead in development. Just look at Black's kingside. }
12... Rd8
{ Some old e-mail games continued like this and Black lost pretty much all of them. }
13. Qe2 Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bd2 { A retreat before going forward. } 15...
Qc5 16. c4 { Kicking the knight to a less favorable position. } 16... Nb6 17.
Rac1
{ We can just complete our mobilization. Black will not be in time to finish his development. We look at this position in more depth in the main course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Scandinavian with 3...Qd6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian.  The Gambit  2...c6  is not really correct, but  2...Nf6  is somewhat of a legitimate alternative as we've seen. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qd6
{ This was very trendy at some point at a reasonably high level, as it even started featuring in some top events, around 10 years ago. Ever since, though, White has found ways to gain an opening edge. Still, an occasional Scandi-fan can throw this one out. The queen is more centralized than in the Qa5 system, but is still quite vulnerable, which we can exploit to our advantage. }
4. d4 { Pawn to d4 and knight to f3 are pretty much the automatic moves. } 4...
Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is a sub-tabiya. Black has a few options and we should know how to respond to each and one of them. }
5... c6
{ The most solid option. Black takes control of the b5-square and retains some flexibility in his development. }
6. Ne5
{ The most principled, though the  6.g3  system also seemed appealing to me when I was exploring the options. }
6... Nbd7
{ The established response. Black right away challenges our knight.  6...g6  7.Bf4!  is not easy to face, as  7...Nh5  8.Be3  just misplaces the Black knight. }
7. f4
{ I played the old theoretical move  7.Nc4  against Artemiev and only achieved a symbolic advantage. When returning to this line, I discovered that the brutal gain of space with  7.f4  is highly appreciated by the modern computers and they are pretty much always right these days. Or at least, there isn't anyone to prove them wrong. }
7... Nb6
{ The main 'theoretical' move, if we can speak of theory here. I recall an old Shirov-Tiviakov game from back in 2010. The modern computer is laughing, saying Black should already start packing his bags.   That said, the engine suggestion of  7...a5!?  is not solving his problems either. }
8. g4
{ Grabbing further space. Black has tried different things here, but it seems he can't get enough counterplay for all the space White has gotten. }
8... g6
{ Black can finish his kingside development, but it doesn't solve all of his opening problems. }
9. Bg2
{ Our plan is to complete the development and then cramp Black with f5. } 9...
Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. a4
{ The computer likes to gain some space on the queenside as well. } 11... a5
12. f5 { A thematic idea. The c8-bishop is now cramped and Black lacks air. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3... Qa5 with 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian. The Gambit 2...c6 is not really correct, but 2...Nf6 is somewhat of a legitimate alternative. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qa5
{ The most popular and also the traditional main move. At some point the  3...Qd6  line was more trendy at the high level, but now things have come full circle and it's this old move which is the main way to go. }
4. d4
{ It seems that  4.Nf3  will most likely transpose, but this is just a more natural move order. We need to grab space in the center anyway. }
4... Nf6
{ The right move order, developing the knight and also hinting at some Bg4!? ideas, if White tries to be clever with moves like  5.Bc4  or  5.Bd2  . The alternatives to this are clearly inferior and we welcome them. }
5. Nf3
{ I tried to be smart, but the moves  5.Bd2  as well as  5.Bc4  are well met with the provocative  5...Bg4!  when we have to weaken ourselves with  6.f3  . Even though those lines continue, White is no longer crushing it in the same way as for example @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5?!  5.Bd2! }
5... Bg4 { This is played a lot as well, but is just bad here. } 6. h3
{ Chasing the bishop, of course. } 6... Bh5
{ If Black wants to give up the bishop, he is much worse for nothing, we will go Bd2 O-O-O and enjoy both the better development as well as the bishop pair. }
7. g4 Bg6 8. Nd2
{ This is apparently a more accurate version of  8.Ne5  ,  but both moves give White a winning advantage according to the mighty modern engines. }
8... e6 9. h4
{ There is a threat of h5 and if Black tries to play h6 or h5 himself, then Nc4-Ne5 will be bad news. Black is sort of lost here, apparently. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3... Qa5 with 4...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian. The Gambit 2...c6 is not really correct, but 2...Nf6 is somewhat of a legitimate alternative. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qa5
{ The most popular and also the traditional main move. At some point the  3...Qd6  line was more trendy at the high level, but now things have come full circle and it's this old move which is the main way to go. }
4. d4
{ It seems that  4.Nf3  will most likely transpose, but this is just a more natural move order. We need to grab space in the center anyway. }
4... Nf6
{ The right move order, developing the knight and also hinting at some Bg4!? ideas, if White tries to be clever with moves like  5.Bc4  or  5.Bd2  . The alternatives to this are clearly inferior and we welcome them. }
5. Nf3
{ I tried to be smart, but the moves  5.Bd2  as well as  5.Bc4  are well met with the provocative  5...Bg4!  when we have to weaken ourselves with  6.f3  . Even though those lines continue, White is no longer crushing it in the same way as for example @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5?!  5.Bd2! }
5... Bf5
{ This, as well as  5...c6  can often transpose, but this move order gives Black an extra option of 6...e6 against our 6.Bd2 setup. }
6. Bd2
{ A major tabiya arises after  6.Ne5!?  c6  7.Bc4  e6  8.g4  Bg6  9.h4  Nbd7  10.Nxd7  Nxd7  11.h5  Be4  12.O-O  Bd5  13.Nxd5  cxd5  @@StartBracket@@all of Black's moves are practically forced@@EndBracket@@. White seems to be better there as well, but I think my recommendation is even better, especially when it comes to the practical aspect of things. The engine likes both moves almost equally, but it doesn't take into account that some positions are easier for us human noobs to play than others. }
6... c6
{ This leads to a major tabiya with thousand of games, but it actually seems quite miserable for Black in the end. }
7. Bc4
{ Our general concept is to castle long after Qe2, but we also have an important idea of Nd5. }
7... e6
{ The most popular move. Black just doesn't care about the  8.Nd5  threat. Wrongly so, as it's actually a big deal here. }
8. Nd5
{ A trick to remember. Now that Black will have to recapture on f6 with a queen or the pawn, we are happy to make this trade. }
8... Qd8 9. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ This is the most popular move. Black may appear to have some play on the kingside, thanks to the open g-file, but in fact it's quite easy to neutralize. Black's king, on the other hand, doesn't have a safe spot in the long term. }
10. O-O Nd7 11. Re1
{ The plan is simple. We want to neutralize any potential kingside play with Bf1 and g3 @@StartBracket@@and if needed Bg2@@EndBracket@@, while on the queenside we will roll with b4, c4 and what not. }
11... Qc7 { This is the most common move, but it allows a tactical shot. } 12.
Nh4 { A good moment to chase the bishop. } 12... Bg6 13. Bxe6
{ This just does it. Playing it slow would also be good, but if it's possible to unleash a strong tactic, why not do so? }
13... fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf7 15. Qe2
{ White is positionally winning. Black's king is too weak and it's mainly the fact that there is no coordination in Black's camp. }
