[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Modern with 3...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ The Modern Defense is a sibling of the Pirc, and in our case, it will almost certainly transpose to it, given our sophisticated move order trickery. Black is delaying the development of the g8-knight, which can be quite smart especially against the Be3-Qd2-Bh6 ideas, but he does allow a transposition into the King's Indian with  2.d4  Bg7  3.c4  .  For us, as mentioned, it doesn't matter, since we play the solid and sound Be2 system in either case, when Black's best bet is to bring the knight out to f6 anyway. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3
{ We are delaying the move Nc3, not allowing Black to hit us with the early a6-b5 expansion, which is the signature of the Modern.   Now, by far the main move is  3...d6  , but there are also some alternatives. }
3... d6 4. Be2
{ A highly sophisticated move order, breaking the 'knight before bishops' rule coined by Lasker. That rule is more of a recommendation and it's being broken left and right. In this particular case, we don't hide our modest intentions with Be2 and O-O, while we will only expose our knight to the a6-b5 idea once Black goes Nf6. }
4... Nd7 { The e5 plan is popular but flawed. } 5. O-O e5
{ There is no point in playing the weakening a6-b5 expansion, since our knight is on b1 not on c3 and after a4, the move b4 doesn't gain that tempo and just weakens the pawn. }
6. dxe5 dxe5
{ The combination of having the bishop on g7 and also pushing e5 is more often than not just very bad. Unlike the King's Indian where White would have the pawn on c4, we don't have a weak d4-square here. }
7. Nc3 { We can just develop Nc3, a4, Bc4 in any order. } 7... Ngf6 8. a4
{ The move order doesn't matter. } 8... O-O 9. Bc4
{ With an excellent position. Black will likely play  9...c6  when  10.h3  transposes to a line we look at in Pirc 6...c6 system, which is quite poor for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Alekhine with 5...dxe5/6...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine is a highly provocative and not entirely sound opening, but it remains a regular guest in games accross all levels. Some top players, including Magnus Carlsen employ it every now and then as a surprise weapon and among club players and amateurs as well, you see some fans of this direct approach. Black provokes us to push forward and we don't have to be asked twice to grab more space in the center. }
2. e5 Nd5
{ This is how the Alekhine was meant to be played. On e4 the knight is too vulnerable, while going back to g8 is far too provocative, even for the diehard Alekhine fans. }
3. c4
{ I wasn't able to spot any significant difference between  3.c4  or  3.d4  for us. I believe they call this a 'soft-fail move' on Chessable. Still, I think maaaaybe  3.c4  would be my choice and that for two reasons. First of all, after  3.d4  there is a very odd  3...c6!?  idea, intending to hide the knight on c7. Secondly, and that is important for the bullet fans, there are apparently people who after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  play  3...Ne3??  hoping for a  4.d4  premove. Punishing those players, that is a very satisfying feeling, trust me. }
3... Nb6
{ The only reasonable move, but again, don't premove 4. d4, for the 3...Ne3?? psychos. }
4. d4 { Three of our four pawns are ready for the Four Pawns Attack! } 4... d6
{ Black should start undermining our center before it's too too late. } 5. f4
{ The most principled system. I was never a fan of systems where we overextend ourselves, as some of my favourite games in my childhood were the counterattacking King's Indian defense games by Fischer and Kasparov.However, in this particular instance it appears that the Four Pawns Attack, which definitely leaves an overextended impression, is an overwhelming favorite of the modern engines which dictate the opening trends. After trying to find a way for Black to undermine our pawn structure and get good counterplay, and failing along the way, I came to the conclusion that this system is worthy of recommending.   The old mainline, the simple @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  , is not nearly as challenging and gives Black plenty of ways to get a playable position, exactly what he wants when going for the Alekhine.   After  5.f4  Black generally has two setups, going for Bf5 e6 development  @@StartBracket@@usually after  5...dxe5  @@EndBracket@@ or the  5...g6  plan. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6
{ The most popular move order, but Black can also start with 6...Bf5 which in most cases leads to the same tabiya. }
7. Be3
{ Here it's important to start with the bishop move, as  7.Nf3  allows the pin with  7...Bg4  . It is quite logical, so shouldn't be that hard to remember. }
7... Bf5
{ Black's only way to develop sensibly here. Next they want to go e6 and develop the f8 bishop as well. }
8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ It's also possible is to start with  9.Be2  ,  but I don't see the reason to be this subtle here as ...Bg4 now comes with a loss of a tempo, having developed itself to f5 first. In this major tabiya Black's main plan is  9...Be7  followed by f6, but we should also know how to deal with the less conventional alternatives. }
9... Be7
{ The mainline of the entire Four Pawns Attack. Black is not trying to do anything weird, but wants to castle and break our center apart with f6. }
10. Be2
{ A few decades ago there was a trend of going for a mess with 10. d5, but the modern computers have established that Black is fine there, while in the simple 10.Be2 line he just gets a worse position. }
10... O-O 11. O-O f6
{ This is a neccessary idea to deal with our strong pawn center, but the problem Black now gets is the weak e6-pawn, as well as the awkward knight on b6 of course. }
12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2
{ White has to make sure the d4-pawn is under control. That is the key in this position, otherwise we are just slightly better thanks to our better pawn structure and the terrible knight on b6. }
13... Qe7
{ By far the most played move. Black just wants to bring the a8-rook into the game. Fair enough, we will do the same thing with the a1-rook. }
14. Rad1 { Mobilizing. } 14... Rad8
{ The x-ray on the d-file seems annoying, but we shouldn't give in and fall for it. }
15. Kh1
{ Black didn't really have a threat, despite the x-ray on the d-file, while the natural  15.Qc1?!  @@StartBracket@@which is still the most played move in this position@@EndBracket@@ would actually allow a trick:  15...e5!  16.d5  Nd4!  17.Nxd4  exd4  18.Bxd4  Bg5!  19.Qa1  Na4!  20.Bf3  Be3+  and Black has great compensation for the pawn @@StartBracket@@this all happened in Perunovic-Berkes 2019@@EndBracket@@. With the text move we don't allow any such shenanigans. }
15... h6 { Black can make a waiting move and we will do the same. } 16. h3
{ We are happy with how things are going, so we also make some useful moves. }
16... Rd7 17. Qc1
{ Now e5 no longer works, as the king is nicely tucked away on h1 and Ray managed to convert this advantage into a full point eventually.  17...Rfd8  can be met with  18.d5!  here thanks to the potential pin after Bc4 in the end.   17...Kh8  18.Bg1  Rfd8  will be met with the thematic  19.c5!  Nd5  20.Bb5  when the pressure on the d4 pawn is swiftly dealt with. }
