[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "1...Nc6 with 2...d6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ This system really doesn't make all too much sense against us, as we are fine with all the transpositions that can eventually arise. }
2. Nf3
{ There is no need to get provoked. Also,  2.d4  d5  is actually not such a bad system for Black.   After  2.Nf3  if Black goes  2...e5  we can play our Italian @@StartBracket@@or a Spanish or Scotch if that's what you prefer@@EndBracket@@ and so in this chapter we should look at other options. }
2... d6
{ This move order makes a lot of sense against people who play systems without Nf3 against the Pirc, but against the Pirc we are playing the Nf3 Be2 system, so we don't care that the knight came out so early to c6. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bg4
{ Many beginners play this way. It's incredibly suspicious, though with the inclusion of Nf6 and Nc3 it is less bad. }
5. Be2
{ We can play in the same spirit as against the Pirc. The  5.d5  Ne5  6.Nxe5!?  idea now only leads to a slightly better endgame after  6...Bxd1  7.Bb5+  c6  8.dxc6  dxe5  9.c7   @@StartBracket@@now there is no  9.cxb7+  because of  9...Nd7!  @@EndBracket@@  9...Qd7  10.Bxd7  Kxd7  etc. }
5... e6 { This is played a lot, but I don't really understand why. } 6. d5 exd5
7. exd5 Bxf3 8. gxf3
{ The simple  8.Bxf3  is also great, but the modern engines really like this creative approach. }
8... Ne5 9. h4
{ We grab space on the kingside and since we have two f-pawns, we don't have to weaken ourselves too much in order to do so. }
9... Be7 10. h5 O-O 11. h6
{ As we know from all the AlphaZero hype, this pawn can be great for us in the long term. }
11... g6 12. f4 Ned7 13. Bf3
{ White has a huge long term edge because we control all the squares. If you want to keep it simple, however, @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/3P4/8/2N2b2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bxf3  is a great option too. }
