[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "1... b6 with 3...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... e6 { The most popular continuation. } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Qe2 f5
{ Best, as after  6...d5  we can try to trap the knight with O-O Ne1 ideas, or simply exchange it off with Nbd2 getting an overwhelming positional advantage in the spirit of the Advanced French. }
7. Nbd2 Nxd2 8. Bxd2
{ We will crush after long castle as Rhg1 g4 will happen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) French Overview"]
[Black "French Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  4...Qb6  or  4...Bd7  and only then follow up with  5.--  Nc6  , but this natural knight development is the most common move order.   4...Qb6  This move can be played with the intention to transpose back to 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 system, but in this move order we look at 4...Qb6 with the intention of going for the Bd7-Bb5 plan.  5.Nf3  Developing the knight is self explanatory.  5...Bd7  Intending to get rid of the bad bishop with Bb5.   As a kid @@StartBracket@@I used to be a French player myself!@@EndBracket@@ I was very attracted to this positional idea, but in this modern day and age, a maneuver this slow looks somewhat artificial. It is important to understand that while it solves the problem of the bad bishop, the issue of the lack of space remains. Taking all this time to trade the bishops takes away from the development of Black's kingside.   4...Ne7  A fancy looking idea, but it looks too good to be true. }
5. Nf3 { The obvious developing move that needs no further explanation. } 5...
Qb6
{ The most popular system and the one I recommended in my Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. Black delays the development of other pieces and prioritizes the pressure on the d4-pawn. Another important function of the move 5...Qb6 is that it is eyeing the b2-pawn, making it difficult for White to develop the c1-bishop.   5...Bd7  I always considered this to be somewhat secondary @@StartBracket@@maybe because as a kid, I learnt that Qb6 is the way to go@@EndBracket@@, but it is a very serious system, with Black prioritizing his development. This has been played by the biggest names of modern chess, including Fabiano Caruana and Ian Nepomniachtchi.  6.Be2  This is the way to go here.   Without the queen on b6, a3-b4 is less attractive, while developing the bishop to d3, which in itself is a better square, is overoptimistic as  6.Bd3  is met by  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  Qb6  ,  hitting the d4-pawn.  6...Nge7  7.O-O  Natural, but not at all the only way to proceed.   Alternatively, White could use the fact that the f8-bishop briefly lost sight of the a3-square and toss in a  7.Na3!?  intending Nc2, a common idea in the Advanced French.  That said, I will stick to the natural short castle as my main recommendation. Here Black once again has a few options of how he untangles his kingside pieces to finally develop the f8-bishop.  7...Ng6  The knight is contributing to the fight for the e5-square, as the f6 break is becoming Black's main source of potential counterplay against White's strong pawn center. The disadvantage of the knight here is that it can potentially get hit by g3-h4-h5 and also that it doesn't quite target the d4-pawn.   7...Nf5  A natural way to develop the knight but it does allow  8.dxc5  ,  when the knight on f5 that was targetting the d4-pawn will experience a mid-life crisis, having lost its main purpose.   7...cxd4  Black wants to capture on d4 before going Nf5, making sure the knight jump won't be met with dxc5 @@StartBracket@@see the 7...Nf5 8. dxc5 line@@EndBracket@@. However, White now gets access to the ideal square for the b1-knight.  8.cxd4  Nf5  9.Nc3  The best square for the knight and now Qb6 can always be repelled with Na4. Here Black usually chooses between  9...Rc8  and  9...a6  , as  9...Be7?!  @@StartBracket@@a common positional mini-blunder@@EndBracket@@ falls into  10.Bd3!  when the d4-pawn is taboo:  10...Nfxd4  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Qg4!  with a nasty double attack against the d4-knight and the g7-pawn.   5...Nge7  A rare move that started gaining in popularity lately, mainly because it is a rare move. }
6. a3
{ The most often played move, but a rather deep one. Instead of developing pieces right away, White is going for the maximalistic approach of clearing up the c3-square for the knight by preparing b4, which will force the c5-pawn to determine its future. Also, White prepares Bd3-Bc2, having secured from any Nb4 jumps.   This is another major junction. Black can close the pawn structure with  6...c4  ,  using the weakness of the b3-square, prevent the b4 push with  6...a5  or choose to develop his light pieces with  6...Bd7  ,  6...Nh6  ,  6...Nge7  or capture with  6...cxd4  first. }
*

