[Black "French Advance 6.a3 Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  4...Qb6  or  4...Bd7  and only then follow up with  5.--  Nc6  , but this natural knight development is the most common move order.   4...Qb6  This move can be played with the intention to transpose back to 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 system, but in this move order we look at 4...Qb6 with the intention of going for the Bd7-Bb5 plan.  5.Nf3  Developing the knight is self explanatory.  5...Bd7  Intending to get rid of the bad bishop with Bb5.   As a kid @@StartBracket@@I used to be a French player myself!@@EndBracket@@ I was very attracted to this positional idea, but in this modern day and age, a maneuver this slow looks somewhat artificial. It is important to understand that while it solves the problem of the bad bishop, the issue of the lack of space remains. Taking all this time to trade the bishops takes away from the development of Black's kingside.   4...Ne7  A fancy looking idea, but it looks too good to be true. }
5. Nf3 Qb6
{ The most popular system and the one I recommended in my Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. Black delays the development of other pieces and prioritizes the pressure on the d4-pawn. Another important function of the move 5...Qb6 is that it is eyeing the b2-pawn, making it difficult for White to develop the c1-bishop.   Releasing the tension in the center immediately with  5...cxd4  as is fairly common in amateur play is just a positional mistake as after  6.cxd4  we get the c3-square available for our knight. The same is true if this capture happens a move earlier. }
6. a3 Bd7
{ One of the big moves, Black develops the bishop, then usually also the a8-rook, and only then starts thinking about his kingside development. }
7. b4
{ We continue with the plan, releasing the b-pawn from the attack and forcing Black to clarify the tension in the center. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8
{ An important move, preventing the b1-knight from developing to c3.   Now there are two big moves here,  9.Bb2  and  9.Be3  . I tried  9.Bb2  against Abdusattorov in the World Cup, but I didn't get much going there and for this course I am switching to  9.Be3  . }
9. Be3
{ The bishop defends the d4-pawn and we are ready to develop with Bd3 next. The bishop on e3 is vulnerable to Nh6-Ng4, but on b2 it is also not ideal, as there it would allow Na5!? tricks. }
9... Nh6
{ A better path than  9...Nge7  , because now after  9...Nh6  10.Bd3  besides  10...Nf5?!  Black also gets  10...Ng4! }
10. Bd3
{ We get to develop the bishop to its ideal square. Now Black should go after our e3-bishop sooner or later, so  10...Ng4  and  10...Be7  are interchangeable, while  10...Nf5  is less accurate because it allows the  11.Bxf5  option. }
10... Nf5
{ This is mostly played via the move order @@StartFEN@@2r1kbnr/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/1P1P4/P3BN2/5PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQk - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nge7  10.Bd3  Nf5  and it's not ideal for Black, since we get a very good version of the Bxf5 positions here. }
11. Bxf5 exf5 12. O-O Be7
{ Both sides will want to complete their development. } 13. Nc3
{ One would expect the knight to be heading to f4, but it can actually also find purpose on g3. }
13... Be6 14. Ne2
{ Playing on the queenside with  14.Na4  and  --  15.Nc5  is also a possible way of playing. }
14... O-O 15. Qd3
{ Suddenly there is a positional threat of  15...--  16.Ng3  when  16...g6  would weaken the dark squares. }
15... Qd8 { A logical way to defend the f5-pawn, but somewhat passive. } 16.
Ng3 Qd7 17. Qd2
{ We intend some trickery on the dark squares on the kingside with Nh5 and Bg5/Bh6 stuff. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
