{ In essence, if Black doesn't get seduced by the extra pawn, which he very well might, what we eventually will get is a Nf5 Bxf5 exf5 pawn structure, but likely a better version of the old line which was  8.cxd4  Bd7  9.Bc2  Nf5  10.Bxf5  exf5  . }
8... Nf5 { This is natural but somewhat mistimed. } 9. b4
{ We can also start with  9.c4!?  , but why not first make the useful moves? After  9.b4  the move  9...dxc3  is always welcomed. We will just take  10.Nxc3  and continue mobilizing. }
9... Be7 10. Re1 a6 11. c4
{ There are a few options, but I like this one quite a bit. In the arising position, the d4-pawn just blocks the files and diagonals for the black pieces, while we can build some potent attacking setups around it. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4
{ Let's take a look at how the play can unfold if Black just makes some primitive moves. }
12... O-O
{ Probably smarter is to try and postpone the castle, but it's hard to come up with a good plan for Black. }
13. Bd3
{ The bishop sits really well here, blocking the d-pawn which is of no use for Black. On the contrary, it stands in the way of Black's counterplay. }
13... Bd7 14. Nbd2 Rfc8
{ I am just making some random moves with Black here, but that's the problem: it's not easy to suggest a great idea for Black in a position like this. }
15. Ne4 { We just bring all our pieces slowly towards the kingside. } 15... Qd8
16. Qe2 Na7 { Black intends Bb5 here, but now we prepare for action. } 17. Bf4
{ Bringing the last undeveloped light piece into play. } 17... Bb5
{ Following the plan mindlessly is wrong, but that's what humans usually tend to do. We tend to do wrong things. Better is  17...h6  but then  18.g4!  anyway:  18...Nh4  19.Nxh4  Bxh4  20.Nd6  with a strong initiative. }
18. g4
{ The knight on f5 starts feeling claustrophobic here. After  18...Nh4  we will capture  19.Nxh4  Bxh4  and trap the bishop with  20.g5! }
