{ The most flexible and the best move. The moves Bd7 Rc8 are Black's main priority, since it's important for him to control the squares along the c-file.   If instead Black plays  8...Be7  we can go  9.Bxh6!  gxh6  10.b4  ,  when Black no longer has Bg7. }
9. b4 { We grab space on the queenside. } 9... Rc8
{ The most useful move of all the waiting ones, not rushing with development of the kingside just yet, since  9...Nf5  allows  10.Bxf5  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p2n/3pP3/1P1p4/P1PB1N2/5PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq b3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be7  10.Bxh6  .   Besides waiting, the move  9...Rc8  also creates some clever concrete ideas. For example,  10.Re1  is now met with  10...dxc3  11.Nxc3  Ng4!  12.Ra2  Ncxe5!  or  12...Nxb4!  ,  when the knight on c3 hangs. }
10. Bb2
{ We threaten cxd4 and also reinforce our c3-square, so that after  10...dxc3  11.Nxc3  there are no Nxb4 related tricks. }
10... dxc3
{ This once again is not a great move. Now we get our b1-knight into the game. }
11. Nxc3 Be7
{ This was played in Asadli-Anand rapid 2021. Facing a lower rated player, Vishy Anand clearly has taken a lot of risks, which was too dangerous of a decision. }
12. Rc1
{ Asadli played  12.Nb5?!  , but a week later Mosadeghpour improved over it against Vetoshko. }
12... O-O
{ Here White went for the tempting and decent Na4-Nc5 idea, but there was an even stronger option available. }
13. Bb1
{ With a nasty threat of  13...--  14.Qd3  which is hard to meet, since  14...g6  weakens the position further and will then be met by  15.Qd2  . Note that on  15...Kg7  there is always the  16.Nxd5  exd5  17.e6+  idea. }
