{ This is a very decent idea at this point and it starts to become hard for us to insist on the pawn sacrifice. }
11. Bxf5
{ It is hard to force Black to play dxc3 here, as after a waiting move like  11.h3  they can play  11...Be7  or even wait as well with  11...h6  or  11...a6  .  Instead, I propose to just take on f5 and go for the cxd4 structure. }
11... exf5 12. cxd4
{ Black is pretty solid in this structure and also this is a decent version for them. Still, I believe if we know what we are doing we can get something going. }
12... Na5
{ Nobody has played this move yet, but the engines rank it highly. We will likely trade a pair of knights and end up playing for a small plus. }
13. Nbd2 Be7 { An interesting move, though somewhat risky. } 14. bxa5 Qxb2 15.
Rb1 Qc3
{ The computer prefers this over  15...Qxa3  after which  16.Rxb7  Qxa5  17.Qa1  leads to a slightly better endgame for White. }
16. Rxb7 Qxa5
{ There is no refutation for Black has done, but we have a few options here. I saw this is the recommendation of Kamil Plichta in his Lifetime Repertoire on the French, so I will just give a few direction for self study, else he will just equalize all my recommendations in the end. }
17. Qb1
{ An alternative to look into is  17.e6!?  Bxe6  18.Qe2!?  when Black is not going to have an easy time to castle. }
17... Bc6 18. Rb2
{ Another good try is  18.Rxe7+!?  Kxe7  19.Qxf5  Bd7  20.Qg5+  Kf8  21.Nb3  , with good compensation for exchange, due to the weak king. }
18... Bd7
{ After  18...O-O  19.Qxf5  Qxa3  20.Rbb1  Rc7  21.e6!?  we keep some initiative, due to Black's somewhat uncoordinated pieces and our jumpy knights. }
19. Nb3 Qa4 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. dxc5 Rxc5 22. Rb8+ Bc8 23. Rc1 Qc6 24. Rxc5 Qxc5
25. Qb4
{ The endgame after  25...Qxb4  16.axb4  is slightly better for White despite us nominally being a pawn down. Black should instead seek for equality after  25...Qc1+!  26.Ne1  a5!  27.Qb5+  Ke7  28.Qxa5  Rd8  , but the game goes on  29.h3  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) French Advance: 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 Qb6 6.a3"]
[Black "French Advance 6.a3 Nh6 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6
{ The most popular system and the one I recommended in my Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. Black delays the development of other pieces and prioritizes the pressure on the d4-pawn. Another important function of the move 5...Qb6 is that it is eyeing the b2-pawn, making it difficult for White to develop the c1-bishop.   Releasing the tension in the center immediately with  5...cxd4  as is fairly common in amateur play is just a positional mistake as after  6.cxd4  we get the c3-square available for our knight. The same is true if this capture happens a move earlier. }
6. a3 Nh6
{ This is a major move that has been around for a long time and remains topical. A few years ago, the trend was to answer  7.b4  , but the more modern engines are much more into the  7.Bd3!?  cxd4  8.O-O  sacrifice and it has become more trendy lately. The trend is your friend, as they say, so let's go with it! }
7. Bd3 { Pawn sacs are all the rage nowadays. } 7... cxd4
{ After  7...Bd7  we can just  8.O-O  when Black should take on d4 anyway and transpose. }
8. O-O
{ In essence, if Black doesn't get seduced by the extra pawn, which he very well might, what we eventually will get is a Nf5 Bxf5 exf5 pawn structure, but likely a better version of the old line which was  8.cxd4  Bd7  9.Bc2  Nf5  10.Bxf5  exf5  . }
8... Bd7
{ The most flexible and the best move. The moves Bd7 Rc8 are Black's main priority, since it's important for him to control the squares along the c-file.   If instead Black plays  8...Be7  we can go  9.Bxh6!  gxh6  10.b4  ,  when Black no longer has Bg7. }
9. b4 { We grab space on the queenside. } 9... Rc8
{ The most useful move of all the waiting ones, not rushing with development of the kingside just yet, since  9...Nf5  allows  10.Bxf5  and @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p2n/3pP3/1P1p4/P1PB1N2/5PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq b3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be7  10.Bxh6  .   Besides waiting, the move  9...Rc8  also creates some clever concrete ideas. For example,  10.Re1  is now met with  10...dxc3  11.Nxc3  Ng4!  12.Ra2  Ncxe5!  or  12...Nxb4!  ,  when the knight on c3 hangs. }
10. Bb2
{ We threaten cxd4 and also reinforce our c3-square, so that after  10...dxc3  11.Nxc3  there are no Nxb4 related tricks. }
10... Nf5
{ This is a very decent idea at this point and it starts to become hard for us to insist on the pawn sacrifice. }
11. Bxf5
{ It is hard to force Black to play dxc3 here, as after a waiting move like  11.h3  they can play  11...Be7  or even wait as well with  11...h6  or  11...a6  .  Instead, I propose to just take on f5 and go for the cxd4 structure. }
11... exf5 12. cxd4
{ Black is pretty solid in this structure and also this is a decent version for them. Still, I believe if we know what we are doing we can get something going. }
12... Na5
{ Nobody has played this move yet, but the engines rank it highly. We will likely trade a pair of knights and end up playing for a small plus. }
13. Nbd2 Nc4 14. Nxc4 Rxc4 15. Nd2 { The knight embarks on a b3-c5 route. }
15... Rc7 16. Nb3 Be7 17. Nc5 O-O 18. Nxd7
{ We trade the knight, end up with a 'bad' bishop, but in fact we will control the only open file which is more relevant. }
18... Rxd7 19. Qd3 g6 20. Rfc1
{ He, who controls the c-file, controls the universe. It's a very small plus here, but we take it. }
*

