{ This is a very decent idea at this point and it starts to become hard for us to insist on the pawn sacrifice. }
11. Bxf5
{ It is hard to force Black to play dxc3 here, as after a waiting move like  11.h3  they can play  11...Be7  or even wait as well with  11...h6  or  11...a6  .  Instead, I propose to just take on f5 and go for the cxd4 structure. }
11... exf5 12. cxd4
{ Black is pretty solid in this structure, and also, this is a decent version for them. Still, I believe that if we know what we are doing, we can get something going. }
12... Be7 { The most natural. } 13. Nc3 Be6 14. Qd3
{ If your opponent looks very scary you can go  14.Na4  Qb5  15.Nc3  Qb6  once, just to make sure he is just one of those who want a draw, just like all the others. }
14... O-O 15. Na4 { It's possible to start with  15.Rfc1!?  as well. } 15...
Qd8 16. Nc5
{ Again, we can go for a less forcing continuation with  16.Rfc1!? } 16... b6
17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Bc3
{ The bishop stands much better on d2, from where it controls two important diagonals. }
18... Qd7 19. Rfc1
{ Our plans include Bd2 and then gaining space on both wings with g3-h4 and b5-a4. }
19... Rc7 { Logical, logical. } 20. Bd2 Rfc8 21. g3
{ All as promised. We gain space on both wings. } 21... Nd8 22. Rxc7 Rxc7 23.
a4
{ Black is solid, but we are in control, and thanks to the spatial advantage, we have the better chances here. }
