8. Rb1
{ We get ready for the b4/b3 break, but we have to be smart about when to pull that trigger. }
8... Bd7
{ This is aimed at  9.b4  , which can now be met with  9...cxb3  10.Nxb3  Ba4! }
9. h4
{ This appears to just be grabbing space on the kingside, but there is also a very concrete idea behind it. We prepare the move  9...--  10.b4  and after the sequence  10...cxb3  11.Nxb3  Ba4  12.Nfd2  Rc8  we can now play  13.Rh3  ,  protecting our c3-pawn. Quite an unexpected point!Black now has quite a few options. }
9... Qc7
{ If Black loses a tempo on preventing our b4 push, we can switch to the standard maneuvering setup. }
10. Be2 O-O-O 11. Nf1
{ Preparing a regrouping with Bf4 Ne3. Now that the queen has left b6, there are no annoyances like Bxa3 or Qb3 that we have to deal with. }
11... Ne7 12. Bf4 Kb8 13. h5 { It's never a bad idea to include h5-h6. } 13...
h6 14. Ne3 a6
{ Next we want to do a Qc2-Bd1-Qe2-Bc2 regroup, but first it is a good idea to drop the bishop back to g3, to have the option of a quick Nh4 f4, if Black leaves the defense of the f5-square and goes for Nc8. }
15. Bg3 Ka7
{ Black is not rushing  15...Nc8  since it can be met with the plan of  16.Nh4  followed by f4. }
16. Qc2
{ Our plan is Bd1 Qe2 Bc2 and then perhaps Nh4 f4, while if Black goes for Nb3 we can always trade it off with Nd2. }
*

