{ Already this is a hard move, as one might be tempted to go for the primitive  7.exf6  which in fact gives Black excellent play. Now after  7.O-O  the main move is  7...fxe5  , determining the pawn structure right away. }
7... Qc7 { Another popular setup, but it's not approved by the computers. } 8.
Bf4 { Grischuk played it very instructively in a recent online blitz game. }
8... Nge7 9. Re1
{ Provoking Ng6, since the immediate  9.Bg3  f5  leads to a slightly better version for Black. }
9... Ng6 10. Bg3 f5 11. h4
{ The knight on g6 will be sent back and White keeps control of the f4-g5 squares. On the queenside and the center, Black is busted, with c4 being one of the ideas. }
