{ Black can also start with  4...Qb6  or  4...Bd7  and only then follow up with  5.--  Nc6  , but this natural knight development is the most common move order.   4...Qb6  This move can be played with the intention to transpose back to 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 system, but in this move order we look at 4...Qb6 with the intention of going for the Bd7-Bb5 plan.  5.Nf3  Developing the knight is self explanatory.  5...Bd7  Intending to get rid of the bad bishop with Bb5.   As a kid @@StartBracket@@I used to be a French player myself!@@EndBracket@@ I was very attracted to this positional idea, but in this modern day and age, a maneuver this slow looks somewhat artificial. It is important to understand that while it solves the problem of the bad bishop, the issue of the lack of space remains. Taking all this time to trade the bishops takes away from the development of Black's kingside.   4...Ne7  A fancy looking idea, but it looks too good to be true. }
5. Nf3 Bd7
{ Releasing the tension in the center immediately with  5...cxd4  as is fairly common in amateur play is just a positional mistake as after  6.cxd4  we get the c3-square available for our knight. The same is true if this capture happens a move earlier. }
6. Be2 Rc8
{ It's possible for Black to take the waiting approach, make two waiting moves and see what White will do, because it's not easy for us to develop our b1-knight as long as Na3 is met with cxd4 cxd4 Bxa3. }
7. O-O a6
{ Against this particular waiting move, even  8.Na3!?  is interesting, since after taking on d4 and on a3 White gets some trumps in exchange for the doubled pawns and  @@StartFEN@@2rqkbnr/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQ1RK1 b k - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  would have been a far more useful move. But I still prefer to recommend the same approach against both  7...h6  and  7...a6  . }
8. Nbd2
{ The knight is doing a very decent job on b3. See also 7...h6, which is a similar line. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nge7 10. Nb3 Nf5 11. Bd2
{ Intending the same setup as against the 7...h6 system. Also very interesting is  11.Bg5!?  pointing out that 7...h6 is more useful than 7...a6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) French Advance: 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 Bd7 6.Be2"]
[Black "French Advance 6.Be2 Rc8 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Nc6
{ Black can also start with  4...Qb6  or  4...Bd7  and only then follow up with  5.--  Nc6  , but this natural knight development is the most common move order.   4...Qb6  This move can be played with the intention to transpose back to 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 system, but in this move order we look at 4...Qb6 with the intention of going for the Bd7-Bb5 plan.  5.Nf3  Developing the knight is self explanatory.  5...Bd7  Intending to get rid of the bad bishop with Bb5.   As a kid @@StartBracket@@I used to be a French player myself!@@EndBracket@@ I was very attracted to this positional idea, but in this modern day and age, a maneuver this slow looks somewhat artificial. It is important to understand that while it solves the problem of the bad bishop, the issue of the lack of space remains. Taking all this time to trade the bishops takes away from the development of Black's kingside.   4...Ne7  A fancy looking idea, but it looks too good to be true. }
5. Nf3 Bd7
{ Releasing the tension in the center immediately with  5...cxd4  as is fairly common in amateur play is just a positional mistake as after  6.cxd4  we get the c3-square available for our knight. The same is true if this capture happens a move earlier. }
6. Be2 Rc8
{ It's possible for Black to take the waiting approach, make two waiting moves and see what White will do, because it's not easy for us to develop our b1-knight as long as Na3 is met with cxd4 cxd4 Bxa3. }
7. O-O cxd4 { Black can go back to the Nge7 plan. } 8. cxd4 Nge7
{ Here we have a choice of Nc3 or Na3, but we generally go for the Na3 setup where possible. }
9. Na3 Nf5
{ This basically leads to similar positions as the immediate Nge7-Nf5, as the move Rc8 doesn't have a huge significance in the big picture. }
10. Nc2
{ And now for  10...Qb6  see the Qb6 setup and for  10...Be7  the Be7 setup, both within the 6...Nge7 system. }
