5. Nf3 Bd7
{ Releasing the tension in the center immediately with  5...cxd4  as is fairly common in amateur play is just a positional mistake as after  6.cxd4  we get the c3-square available for our knight. The same is true if this capture happens a move earlier. }
6. Be2 Nge7 7. Na3
{ There are two major directions here,  7.O-O  as well as  7.Na3  , both of which are played almost equally frequently - both in general but also at the highest level. In fact, I have played them both and after weighing all the pros and cons, I decided to recommend 7.Na3 for the course.  I think the main reason for 7.Na3 is that we pretty much determine the square for the b1-knight which makes our life easier, not having to decide on it and have doubts later.   It's also really pleasant to be able to play both @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nge7  7.Na3!  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nge7  6.Na3! }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 f6
{ This has only been played once at a high level, but it is a relatively recent game of Nepo. We have to take that seriously, because that guy may have some followers as he keeps winning the Candidates. }
9. Nb5
{ A fancy move, but we want to distract Black from the idea of going Bg7 @@StartBracket@@after exf6 gxf6 happens@@EndBracket@@ and frankly just transfer the knight to the freshly available c3-square with tempo. The natural  9.exf6  gxf6  10.Nc2  is also possible, when Black can consider playing  10...a5!?  not allowing the b4 advance. Those positions are also very interesting. }
9... Nf5 { This is a pawn sacrifice that I think we don't mind seeing. } 10.
exf6 a6
{ This is the point, since after  10...gxf6  the knight is not as well placed on f5 as it would be on g6. }
11. fxg7 { This is pretty much a forced sequence. } 11... Bxg7 12. g4
{ We don't go back. } 12... axb5 13. gxf5 O-O 14. Rg1
{ The rook is doing a good job on the open g-file and with the g-pawn gone from g2, we can forget about castling short. }
14... Kh8 15. fxe6 Bxe6 16. Be3
{ We are up a pawn and have a pretty stable position. The king is not in too bad a shape, as it can swing across to f1 after the preparatory Rg3. Black has some compensation but has to work for it by coming up with some creative ideas to get something going. Meanwhile the black king is also not too safe potentially. }
*

