7... cxd4 8. cxd4 f6
{ This has only been played once at a high level, but it is a relatively recent game of Nepo. We have to take that seriously, because that guy may have some followers as he keeps winning the Candidates. }
9. Nb5
{ A fancy move, but we want to distract Black from the idea of going Bg7 @@StartBracket@@after exf6 gxf6 happens@@EndBracket@@ and frankly just transfer the knight to the freshly available c3-square with tempo. The natural  9.exf6  gxf6  10.Nc2  is also possible, when Black can consider playing  10...a5!?  not allowing the b4 advance. Those positions are also very interesting. }
9... Ng6
{ This forces exf6 gxf6 and leads to a very murky structure, where it's unclear who has the initiative on the kingside. Black has an open g-file and potential for a center with e5, but at the same time, his own king does not have a perfect pawn shelter unlike ours, and the f6-e6 pawns are potentially somewhat soft as well. Black's center after a potential e5 push is also rather vulnerable. }
10. exf6 gxf6 11. O-O
{ Our king is pretty safe on the kingside, especially after we regroup and fianchetto our light-squared bishop. }
11... Kf7
{ Black goes for an artificial kind of castle - also because there is no real choice since  11...a6  12.Nc3  Bd6  can be met with  13.Bh6! }
12. Re1 { We proceed with out kingside regrouping. } 12... Rg8
{ Black also proceed with the plan. } 13. Bf1 Kg7 14. g3 Kh8
{ Some computers slightly prefer  14...Rc8!?  but our play is similar: we will proceed with the Nc3 Bh3 idea. }
15. Nc3
{ The computer likes to start with this move, keeping the options open for the f1-bishop, as Bh3 is a very tempting idea now as well. }
15... Bd6 16. Bh3 Re8 17. Bh6
{ Black's pieces are quite tied down. It's hard to see the e5 push happen anytime soon, and there is no prospects for any kingside play for Black at all. }
*

