7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5
{ By far the main setup that Black chooses. It can also arise via 7...Nf5 first. }
9. Nc2 Be7
{ The computer likes this more than  9...Qb6  and indeed, the idea of a quick f6 seems very decent here for Black. }
10. O-O O-O 11. Bd3
{ In my game against Wesley where I was in a must-not-lose situation, leading the match with 1 round to play, I went for the even more solid  11.Bd2  ,  transferring the bishop to c3 with a rock of a position. }
11... f6
{ After  11...Rc8  we can go for either Re1 and Bf4 or the Bd2-Bc3 idea, like in my game against So. }
12. Bf4
{ This move was played recently by Abdusattorov. Also possible is the simple  12.Bxf5  exf5  13.Re1  ,  where our domination of the dark squares in the center and Black's awkward pawn structure @@StartBracket@@the isolated d5-pawn and a weakened f5-pawn@@EndBracket@@ more than compensates the fact that we have given up the bishop pair. In fact, what is likely to happen @@StartBracket@@and something we strive for@@EndBracket@@ is that the dark-squared bishops get traded and we are left with a good knight vs bad light-squared bishop. }
12... fxe5
{ If Black takes the d4-pawn we have the standard trick to regain the pawn. }
13. Nxe5 Nfxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 { And now the thematic cheapo. } 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7
16. Qxd4
{ Like in the My System book by Nimzowitsch we gave up the d4 and e5-pawns, but we blockaded these squares with our pieces. }
