{ Black can also start with  4...Qb6  or  4...Bd7  and only then follow up with  5.--  Nc6  , but this natural knight development is the most common move order.   4...Qb6  This move can be played with the intention to transpose back to 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 system, but in this move order we look at 4...Qb6 with the intention of going for the Bd7-Bb5 plan.  5.Nf3  Developing the knight is self explanatory.  5...Bd7  Intending to get rid of the bad bishop with Bb5.   As a kid @@StartBracket@@I used to be a French player myself!@@EndBracket@@ I was very attracted to this positional idea, but in this modern day and age, a maneuver this slow looks somewhat artificial. It is important to understand that while it solves the problem of the bad bishop, the issue of the lack of space remains. Taking all this time to trade the bishops takes away from the development of Black's kingside.   4...Ne7  A fancy looking idea, but it looks too good to be true. }
5. Nf3 Bd7
{ Releasing the tension in the center immediately with  5...cxd4  as is fairly common in amateur play is just a positional mistake as after  6.cxd4  we get the c3-square available for our knight. The same is true if this capture happens a move earlier. }
6. Be2 Nge7 7. Na3
{ There are two major directions here,  7.O-O  as well as  7.Na3  , both of which are played almost equally frequently - both in general but also at the highest level. In fact, I have played them both and after weighing all the pros and cons, I decided to recommend 7.Na3 for the course.  I think the main reason for 7.Na3 is that we pretty much determine the square for the b1-knight which makes our life easier, not having to decide on it and have doubts later.   It's also really pleasant to be able to play both @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nge7  7.Na3!  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nge7  6.Na3! }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5
{ By far the main setup that Black chooses. It can also arise via 7...Nf5 first. }
9. Nc2 Qb6
{ The most common move, trying to put pressure on the d4-pawn, but we have it well guarded so there is nothing to worry about. }
10. O-O
{ Here Black tries various moves, but essentially we have a set of ideas that we are going to choose from. There is also a g4 move to keep in mind, but that usually only becomes a thing when Black has a bishop on e7 and doesn't have a Nfe7 response. We also have the idea of Bd3!?, and sometimes we can start with Kh1 as a useful waiting move, for both g4 as well as the Bd3 follow up, since in some lines after Black takes the d4-pawn, the king is out of check. }
10... Na5
{ This move followed by Bb5 is a logical idea. Now we shouldn't go with the most played move  11.g4?!  because after  11...Ne7!  we achieved nothing and h5 is coming. Instead, the engines point out a brilliant positional idea. }
11. Re1
{ This is so incredibly sophisticated and subtle, you just got to love it. }
11... Bb5 { Black trades the bishop, unsuspecting. } 12. Bxb5+ Qxb5 13. Ne3
{ This is quite a brilliant idea, to then take with the rook and prepare to swing the rook accross. Remarkably it has been played twice already by GM Semen Dvoirys, the first time in 2008, long before the engines reached the level of today, where this is just their first line now. }
13... Nxe3 14. Rxe3
{ We are going to start a huge initiative on the kingside with Ne1 Rg3 or the even more cunning h4-h5, Nh2, Rg3. }
*

