{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... a6
{ This position occures a lot via the O'Kelly Sicilian @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  and now  3.c3  e6  4.d4  d5  5.e5  @@EndBracket@@. We look at this move in connection with Nc6 Bd7 in the Nc6 Bd7 chapter, but here we can look at the Bd7-Bb5 plan. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Be2
{ Here after  6...Bd7  7.O-O  Rc8  we transpose and in essence not much changes for us with the move a6, if Black goes Nge7 we go Na3, etc. See the Nc6 Bd7 chapter for this type of positions. }
6... Bd7 7. O-O { Now 7... Rc8  transposes to a line in the Nc6 Bd7 chapter. }
