[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) French Advance: Black's Sidelines"]
[Black "French Advance 4...Qb6/5...Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French firmly belongs to the category of main openings that Black can play against 1.e4, though its soundness is still somewhat debated amongst theoreticians. Black accepts having less space from the start, often a 'bad' bishop on c8, and aims at a counter-attacking strategy, hoping to destabilize White's center control in the long run.Fun fact: my very first course for Chessable was a Lifetime Repertoire on the French Defense! }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advanced French has experienced something of a renaissance in the last few years. While previously it was only played by the specialists and its narrow group of devotees, modern theoreticians and top players have uncovered the hidden potential of this very natural concept.White right away clarifies the pawn structure in the center, grabbing space and locking up the c8-bishop. Black, in turn, will try to develop quickly and put pressure on White's expanded pawn center, hoping for counterplay. }
3... c5
{ This really has to be played. Black has to start challenging White's central block d4-e5, and there is not a single downside in doing so. }
4. c3
{ Reinforcing the pawn chain. Now Black is at the first crossroads. Besides some minor lines, there are three major systems:  Nc6 Qb6 applying maximum pressure on the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@also the system I recommend in my Lifetime Repertoires French Defense!@@EndBracket@@;  Nc6 Bd7 going for quick development;  Qb6 Bd7 intending to solve the problem of the bad light-squared bishop with Bb5. }
4... Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 Bb5
{ Offering the trade right away is the most popular way to play, naturally. It does allow some dxc5!? ideas. }
7. Bxb5+
{ This is a simple line, not entering the complications after  7.dxc5!?  Bxc5  8.b4  Bxf2+  9.Kf1  .  The resulting position is crazy and even though the computer likes White, if you dig deeper, it seems to be far from easy. }
7... Qxb5 8. Na3 Qa6
{ Keeping White away from castling, but in the end we will gain some time on the queen. In case of a simple  8...Qd7  we can play  9.Nc2  followed by O-O with a familiar type of position, where we might go for h4-h5 and some slow kingside build up in the long term. We also get such positions in our Caro-Kann repertoire. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b4 { Kicking the bishop back. } 10... Be7 11. Nd4
{ Intending Nab5, which not only lets us castle but also starts initiative of our own. }
11... Nd7 12. Nab5 Qb6 { Returning to d8 is the best Black has. } 13. Be3
{ Natural. } 13... Qd8
{ Here we should play energetic chess to make use of our lead in development. }
14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh3 { Eyeing the e6-pawn. A sac is coming. } 15... Nxe5 16. Bf4
{ The more things we tie down, the more likely something will get overloaded. }
16... Bf6 17. O-O { The calm before the storm. } 17... a6
{ Black can't stop the inevitable anyway. } 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Nd4
{ We keep e6 alive for now. } 19... Ne7 20. Rae1
{ A correspondence game from 2017 continued  20.Qxe6  , but Black held in the end. We can deviate here and get an advantage. }
20... Qd6 { Black's only option is to give back the piece. } 21. Qg3
{ We win back the piece and end up in a heavy piece middlegame with a safer king. }
21... N7c6 22. Nxc6 Qxc6 23. Bxe5 O-O 24. h4
{ Black king is weaker and that matters. White is much better, as h5 is very annoying to face. }
