[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Overview"]
[Black "Caro-Kann vs. overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5
{ The main-line and also the most natural and conceptual response. Black wants to get the bishop outside the pawn chain, then lock it with e6 and develop the rest of his pieces. That is all perfect. The only issue is that he lacks space and it will take a while to develop the kingside pieces.   3...c5  This looks like an Advanced French @@StartBracket@@1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.e5 c5@@EndBracket@@ a full tempo down, but in fact with the c8-bishop being open there are definite advantages to Black not having played e7-e6 yet. This system is quite trendy across various levels, especially in the quicker time controls, and while its soundness remains somewhat questionable, if Black knows what he is doing he is often able to come out of the opening with an acceptable position.For this course, however, I have discovered an unknown system that will pretty much transpose into similar @@StartBracket@@often the same!@@EndBracket@@ positions to the ones in the mainline of 3... Bf5:  4.c3!?  We go for the familiar type of positions, the same pawn structure as in the 3...Bf5 Caro-Kann and the Advanced French as well. An important nuance here, though, is that after  4...Nc6  we should prevent Black from getting the bishop in one go to g4 after  5.Nf3?!  Bg4!  and start with the cunning @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Be2!  , intending after Black goes  5...Bf5  to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  4.Nf3  e6  5.Be2  c5  6.O-O  Nc6  7.c3  setups. }
4. Nf3
{ White has a lot of tempting options on move 4, including  4.Nc3  ,  4.h4  ,  4.c4  , even  4.g4!?  ,  but finally I have settled on the most simple and sound recommendation. First of all, I have some interesting fresh ideas in this line that I want to share, but mainly I feel that this fits in well with the general concept of my repertoire series. Before starting an offensive, let's first cover our basis in the center.Our next moves are also quite obvious: we just want to finish kingside development and castle and see what happens next, when it happens. }
4... e6
{ Black can't do without this move sooner or later, reinforcing the center and opening the f8-bishop. }
5. Be2
{ It is also possible to start with  5.c3  , which is mainly a less flexible move order for White, but it does give White some other options after  5...c5  besides developing the bishop to e2, such as  6.Be3  or  6.Bb5+  .  I do encourage the students of this course to investigate 5.c3 on their own, if they feel the need to expand the repertoire a little bit, at some point in the future, while staying within the familiar pawn structure and strategic ideas.   After  5.Be2  Black has a lot of possible setups and an incredible amount of move orders possible, so instead I would like to outline a few strategic ideas that we have to take into account.  In terms of pawn breaks Black has two: c5 and f6. Both can be played quickly or prepared instead, with c5 being far less risky and the more sound one, not impacting Black's king safety nor weakening the e6-pawn. Note that Black needs these pawn breaks in order to counter White's space advantage.  If Black plays c5 quickly, the risk he is facing is that the position will open up with him not having developed his kingside yet.  If Black tries to prepare c5 by developing his kingside first, he is facing a potential issue that White will be fully mobilized to face it, or be able to stop it altogether @@StartBracket@@with c3-b4 for example@@EndBracket@@.  Due to the lack of space it takes Black more time than desired to develop both the g8-knight as well as the f8-bishop.As a consequence of the elements mentioned above, Black has an issue balancing the c5 break @@StartBracket@@solving the space issue@@EndBracket@@ with developing his kingside pieces. As a result his path to equality is very narrow.In terms of what Black can do next, I decided to arbitrarily split the systems into three different sub-chapters, though it is possible to categorize things a little differently.  Chapter 6: the 3...c5 line, which in many cases will transpose to 3... Bf5 with 5... c5.  Sub-chapter 7: systems with a quick c5. In our case this is only 5...c5 since we meet 5...Ne7 with 6. c3, preventing the 6... c5 push.  Sub-chapter 8: Systems with Ne7 and standard development, which usually includes Nd7, h6/Bg6 in some order. The e7-knight can later either move to g6, c8 or f5 or it can also stay on e7 and the f8-bishop may develop via g7 after the h6-g5 push. Move orders can vary a lot, but as long as the knight appears on e7, I will put it under the 5...Ne7 move order.  Sub-chapter 9: Systems with unusual development without Ne7 e.g. 5... Nd7, 5...Bb4+, various Nh6 setups, early a5-a4, Be7-Bd8, Be7 h5-g5, early f6 plans and what not. }
*

