[White "6) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...c5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3...c5 with 5...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ This is pretty automatic. Next Black is hoping to develop his c8-bishop. } 5.
Be2
{ This is a very clever move order, not allowing Black  5.Nf3  Bg4!  in one go. The bishop on f5 is slightly less well placed than on g4 and that little detail is the difference between Black equalizing comfortably and White being able to put some pressure in the opening.   After  5.Be2  ,  5...Bf5  is the most played move. An alternative would be  5...cxd4!?  first, avoiding the  5...Bf5  6.Nf3  cxd4  7.Nxd4!?  option, and there is also the computer suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6!?  , trying to keep the flexibility and get that Bg4 move in one go after all in case of  6.Nf3  . }
5... a6
{ This is very clever and I wouldn't expect to face it a lot, but the engines do rank this move quite highly. Black is waiting for  6.Nf3  to go  6...Bg4  .  We can allow that, since the extra tempo of a6 is barely useful, or we can try to be principled too and play the waiting game with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p2pppp/p1n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3!?  . }
6. Nf3
{ We can also very much play  6.a3!?  ,  but it's a question how useful move that is. After Black completes their development with Bf5 and e6, there may at some point come a moment where Black will push c4, closing the position. Then the b3 pawn break is less good than if our pawn is on a2, because after cxb3 we will have to recapture with a piece, leaving ourselves with somewhat weak light squares on the queenside. }
6... Bg4 7. Nbd2 e6 8. O-O
{ The remarkable thing about this position is that it is covered in the 3...Bf5 with 5...c5 Chapter, but with a difference being that Black doesn't have the move a6 included. What is actually funny is that the engines nonetheless suggest to go for  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  a5  ,  which transposes to that chapter.If you don't like giving Black this extra a6 tempo for some reason, I would look into the 6.a3!? option after all. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4
{ Now after  9...a5  we transpose to a line in the 3...Bf5 chapter. } 9... Nge7
{ Just trying to finish development like a lazy Caro-Kann player is not going to get Black to equalize the game. }
10. h3 Bh5 11. Nb3 Nc8
{ This is what they like to do sometimes, those odd Caro-Kann people. } 12. Be3
Be7 13. Rc1 O-O 14. Nc5
{ There is not much use to having the pawn on a6 after all. Black does not have enough counterplay here and we have nice pressure on the queenside and the usual long-term potential on the kingside as well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...c5"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 3...c5 with 5...a6 (Alternative 6.a3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ This is pretty automatic. Next Black is hoping to develop his c8-bishop. } 5.
Be2
{ This is a very clever move order, not allowing Black  5.Nf3  Bg4!  in one go. The bishop on f5 is slightly less well placed than on g4 and that little detail is the difference between Black equalizing comfortably and White being able to put some pressure in the opening.   After  5.Be2  ,  5...Bf5  is the most played move. An alternative would be  5...cxd4!?  first, avoiding the  5...Bf5  6.Nf3  cxd4  7.Nxd4!?  option, and there is also the computer suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6!?  , trying to keep the flexibility and get that Bg4 move in one go after all in case of  6.Nf3  . }
5... a6
{ This is very clever and I wouldn't expect to face it a lot, but the engines do rank this move quite highly. Black is waiting for  6.Nf3  to go  6...Bg4  .  We can allow that, since the extra tempo of a6 is barely useful, or we can try to be principled too and play the waiting game with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1p2pppp/p1n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a3!?  . }
6. a3 { I will give a sample line with this waiting move. } 6... Bf5 7. Be3
{ Developing the queenside first is interesting, keeping the option to play g4 open. }
7... e6 8. Nd2 cxd4
{ Going for the more standard Nge7 is less attractive. If Black does so without this capture, he would have to deal with  8...Nge7  9.dxc5!  Nxe5  10.Ngf3  ,  when the c5-pawn and our entire queenside pawn mass is quite annoying once we support it with b4. }
9. cxd4 Nge7 10. Rc1 Nc8
{ This is a bad move, but a good demonstration on why it was clever for White to postpone Ngf3. }
11. g4 Bg6 12. Nh3
{ And suddenly Black is facing some serious issues on the kingside, with Nf4 and h4 coming. }
