3... c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ This is pretty automatic. Next Black is hoping to develop his c8-bishop. } 5.
Be2
{ This is a very clever move order, not allowing Black  5.Nf3  Bg4!  in one go. The bishop on f5 is slightly less well placed than on g4 and that little detail is the difference between Black equalizing comfortably and White being able to put some pressure in the opening.   After  5.Be2  ,  5...Bf5  is the most played move. An alternative would be  5...cxd4!?  first, avoiding the  5...Bf5  6.Nf3  cxd4  7.Nxd4!?  option, and there is also the computer suggestion of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP2BPPP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6!?  , trying to keep the flexibility and get that Bg4 move in one go after all in case of  6.Nf3  . }
5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Qb6
{ This move has been played quite a few times. Black is hoping for  7.Nf3  Bg4!  but misses our strong reply. }
7. Nc3
{ We don't defend, we attack. Now  7...e6?  would lead to a terrible French after  8.Nf3  , so Black has to trade the central pawns. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nxd5 Qxd1+ 9. Bxd1
{ Black faces a very annoying issue of Nc7+ and that is a serious problem. }
9... Rb8 { Black has to waste time instead of developing. } 10. Nf3
{ We can just develop.  10.e6!?  ,  by the way, is an interesting alternative, trying to spice things up. }
10... e6 11. Nc7+ { Dislodging the black king as well. } 11... Kd8 12. Nb5
{ We want to continue developing, while Black has a much harder task doing that. The pawn structure is fine for Black @@StartBracket@@in fact in some endgames our e5-pawn could be a weakness@@EndBracket@@, but with so many pieces on the board and Black lacking development and coordination, we can use that extra space to our advantage. }
