{ Black has to play this pretty much anyway.  6...Ne7  with the idea Nec6 loses the pawn to  7.dxc5  and b4 next. }
7. O-O
{ This is a major tabiya and although  7...cxd4  is by far the most played move, Black has a ton of reasonable alternatives with which he can try to be clever. Let's uncover them one by one. }
7... Bg6
{ This is a big system at the high level and you may encounter it as well. Black is securing his bishop somewhat before settling on cxd4. }
8. Be3
{ I propose to go for a very creative new idea that I have come up with together with my computers. The main-move  8.a3  is very reasonable, but the closed position that occured in the game Yu-Keymer is rather hard to understand.  8.a3  Be7!?  9.b4  c4!  10.a4  h5  and the players moved around a little bit before agreeing to a draw. Perhaps White does have a way to try and push for f4-f5 eventually, but it is easier said than done. Black will close the queenside, move the king over to that side, etc. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ A rare idea that I would like to propose. It has been played by Fedoseev recently against Keymer, but he either improvised, or forgot what the point was, because after the principled  9...Nxe5  he went astray right away. }
9... Nge7
{ If Black doesn't take up the challenge, his life will not be easy either. }
10. Nd2
{ It is possible to go for f4 ideas, but I like the queenside plan with a deep brilliant point in the end. }
10... Nxd4
{ Taking the pawn on e5 is just bad now:  10...Nxe5  11.Qb3!  followed by c4 will open the position before Black gets to finish his kingside development. }
11. cxd4 Nc6
{ Black wants to complete his development. Going for f4-g4 here is not as efficient, since we have lost some time on Be3 Nd2 moves.   It is possible to include  12.h4!?  , which is a funky pawn sac, but I just really like the idea of the queenside bind that the computer suggests as well. }
12. a3 { The simple plan of a3-b4 Nb3, Rc1, Nc5 is pretty good. } 12... Be7
{ Preventing b4 with  12...a5  looks ugly, as it weakens the b5-square. } 13.
b4 O-O 14. Nb3 { We proceed with our plan. } 14... Rc8
{ Both sides will bring the rook to the open file. } 15. Rc1 a5
{ Black is trying to fix the queenside pawn structure in a way that will restrict our knight on b3, but there is a little detail that our opponent might not be aware of here. }
16. b5 Na7 17. Nc5
{ This is very surprising. Won't the knight get kicked with b6? } 17... b6 18.
a4
{ This is a brilliant idea and would be absolutely shocking, but I actually have seen a very similar idea before, in the game Van Foreest-Grandelius in the final round of Wijk aan Zee 2021. The passed pawns are worth more than the knight. It's somewhat shocking! }
18... bxc5
{ Black should trust us instead and just stay passive, hoping to hold on, despite not having any active play. }
19. dxc5
{ The passed pawns are going to march quickly or slowly, depending on how Black wants to treat this. Our threat is c6, but if Black defends against it with a move like  19...Qd7  , we can renew the threat with  20.Qd2!  There is no big rush. }
