{ Accepting the sacrifice is the best bet and is also what Keymer played against Fedoseev in the prestigious Titled Tuesday. }
10. Qa4+ { We will start action in the center quickly! } 10... Nd7
{ The only move. } 11. c4
{ We have to open up the position before Black can finish his kingside development. }
11... e5
{ We are totally going to sacrifice the knight here. The only question is whether to play  12.cxd5  or  12.Nc3!? }
12. Nc3
{ The fancier and the stronger one of the two possible knight sacrifices. }
12... exd4 { Is no bueno. } 13. Bxd4 Nf6
{ We have a lot of ways to eventually regain the piece. The most direct is to just take on f6 and continue with Nxd5. }
14. Bxf6 { The most direct of the many good options. } 14... gxf6
{ Trying not to lose more tempi as  14...Qxf6  15.Nxd5!  is clear a disaster. In that line the knight on d7 is not going to make it, being under the pin and all kinds of potential X-rays. }
15. Nxd5 { Black can't survive this. } 15... Bd6
{ If  15...Be7  then  16.Bg4!  wins, followed by Rfe1 after f5. } 16. c5 Bxc5
17. Bb5
{ Black is going to lose the d7-knight and get an awful position with no material compensation. }
