{ Black has to play this pretty much anyway.  6...Ne7  with the idea Nec6 loses the pawn to  7.dxc5  and b4 next. }
7. O-O
{ This is a major tabiya and although  7...cxd4  is by far the most played move, Black has a ton of reasonable alternatives with which he can try to be clever. Let's uncover them one by one. }
7... Bg4
{ This is a thematic response. Black doesn't mind to get rid of this bishop and focus on targetting our d4-pawn. }
8. Nbd2
{ Preparing for Bxf3 but we are also ready to send a knight to b3 in some cases, from where it will defend d4 and head towards c5. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4
{ White also gets a pleasant position after  9.Nxd4!?  , trading everything and then just playing that position. }
9... a5
{ This is a very difficult move to make, but the engine finds it important to prevent the Nb3 idea. It's also never been played before.   Black could also have started with  9...Bh5  and then we would probably have nothing better than  10.h3  anyway. }
10. h3 Bh5 11. Nb1
{ I like this switch back. Our knight will now head to c3, to point at the newly created weakness on b5.   Alternatively, we also have options of  11.Bb5!?  and  11.Qa4!?  to investigate. }
11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nge7 { Now we have to defend the d4-pawn. } 13. Bg4
{ Stopping Nf5. Now if Black tries to chase us away with  13...g6  we have a nice idea in mind-  14.Nc3  h5  15.Be2!  and we are in time for  15...Nf5  16.Nb5!  Qb6  and now having gained time for Be2 we can defend the pawn with  17.Be3  or play the even stronger  17.Bd3!   There is also the direct  13...h5!?  , which we can take  14.Bxh5  Nf5  15.Be3  and then Black has to find a long sequence to eventually justify this sacrifice. }
13... Qb6 { Here we sac the b2-pawn. The pawn on d4 is much more important! }
14. Be3 Qxb2 15. Qd3
{ The queen gets trapped if Black takes the rook and otherwise Nc3 and Rab1 is coming. Black does get two rooks for the queen after  15...Qxa1  16.Nc3  Qxf1+  17.Kxf1  , but then the position favors our much more active pieces. }
15... Nf5 { The most sensible try. } 16. Nc3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bb4
{ Black gets to finish development and will even make it to an endgame, but we still get a pleasant position. }
18. Nb5 O-O 19. a3
{ Forcing Black to find  19...Qd2!  and trade into an endgame that's slightly better for White. }
19... Qd2 20. Qxd2 Bxd2 21. Kf2 a4 22. Rab1
{ We are a pawn down for now, but with Ke2, Nd6 and Rfc1 incoming, it is Black who has to figure out how to give back the pawn and try to make a draw. White is certainly for choice here. }
*

