{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5
{ The main-line and also the most natural and conceptual response. Black wants to get the bishop outside the pawn chain, then lock it with e6 and develop the rest of his pieces. That is all perfect. The only issue is that he lacks space and it will take a while to develop the kingside pieces. }
4. Nf3
{ White has a lot of tempting options on move 4, including  4.Nc3  ,  4.h4  ,  4.c4  , even  4.g4!?  ,  but finally I have settled on the most simple and sound recommendation. First of all, I have some interesting fresh ideas in this line that I want to share, but mainly I feel that this fits in well with the general concept of my repertoire series. Before starting an offensive, let's first cover our basis in the center.Our next moves are also quite obvious: we just want to finish kingside development and castle and see what happens next, when it happens. }
4... e6
{ Black can't do without this move sooner or later, reinforcing the center and opening the f8-bishop. }
5. Be2
{ It is also possible to start with  5.c3  , which is mainly a less flexible move order for White, but it does give White some other options after  5...c5  besides developing the bishop to e2, such as  6.Be3  or  6.Bb5+  .  I do encourage the students of this course to investigate 5.c3 on their own, if they feel the need to expand the repertoire a little bit, at some point in the future, while staying within the familiar pawn structure and strategic ideas. }
5... c5
{ This is certainly the toughest nut to crack and the most principled line one can play against the Advance variation. The fact that GM Erwin l'Ami chose this as the main weapon for his LTR Caro-Kann says enough! After meticulous research, though, I have come up with an excellent weapon for White - one that fits our repertoire conceptually, but is also challenging enough theoretically! }
6. c3
{ The main-line is  6.Be3  ,  when Black has to memorize a ton of long variations to defend a slightly worse endgame in the end. It is certainly possible to go down that route with White, hoping that Black forgets something on the way, or fails to hold the final position after his analysis ends, but I think it's more interesting to take them to a less explored territory, where we have a much better chance of surprising them and where the new ideas are analysed far less deeply. Luckily, I was able to find plenty of new ideas in this c3 O-O setup and it also fits in with our repertoire in general, as we end up with the same pawn structure in both the Advanced Caro, as well as the Advanced French.   It is by the way clever to start with  6.c3  , as it avoids the  6.O-O  Ne7!?  line that Black can switch to. Likewise, against @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  we will go for the  6.c3  move order as well. }
6... Nc6
{ Black has to play this pretty much anyway.  6...Ne7  with the idea Nec6 loses the pawn to  7.dxc5  and b4 next. }
7. O-O
{ This is a major tabiya and although  7...cxd4  is by far the most played move, Black has a ton of reasonable alternatives with which he can try to be clever. Let's uncover them one by one. }
7... Bg4
{ This is a thematic response. Black doesn't mind to get rid of this bishop and focus on targetting our d4-pawn. }
8. Nbd2
{ Preparing for Bxf3 but we are also ready to send a knight to b3 in some cases, from where it will defend d4 and head towards c5. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4
{ White also gets a pleasant position after  9.Nxd4!?  , trading everything and then just playing that position. }
9... Nge7 { This is very natural, but in fact not that accurate. } 10. h3 Bh5
11. Nb3
{ The knight is well placed here, as we can see in some similar lines in this chapter. It is potentially heading to c5. }
11... Nc8 12. Be3 Be7 13. Rc1 O-O 14. Nc5
{ And White had some nasty pressure on the queenside thanks to the excellent knight on c5 in Adams-L'Ami 2009. }
*

