{ The point of our play. Once we get Rb1, we will be able to exploit Black's lack of development. }
11... Bd3
{ Black's bishop decides that if it goes down, it will take our bishop down with it as well. }
12. Bxd3 cxd3
{ Here White has a few exciting options. There is  13.f4!?  ,  13.c4!?  and  13.Nhf3  heading towards the d3-pawn. It's a fun position to investigate, but I will give the simplest option. }
13. Nhf3
{ We just want to pick up the d3-pawn with Ne1-Nxd3. Black has a lot of options, but none of them seem to be offering easy solutions. Let's look at the sequence that I personally consider the most likely to occur. }
13... Nge7
{ Who wouldn't try to finish the kingside development? Instead,  13...Ba3  can lead to complications after  14.Rb1  , but we can also just play  14.Nb1!?  forcing the bishop to go back. }
