{ There are some other very clever moves for White as well, but frankly castling has to be the best. Note that the direct  7.h4  h5  8.Ng5  doesn't lead to a clear position, since after  8...f6!  9.exf6  gxf6  10.Nh3  Black can just sacrifice the h5-pawn and go for a Qe7 Nd7 O-O-O setup with plenty of compensation thanks to the upcoming e5 break.After castling, the threat now is Ne1 hunting down the bishop on f5. }
7... Nd7
{ The most common move, but a very unfortunate one. This position can also arise after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3  Nd7  7.O-O  Ng6?! }
8. Ne1 { This is the key idea in this line. The bishop on f5 has no air. } 8...
f6 { This comes too late, as White can now support the e5 pawn with f4. } 9. f4
Qb6
{ Black is trying, but it is not hard to defend from the threat of fxe5 and Nxe5. }
10. a4 { A clever inclusion, even stronger than the direct 10. Kh1. } 10... a5
{ Black stops our a5, but now whenever c5 comes, we get the b5-square. } 11.
Kh1
{ Thanks to the inclusion of a4-a5, Black now can't even go for  11...c5  because  12.Bb5!  would be too painful. Black lacks counterplay and eventually the knight on g6 will have to go back, to free space for the f5-bishop. This means Black's whole plan has pretty much failed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 with 5...Ne7"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 5...Ne7 with 6...Ng6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7
{ The third most played move after  5...Nd7  and  5...c5  , but  5...Nd7  will in many cases transpose to 5...Ne7 as well. Generally there are many transpositions as Black, for example, can play Ne7, Nd7 and h6 in any of the orders.   Essentially, in this  5...Ne7  chapter, I would like to look at all the critical variations that can arise when the knight gets developed to e7 @@StartBracket@@before the f8-bishop comes out onto the f8-a3 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. Lines where Black plays without the early Ne7, such as for example the rare Nd7 Be7 setup, will be looked at in the next chapter which covers all the sidelines.I hope that makes sense! }
6. c3
{ With the move orders @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3!?  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.c3!?  , we essentially avoid a large system - @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.O-O  c5  .  This system is not such a problem for White, but it just saves us extra work, since we can place the pawn on c3 against pretty much all of the setups with Ne7. }
6... Ng6
{ This was played against me by Motylev in the World Cup 2015 and since then has been picked up by many players at the higher level. Also club players and amateurs may find the plan with Ne7-Ng6 attractive. The bishop on f5 doesn't have that much room to breathe here, but Black will most likely go for the quick f6 break to make sense of his setup as soon as possible. }
7. O-O
{ There are some other very clever moves for White as well, but frankly castling has to be the best. Note that the direct  7.h4  h5  8.Ng5  doesn't lead to a clear position, since after  8...f6!  9.exf6  gxf6  10.Nh3  Black can just sacrifice the h5-pawn and go for a Qe7 Nd7 O-O-O setup with plenty of compensation thanks to the upcoming e5 break.After castling, the threat now is Ne1 hunting down the bishop on f5. }
7... c5 { This is not good. } 8. Be3 Qb6
{ This is bad for multiple reasons, but I really like the rough punishment here. }
9. g4 { The start to a beautiful sequence. } 9... Bxg4 10. Qa4+
{ We can already see how it will go wrong for Black. } 10... Nc6 11. dxc5
{ The queen on a4 says hi to the bishop on g4. } 11... Qxb2
{ Black has to go for the poisoned pawn. } 12. Nbd2
{ Also  12.Bb5  is going to get the job done, but I like this idea as well. After  12.Nbd2  there are two threats, Qxg4 and Rab1-xb7. Even after  12...Bf5  we go  13.Rab1!  Bxb1  14.Rxb1  Qxc3  and  15.Rxb7  collecting more material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 with 5...Ne7"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 5...Ne7 with 6...Ng6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7
{ The third most played move after  5...Nd7  and  5...c5  , but  5...Nd7  will in many cases transpose to 5...Ne7 as well. Generally there are many transpositions as Black, for example, can play Ne7, Nd7 and h6 in any of the orders.   Essentially, in this  5...Ne7  chapter, I would like to look at all the critical variations that can arise when the knight gets developed to e7 @@StartBracket@@before the f8-bishop comes out onto the f8-a3 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. Lines where Black plays without the early Ne7, such as for example the rare Nd7 Be7 setup, will be looked at in the next chapter which covers all the sidelines.I hope that makes sense! }
6. c3
{ With the move orders @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3!?  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.c3!?  , we essentially avoid a large system - @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.O-O  c5  .  This system is not such a problem for White, but it just saves us extra work, since we can place the pawn on c3 against pretty much all of the setups with Ne7. }
6... Ng6
{ This was played against me by Motylev in the World Cup 2015 and since then has been picked up by many players at the higher level. Also club players and amateurs may find the plan with Ne7-Ng6 attractive. The bishop on f5 doesn't have that much room to breathe here, but Black will most likely go for the quick f6 break to make sense of his setup as soon as possible. }
7. O-O
{ There are some other very clever moves for White as well, but frankly castling has to be the best. Note that the direct  7.h4  h5  8.Ng5  doesn't lead to a clear position, since after  8...f6!  9.exf6  gxf6  10.Nh3  Black can just sacrifice the h5-pawn and go for a Qe7 Nd7 O-O-O setup with plenty of compensation thanks to the upcoming e5 break.After castling, the threat now is Ne1 hunting down the bishop on f5. }
7... f6
{ This was Motylev's novelty at the time. Black prevents Ne1 and attempts to free himself by force, but it will not be easy to get rid of the weak e6-pawn and White has a few ways to keep fighting for the opening advantage. }
8. exf6
{ The most natural move and although there are alternatives, this is probably still the most promising way to go. }
8... Qxf6
{ Now the question is whether to include  9.Qb3  b6  or not. Of course b6 would weaken Black's queenside pawn structure somewhat, but b3 is also not always a useful position for our queen. }
9. Qb3
{ This is the move I played over the board too. I find it tempting to soften Black's queenside.   It is definitely possible to dig into  9.Bg5  as well.  9.Bg5  Qf7  10.Nh4!?  Nxh4  11.Bxh4  being the critical direction there, with fight revolving around the dark squares and the e6-e5 break. }
9... b6 { Black has to make this concession. } 10. Bg5
{ It is also possible to start with  10.c4  Bd6  and play  11.Bg5  after that. }
10... Qf7 11. c4
{ We create some tension in the center and try to get close to Black's weaknesses. }
11... Bd6
{ This is a critical moment. White has the option to play it more positionally and long-term with a Nbd2, Bh4-Bg3 setup in some order, or he can go for the direct attempt. I believe the direct approach puts more pressure and demands more knowledge from Black, so I propose to go with that. }
12. cxd5 { This is very concrete. Black now has no room for a mistake. } 12...
exd5
{ Black can't take with the other pawn in view of the check along the a4-e8 diagonal:  12...cxd5?  13.Qa4+  forces a king move, as  13...Nd7?  runs into  14.Qc6  . }
13. Qe3+ { A very concrete idea. } 13... Qe6
{ This leads to a slightly worse endgame for Black, something we will happily take. }
14. Qxe6+ Bxe6 15. Re1 { Rooks belong on open files. } 15... O-O 16. Bd3
{ Improving both the bishop and the rook. } 16... Re8
{ Black defends the e6-bishop. Now White has a few different ways of playing. }
17. Be3
{ There are alternatives: the natural  17.Nbd2  and the engine also likes  17.g3  followed by Kg2, to postpone the decision on the b1-knight. The text move appeals to me because we attempt to gain the bishop pair, which is something tangible to hold on to in the endgame. }
17... Nd7
{ Finishing the development is only natural, but now we gain the bishop pair. }
18. Ng5 { We gladly collect the bishop pair. } 18... Ndf8 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 20. Nd2
{ We've got a beautiful unopposed light-squared bishop. Black's problem is that whenever the weak c6-pawn gets pushed, the d5-pawn becomes weak instead. }
