{ Objectively better than  13...Qe6  , though here Black must really know what he is doing. }
14. Nh4 { A very concrete way of putting pressure on Black. } 14... Nxh4
{ This simplifies into a pleasant position for White. } 15. Bxh4 O-O 16. Bg3
Bxg3 17. hxg3
{ Long term, positionally speaking, I prefer this capture, since after  17.fxg3  I am always wondering: what about the very long-term prospect of an endgame where our doubled pawns are of a lesser value? But those who trust their dynamic instincts can certainly go for the time factor and take with the f2-pawn. In those fxg3 positions White has a safer king, since we can push g4-g5 at some point without weakening ours, but again, we have to be careful not to trade the wrong pieces. }
17... Nd7 18. Nd2 Rae8 19. Qc3 Nf6 20. Bf3 Bd7 21. Rae1
{ We have a little pull here, with ideas like Re5 and b4. Black's dark squares are still somewhat weak. }
