[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 with 5...Ne7"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 5...Ne7 with 6...Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7
{ The third most played move after  5...Nd7  and  5...c5  , but  5...Nd7  will in many cases transpose to 5...Ne7 as well. Generally there are many transpositions as Black, for example, can play Ne7, Nd7 and h6 in any of the orders.   Essentially, in this  5...Ne7  chapter, I would like to look at all the critical variations that can arise when the knight gets developed to e7 @@StartBracket@@before the f8-bishop comes out onto the f8-a3 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. Lines where Black plays without the early Ne7, such as for example the rare Nd7 Be7 setup, will be looked at in the next chapter which covers all the sidelines.I hope that makes sense! }
6. c3
{ With the move orders @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3!?  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.c3!?  , we essentially avoid a large system - @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.O-O  c5  .  This system is not such a problem for White, but it just saves us extra work, since we can place the pawn on c3 against pretty much all of the setups with Ne7. }
6... Nd7
{ This is the main move. Black develops both the knights for now and wants to decide on the future of the f5 and f8-bishops later. }
7. O-O
{ Going for the bishop with  7.Nh4  is possible, but Black seems to be doing fine in the complications after  7...Be4  8.Nd2  c5  .   If Black wants to play the 7.O-O h6 variation, it is also possible to start with another move order, for example  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3  h6  7.O-O  Nd7  . }
7... c5
{ This is extremely popular accross all levels and it is also very logical. Black has developed both the knights and now feels it's time to fight for the center and push the thematic pawn break. However, it seems that this break comes too late as well as too early, and although the correspondence players often managed to hold this line, the modern engines don't favor it very much and it seems to me that White has a lot of attractive options against it.For this course, I have prepared a rare nuance just two moves down the line, avoiding most of the correspondence material on this topic. }
8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Nd4
{ The main move. We target the f5-bishop and bring the knight to the center. Now also the move Nc6 becomes less attractive, as Black will have to deal with the capture on c6. }
9... Bg6
{ Bringing the bishop back is the way they play. Now most games go  10.Be3  Nc6  11.c4  and the lines are long and deep. Instead, I propose a rare inclusion, which looks much more 2022 to me. }
10. h4
{ Grabbing space with the h-pawn advance screams AlphaZero and indeed, the modern computers nod in approval @@StartBracket@@in fact I was the one doing the nodding@@EndBracket@@. }
10... h6 11. h5
{ This extra space will be useful once we eventually get some pieces towards the kingside. }
11... Bh7 12. Be3
{ Now that we have included h4-h5, we are back to playing the 'normal' way. }
12... Nc6 13. c4 { Challenging the center. } 13... dxc4
{ This is also the response in the line without the h4-h5 inclusion. } 14. Nxc6
bxc6
{ In this position without the h4-h5 inclusion, most games would go  15.Nd2  c3  16.bxc3  and this is possible here as well. However, there is something much more funky. }
15. Na3 { The knight still develops itself, but after c3 it doesn't get hit. }
15... c3
{ The only move, as otherwise Black also has to deal with a worse queenside pawn structure for no compensation. }
16. Qc1
{ Actually the simple  16.bxc3  leads to a very pleasant endgame for White, as we have the more developed position and a nice pawn structure on the kingside. However, the text move is much more ambitious. We are going for the throat. }
16... cxb2 17. Qxb2
{ Black has to deal with a bunch of threats and is not in time to finish development, as  17...Be7  is unpleasantly met with  18.Rfd1  when the black position basically collapses. The only way to play is to try to interpose a bishop on d5. }
17... Be4 { A good attempt to try and stabilize the sinking ship. } 18. Rad1
{ We are going to play on the kingside and will not be needing the rook on the c-file. }
18... Bd5
{ Black would think that everything is not going too badly and at least there is going to be some stability thanks to the d5-bishop. Oh well. }
19. Rxd5
{ A beautiful sacrifice, which according to the engine is just one of multiple options to put pressure. Luckily a human being could interfere, select the move from the dropdown menu and attach an exclam mark to it for the beauty. }
19... exd5
{ The only recapture, as after  19...cxd5  there is  20.Bxc5  Bxc5  21.Qb5+  while @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/p4pp1/2p1p2p/2nRP2P/8/N3B3/PQ2BPP1/5RK1 b kq - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Qxd5  loses to  20.Rd1  Qe4  21.Nb5! }
20. Qc3 { Black has some issues on the c-file. } 20... Nd7
{ Again, the only move. } 21. Nc2
{ We are rerouting our knight to where all the action is. } 21... Be7
{ The best move, though e6 looks crushing. } 22. e6 fxe6 23. Nd4
{ Black has to keep his cool to keep the game going. } 23... Bf6 24. Qxc6
{ And Black has to try to castle somehow and return all the pawns. The first line of the engine goes  24...Rc8!  @@StartBracket@@a hard move to find!@@EndBracket@@  25.Qxe6+  Qe7  26.Qxd5  Bxd4!  27.Qxd4  O-O  28.Qxa7  and White is now up material with two bishops and two pawns for the exchange, while Black is happy that at least the game is still ongoing and the suffering continues. }
