{ Going for the bishop with  7.Nh4  is possible, but Black seems to be doing fine in the complications after  7...Be4  8.Nd2  c5  .   If Black wants to play the 7.O-O h6 variation, it is also possible to start with another move order, for example  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3  h6  7.O-O  Nd7  . }
7... h6
{ This is a mega super duper tabiya of the entire Advance Caro-Kann and can be reached by all sorts of move orders. It occurs a lot at high level, low level, correspondence, over the board, online and what not. Black is very flexible in his plans. It is still possible to play the position quietly with the bishop dropping back to h7 and so on, but it's also possible to go for the much sharper plans with long castle and/ or g5.I selected a plan that I find quite effective against all of those setups, but in particular against the sharper ones with O-O-O and g5, because these are the things I expect one is mainly concerned about when entering this line with White. The sharp setups are also the ones that I have personally faced in my own experience in this line as well. }
8. Na3
{ The knight is extremely well placed on e3 against the g5 setups and this route is much more efficient than going Nbd2 Re1 Nf1 or Nbd2 and then take the other knight with Ne1-Nc2-Ne3. It is also pretty decent against the plans with c5, since from c2 the knight is contributing well to the fight for the d4-square. Black does have a lot of options here, and we'll consider them one by one. }
8... Qc7
{ Plans with long castle are really dubious as Black's kingside play is very hypothetical, while our queenside pawns are ready to launch an offensive at any point. }
9. Nc2 O-O-O
{ It is not so easy for us to mate the black king since b4-b5 is not the end of the world, but it is even harder for our opponent to get to ours. In fact, what I saw in the correspondence games where White was successful is that often times White spent a lot of time fighting for the squares on the kingside and the center in order to establish control over the position, and reserved the queenside action for later. }
10. a4
{ It is also possible to play the more natural  10.b4  first, but there is also no need to rush into pushing it, since the position is much more nuanced than Black attacking on the kingside and White on the queenside. }
10... Kb8
{ This can be somewhat different, as including Kb8 and b4 changes some nuances, but can also transpose to 10...f6. }
11. b4
{ We always have our pawns ready for action, but we don't have to pull the trigger too early. }
11... f6 { Black needs this move to get any sort of counterplay. } 12. exf6
gxf6 13. Nh4 { It's important to fight for the squares on the kingside. } 13...
Be4 14. Bf3 { Again, the fight for the kingside squares continues! } 14... Rg8
15. g3 f5 16. Bg2 { We are forcing the trade of the bishops. } 16... Bxg2 17.
Kxg2 Ng6
{ Black has to keep trading our pieces in order to try and get access to the squares and get any kind of play going. }
18. Nxg6 Rxg6 19. Ne1
{ Again, we keep fighting for the squares and don't yet think about any queenside play, which at this point is not on the agenda. }
19... Bd6 20. Nd3 f4 21. Kh1 { Unpinning ourselves. } 21... e5
{ This looks impressive, but doesn't even have a clear threat. } 22. Ra2
{ Adding an extra security layer! } 22... fxg3 23. fxg3 e4
{ This tempting push gains Black absolutely nothing. } 24. Nc5
{ The pawn on e4 looks pretty, but Black has no play here at all and White is suddenly dominating the entire board with Qh5 and Raf2 coming. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 with 5...Ne7"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance 5...Ne7 with 6...Nd7 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7
{ The third most played move after  5...Nd7  and  5...c5  , but  5...Nd7  will in many cases transpose to 5...Ne7 as well. Generally there are many transpositions as Black, for example, can play Ne7, Nd7 and h6 in any of the orders.   Essentially, in this  5...Ne7  chapter, I would like to look at all the critical variations that can arise when the knight gets developed to e7 @@StartBracket@@before the f8-bishop comes out onto the f8-a3 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. Lines where Black plays without the early Ne7, such as for example the rare Nd7 Be7 setup, will be looked at in the next chapter which covers all the sidelines.I hope that makes sense! }
6. c3
{ With the move orders @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3!?  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.c3!?  , we essentially avoid a large system - @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.O-O  c5  .  This system is not such a problem for White, but it just saves us extra work, since we can place the pawn on c3 against pretty much all of the setups with Ne7. }
6... Nd7
{ This is the main move. Black develops both the knights for now and wants to decide on the future of the f5 and f8-bishops later. }
7. O-O
{ Going for the bishop with  7.Nh4  is possible, but Black seems to be doing fine in the complications after  7...Be4  8.Nd2  c5  .   If Black wants to play the 7.O-O h6 variation, it is also possible to start with another move order, for example  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3pPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  6.c3  h6  7.O-O  Nd7  . }
7... h6
{ This is a mega super duper tabiya of the entire Advance Caro-Kann and can be reached by all sorts of move orders. It occurs a lot at high level, low level, correspondence, over the board, online and what not. Black is very flexible in his plans. It is still possible to play the position quietly with the bishop dropping back to h7 and so on, but it's also possible to go for the much sharper plans with long castle and/ or g5.I selected a plan that I find quite effective against all of those setups, but in particular against the sharper ones with O-O-O and g5, because these are the things I expect one is mainly concerned about when entering this line with White. The sharp setups are also the ones that I have personally faced in my own experience in this line as well. }
8. Na3
{ The knight is extremely well placed on e3 against the g5 setups and this route is much more efficient than going Nbd2 Re1 Nf1 or Nbd2 and then take the other knight with Ne1-Nc2-Ne3. It is also pretty decent against the plans with c5, since from c2 the knight is contributing well to the fight for the d4-square. Black does have a lot of options here, and we'll consider them one by one. }
8... Qc7
{ Plans with long castle are really dubious as Black's kingside play is very hypothetical, while our queenside pawns are ready to launch an offensive at any point. }
9. Nc2 O-O-O
{ It is not so easy for us to mate the black king since b4-b5 is not the end of the world, but it is even harder for our opponent to get to ours. In fact, what I saw in the correspondence games where White was successful is that often times White spent a lot of time fighting for the squares on the kingside and the center in order to establish control over the position, and reserved the queenside action for later. }
10. a4
{ It is also possible to play the more natural  10.b4  first, but there is also no need to rush into pushing it, since the position is much more nuanced than Black attacking on the kingside and White on the queenside. }
10... Kb8
{ This can be somewhat different, as including Kb8 and b4 changes some nuances, but can also transpose to 10...f6. }
11. b4
{ We always have our pawns ready for action, but we don't have to pull the trigger too early. }
11... f6 { Black needs this move to get any sort of counterplay. } 12. exf6
gxf6 13. Nh4 { It's important to fight for the squares on the kingside. } 13...
Be4 14. Bf3 { Again, the fight for the kingside squares continues! } 14... Rg8
15. g3 f5 16. Bg2 { We are forcing the trade of the bishops. } 16... Bxg2 17.
Kxg2 Ng6
{ Black has to keep trading our pieces in order to try and get access to the squares and get any kind of play going. }
18. Nxg6 Rxg6 19. Ne1
{ Again, we keep fighting for the squares and don't yet think about any queenside play, which at this point is not on the agenda. }
19... Bd6 20. Nd3 f4 21. Kh1 { Unpinning ourselves. } 21... fxg3 22. fxg3
{ We are now holding all the trumps on the... kingside, and all Black has created is weaknesses. Our king is safe and we will soon start harvesting the weak e6 and h6-pawns. }
