{ The safest option, but Black is nowhere safe at this point. } 12. Ncd4
{ Black has to deal with the nasty threat of c4, opening the d-file, when it will be relevant that instead of developing his kingside, Black was just shuffling pieces around. }
12... g5
{ Trying to quickly finish the development. Now an old correspondence game went  13.c4  which remains critical, but the computer also comes up with  13.h4!?  , the idea being the very same  13...g4  14.Nxe6!  sac, though after  13...gxh4!  things are not so simple. }
13. c4 Bg7
{ The natural move, but the correspondence player Biedermann had seen the piece sac coming and deviated with 13... Be4 instead. }
14. Nxe6
{ With the pawn on g5 and the king in the center, this sacrifice is thematic. }
14... fxe6 15. Nd4
{ Black has a lot to worry about and can't so easily return the material, as after  15...O-O  he returns too much with  16.Nxe6  ,  --  17.cxd5  and  --  18.Nxf8  gaining us the upper hand on the material counter as well. }
15... Nf8 { Trying to hold on to the weak e6-pawn. } 16. cxd5
{ Opening the d-file and using the fact that  16...Nxd5  can be met with  17.Bh5+! }
16... Qxd5 17. Qa4+ { A nasty check from the left. } 17... Kf7 18. f4
{ We open the f-file and will keep adding pressure. Black's pieces are grouped together around the king, but there is no harmony and they are stepping on each other's toes. White is for choice and as a great player once said "It is much easier to attack than to defend, no?". }
