{ The knight is extremely well placed on e3 against the g5 setups and this route is much more efficient than going Nbd2 Re1 Nf1 or Nbd2 and then take the other knight with Ne1-Nc2-Ne3. It is also pretty decent against the plans with c5, since from c2 the knight is contributing well to the fight for the d4-square. Black does have a lot of options here, and we'll consider them one by one. }
8... a6
{ The most often played move according to my database, though many moves are close and it depends mainly on the database you will be using. Somehow people have the urge to guard the b5-square and prepare the c5 push. }
9. Nc2 { The knight is happy to have reached the destination safely. } 9... c5
{ Black's play is logical: Ne7, Nd7, h6, a6, c5. It's almost beautiful, yet Black's position is still not going to be great. Life is unfair. }
10. dxc5
{ It is possible to maintain the tension, but very often this capture is the way to punish Black for a somewhat mistimed c5 break. }
10... Nxc5 11. Be3
{ In this particular version, we are doing ourselves a favor by gaining some time on the c5-knight before going for Ncd4. }
11... Rc8 12. Ncd4
{ Here the g5 idea is even worse than after 11... Nd7, but it is also not easy to think up a good way to develop, since Rc1 and c4 are coming. }
12... g5 { Now this loses in a very surprising way. } 13. Nxf5
{ This works because of the concrete circumstances. Positionally the operation is quite insane. }
13... Nxf5 14. Nd4
{ A shocker. It appears as though we are going to get totally dominated on the dark squares, but Black is just not in time to get his king to safety. }
14... Nxe3 15. fxe3 Bg7 16. b4 { And now it becomes clear. Nxe6! is coming. }
16... Ne4 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Bh5+ Kd7 19. Rf7+ Kc6 20. Rxg7 { And White wins. }
