[Black "Caro-Kann Advance: 5...Bb4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Bb4+
{ This is a provocative system that has a very clear point. Black wants to transfer the bishop to c7, making sure the bishop is not in the way of Ne7. The concept is great, but the problem is that it is too artificial and slow. }
6. c3
{ It is also possible to go for  6.Nbd2  ,  but I like the concrete idea of 7. Qb3!?. }
6... Ba5 7. Qb3
{ I like this concrete idea, trying to distract the black queen with the defense of the b7 pawn in order to then chase the f5-bishop. }
7... Bb6
{ If  7...Qc7  we have  8.Nh4!  ,  collecting the important bishop, while if Black chooses to sacrifice the b7-pawn we will just take it and say thanks. }
8. a4 { Softening up the b6-bishop for our Nh4 purposes. } 8... a5 9. Nh4
{ Black is in a very bad shape here. } 9... Ne7 10. Bg5
{ We are following a correspondence game from 2018 Abrile-Jung for now. } 10...
Bxb1 11. Rxb1 c5 12. Bxe7
{ Black has to recapture with the king, which is quite awkward. } 12... Kxe7
13. Qa3 Nc6 { Now I propose to improve on the correspondence game. } 14. Nf3
{ A better move order than  14.dxc5  first. } 14... Kf8 15. dxc5 Bc7
{ And here the correspondence game continued  16.O-O?!  g5!  and Black got some counterplay and escaped. Instead the modern engines point out a strong improvement. }
16. b4 axb4 17. cxb4 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. g3 g6
{ Black solves the problem of the king, but faces great issues on the queenside. }
20. a5
{ I wouldn't be able to tell so easily, but the computers claim a near winning advantage at this point already. At some point a c6 or a6 break will happen and then we have the two connected passers. }
