{ Here the pawn break is outright bad. Black could get the move  7...h6  for free, since we anyway play  8.c3  c5  9.c4!  @@StartBracket@@see the 5...Nd7 6. O-O h6 move order@@EndBracket@@. }
8. c4 Ne7 9. dxc5 { Our standard response. } 9... Nxc5 10. Nd4 Bg6
{ And here a fresh correspondence game saw White play very powerfully. } 11. h4
h6 12. h5 Bh7 13. b4 Nd3 14. Qb3
{ And Black eventually lost after  14...Nf4  15.Bf3  ,  but also had he picked up the pawn with  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2nppb/p3p2p/3pP2P/1PPN4/1Q1n4/P2NBPP1/R1B2RK1 b kq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nxe5  15.Bb2!  White's compensation would be enormous. }
