[White "9) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance: 5...Nd7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7
{ This move can often transpose to systems looked under 5...Ne7 move order, especially if Black follows this up with h6 and Ne7, but it can also lead to independent lines, if Black chooses not to develop the knight on e7 just yet. }
6. O-O Bg6
{ The are a lot of games in the database with this move. Black usually chooses to follow up it up with Nh6! next, but positions with Bxh6 gxh6 can be pleasant for White - after all, Black does have a weakened kingside. }
7. c3 { It is also possible to try and grab space immediately with  7.a4  . }
7... Nh6
{ The most popular move here.  7...Ne7  transposes to the line 5...Ne7 6. c3 Nd7 7. O-O Bg6. }
8. a4
{ This is a smart inclusion here. We want to grab space, while if Black chooses to meet our advance with  8...a5  the eventual c5 push will weaken the b5-square. }
8... a5
{ On this topic there is a highly instructive game of Yu Yangyi against Artemiev which Yu up to a point played very well. }
9. Na3
{ The knight embarks on a journey. The good thing here is that whenever Black goes c5, we can exploit the weakness of the b5-square. }
9... Be7
{ Artemiev insists on allowing Bxh6. It can be smart to wait for Bxh6 before Black goes Be7, so that after gxh6 there is no more Bg7 move. }
10. Nc2
{ It was already sensible to take on h6, but postponing it is also a perfectly fine idea. }
10... O-O 11. Nce1 c5
{ Black needs some kind of counterplay, but now White can plant the bishop on b5. }
12. Bxh6 { Finally Yu decides to take. } 12... gxh6 13. Bb5
{ The bishop sits well here. } 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Nb8 15. Qd2
{ Gaining a tempo on the pawn. } 15... Kg7 16. Nd3
{ The knight is heading to f4. } 16... Na6
{ Not a very appealing move, but Artemiev wants to put the knight on b4 and was bothered by Bxc6 ideas. }
17. Nf4 Qb6 18. h4
{ On h4 the pawn restricts Bg5 just in case and provides more room for our king. We don't want to push h5 usually, keeping that square open for our knight. }
18... Rfc8 19. Rfc1 Rxc1+ 20. Rxc1 Nb4 21. g3
{ White keeps improving the position little by little. } 21... Na2 22. Rd1
{ Yu Yangyi of course plays for a win. } 22... Rc8
{ Only here comes a mistake from Yu. After the tempting  23.Nh2  intending Ng4, it turns out Black has  23...Qc7!  followed by Qc2! with enough counterplay. Eventually Black won in Yu-Artemiev, Gibraltar 2019. Instead, White had to prevent the invasion and not rush it. }
23. Ne1
{ Followed by Qe2 and then perhaps Nh5, with a slow attack. The main point is that Black just doesn't have much counterplay now that the c2-square is under control. }
