{ This has been played by Mamedyarov and Jobava and they both got away with it. }
10. Nc3
{ Threatening both Nb5 as well as Na4, so Black has to play a6 to secure the d4-square. }
10... a6 11. Ng5 Nxe5
{ Greed leads to trouble, but the punishment is not so easy to find. A correspondence game went  11...Qe7  12.Bh5+!  g6  13.Be2!  when Black had to weaken the position further with  13...h5  to stop g4 and then  14.Nf3!  followed by Bg5 sealed the deal. }
12. Re1 { Now Black has a choice between  12...Nf6  and  12...Qf6  . } 12...
Nf6 { It's not hard to demonstrate the deficiency of this move. } 13. Bh5+ Nxh5
14. Rxe5
{ This way we regain the sacrificed pawn with a clear positional advantage. }
14... Nf6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Rxe6+ Kf7 17. Re5
{ The d5-pawn is likely to fall soon. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance: 5...Nd7 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7
{ This move can often transpose to systems looked under 5...Ne7 move order, especially if Black follows this up with h6 and Ne7, but it can also lead to independent lines, if Black chooses not to develop the knight on e7 just yet. }
6. O-O f6
{ This is an interesting concept, but this early it doesn't work very well. }
7. c4 { In the sharp complications Black's position just doesn't hold up. }
7... fxe5 8. dxe5 Bc5
{ This setup is pretty reasonable for Black with the inclusion of the moves a5 and a4, which is why 6... a5 is interesting. Here, however, things just don't work that well for Black. }
9. cxd5 cxd5
{ This has been played by Mamedyarov and Jobava and they both got away with it. }
10. Nc3
{ Threatening both Nb5 as well as Na4, so Black has to play a6 to secure the d4-square. }
10... a6 11. Ng5 Nxe5
{ Greed leads to trouble, but the punishment is not so easy to find. A correspondence game went  11...Qe7  12.Bh5+!  g6  13.Be2!  when Black had to weaken the position further with  13...h5  to stop g4 and then  14.Nf3!  followed by Bg5 sealed the deal. }
12. Re1 Qf6 13. Bf4 { Setting up a sacrifice in the center. } 13... Ng6 14.
Nxd5 { We sacrifice and play Bh5 in some order or the other. } 14... exd5 15.
Qxd5 N8e7 16. Bh5 { Now there are maximum pins on the king. } 16... Rc8
{ Black keeps trying to hold on to the material, which is principled. } 17.
Rad1 { Adding the last piece into the attack. } 17... Bb4
{ Black's bishop gets out of the way for  18.--  h6  19.Ne4  Qf7!  to work. }
18. Re2 h6
{ Here  19.Ne4  Qf7  leaves Black with some decent chances, as we can win back the piece with  20.Bxg6!  but it gets drawish after  20...Nxd5  there. Instead, the computer finds an absolutely insane sequence that wins outright. }
19. Nh7
{ Now  19...Qf7  can be met with  20.Qxb7  ,  but I like the follow up after Rxh7 even more. }
19... Rxh7 20. Qg8+ Qf8
{ Now fortunately  22.Qxh7  also wins, but the best move according to the computer is really shocking. }
21. Qb3 a5 22. g4
{ Beauty lies in the eyes of the beholder and also in the variation after  22...Bb1  23.Rxb1  Qxf4  24.Bxg6  Kf8  25.Qe6  Rc6  26.Re4  Qf3  27.Rd4!!  intending Rd8 checkmate.   22...Bc2  23.Qxc2!  also pretty. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance: 5...Nd7 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7
{ This move can often transpose to systems looked under 5...Ne7 move order, especially if Black follows this up with h6 and Ne7, but it can also lead to independent lines, if Black chooses not to develop the knight on e7 just yet. }
6. O-O h6
{ In most cases Nd7/h6/Ne7 will all transpose to each other, but there can be extra options for both sides along the way.   For  6...Ne7  see the mainline of the 5... Ne7 chapter. }
7. c3
{ We are fishing for a transposition after  7.c3  Ne7  which is by far the most logical move here.   It's also possible in this particular position to go for  7.a4!?  grabbing space on the queenside, but I see no reason to complicate it for ourselves. }
7... a6
{ If Black waits, trying to get us out of our Na3 setup, we can show some flexibility as well.   Again  7...Ne7  would transpose to the mainline of the 5...Ne7 chapter. }
8. Nbd2
{ We haven't promised anybody that we will go for Na3-Nc2 setup at all costs. If Black wants to play an odd move just to take us out of our preparation, we can also switch to another setup. }
8... c5
{ A reasonable moment to expect the c5 break to work, as White will now go c3-c4 in two sessions. Still, Black does not have an easy life here. }
9. c4
{ The usual story. We start the action before Black gets to complete the development. }
9... Ne7 { The obvious reply. } 10. dxc5
{ A standard way to get things moving, dxc5 followed by Nd4. } 10... Nxc5 11.
Nd4
{ Some relatively old correspondence games went  11.Nb3  first, but this move order seems smarter. }
11... Bh7 { This is different from  11...Bg6  . } 12. N2b3 Nd7 13. Re1
{ With the bishop on g6 this would have been pointless, but now we actually have a nasty threat of Bh5! }
13... Rc8 { This is falling for it. } 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Bh5 Qb6
{ To demonstrate the full point behind our play. } 16. Nxe6
{ The point behind Re1. } 16... Qxe6 17. Nd4 { And we crush. } *

