[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Caro-Kann Advance: 3...Bf5 Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Advance: 5...Nd7 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann certainly belongs to the most respectable of the defenses one can play against 1.e4 and I have to say it wasn't easy to come up with a convincing suggestion against the followers of my friend Erwin l'Ami's Chessable course, Lifetime Repertoires Caro-Kann. It is a little more passive than 1...e5 or 1... c5, but is perhaps still the soundest of the openings that this course, Part II, actually covers.Black wants to reinforce the d5 push and compared to the French defense @@StartBracket@@1... e6@@EndBracket@@ he keeps the c8-bishop open, which attracts positional chess players who like having healthy development, no bad pieces and no pawn weaknesses. Black's only issue is his lack of space, which explains my choice for this Chapter. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just as against the French, I recommend the Advanced variation against the Caro-Kann, gaining space right away. It is certainly one of the most testing systems and the logic behind it is that even though Black gets to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, it comes at a cost. First of all, that is a lot of moves neglecting the development of the kingside. Also, the move c7-c6 turns out to be a waste of time as strategically speaking the c5 push is anyway the most desirable plan, which now comes with a loss of a tempo. }
3... Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7
{ This move can often transpose to systems looked under 5...Ne7 move order, especially if Black follows this up with h6 and Ne7, but it can also lead to independent lines, if Black chooses not to develop the knight on e7 just yet. }
6. O-O h6
{ In most cases Nd7/h6/Ne7 will all transpose to each other, but there can be extra options for both sides along the way.   For  6...Ne7  see the mainline of the 5... Ne7 chapter. }
7. c3
{ We are fishing for a transposition after  7.c3  Ne7  which is by far the most logical move here.   It's also possible in this particular position to go for  7.a4!?  grabbing space on the queenside, but I see no reason to complicate it for ourselves. }
7... a6
{ If Black waits, trying to get us out of our Na3 setup, we can show some flexibility as well.   Again  7...Ne7  would transpose to the mainline of the 5...Ne7 chapter. }
8. Nbd2
{ We haven't promised anybody that we will go for Na3-Nc2 setup at all costs. If Black wants to play an odd move just to take us out of our preparation, we can also switch to another setup. }
8... Ne7
{ Black continues with his normal setup, but a6 was kind of slow, which we can now use to our advantage. }
9. b4
{ We get the time to grab the space here, since a5! which is Black's standard response in such cases comes with a loss of a tempo. }
9... a5 10. Nb3
{ We are in time to consolidate our queenside. Don't play  10.a4  though, because of  10...Ng6  followed by Nf4! }
10... axb4 11. cxb4 Nc8 { Black sends the knight towards the queenside. } 12.
Bd2 Ncb6 13. a4
{ We get to push the pawn to a5, since capturing  13...Nxa4  is well met with  14.Na5!  winning back the b7-pawn and then piling up on the c6 weakness. }
13... Be7 14. a5 Nc4 15. Bc3
{ We get an interesting position with a potential for a complete bind. } 15...
O-O 16. Nfd2 b5
{ Our a-pawn is not queening any time soon, but it can be a long-term asset for the future. What is important, though, is stopping the f6 break, which is Black's only source of potentialy counterplay. }
17. Bg4
{ We have to keep an eye on the e6-pawn to make sure f6 doesn't happen. As long as that will be the case, it promises to be a one-sided game. One other detail I should mention is that we should be ready to meet Nb8-Na6 with Nf3 and Nc5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Modern Philidor 1...d6"]
[Black "Philidor: 3...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7
{ This is what they do when they want to play the Philidor, but want to avoid the unpleasant endgame after  3...e5  4.dxe5!? }
4. f4 { The most principled response is to grab more space in the center. }
4... e5 5. Nf3 exd4 6. Qxd4
{ As a rule, a queen is good in the center when it can't be attack with Nc6. I made up this rule at some point and I think it works really well. }
6... c6
{ Black now has to play extremely accurately in order not to get blown away by our impressive central presence. }
7. Bd2
{ The other major move is  7.Be3  , which is more logical and somewhat more popular, but Black is actually getting some play there after  7...d5!  8.e5  Ng4!  when things are far from simple. I like the text move more. }
7... d5 { This works less well here than after 7. Be3. } 8. O-O-O Bc5 9. Qd3
O-O { Black has to sacrifice the pawn, but there isn't enough compensation. }
10. exd5 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5
{ There is no compensation for the pawn here either. } *

