{ Black's king lost the right to castle which can be a factor, especially once the position opens up and many pieces stay on the board. }
6. Bc4
{ I once mixed up the move order in a blitz game and played  6.f4?!  I won anyway, but it is apparently really important to only go for f4 after  6.Bc4  Ke8  . After  6.Bc4  Black has three ways to defend.  6...Ke8  ,  6...Be6  and the rare but decent  6...Bb4!? }
6... Be6
{ This used to be considered really smart back when I was a kid and I remember somehow getting outplayed here with White, but I can really no longer understand how that happened.I think an important idea that White must be aware of and probably what I didn't know as a kid, is that what White will often need to do is remove the knight from c3 and place a pawn there, dominating the c6-knight. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3
{ We have to solidify our e4-pawn and develop a little bit, but in the long run, we need to remove the c3-knight and place the pawn there, not allowing Nc6-Nd4 jumps. }
8... Bd6 9. Be3 { The ideal square for the bishop. } 9... Ke7 10. Nh3
{ The knight on f2 is really weall placed, anticipating g5-g4 ideas. } 10... a6
11. Nf2 Nc6 { This is how they usually play, hoping to get the knight to d4. }
12. Nb1
{ This is the key idea to remember. We go c3, kill the c6-knight @@StartBracket@@if  12...Nd4  now we have  13.Kd1!  @@EndBracket@@  then go Nd2 Ke2 and once Black has no more constructive ideas, we can start thinking of queenside play with a4-b4 etc. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Modern Philidor 1...d6"]
[Black "Philidor Endgame: 6...Bb4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5
{ This is the modern Philidor, which is quite different from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Philidor covered in Part 1 of my 1.e4 LTR. In the old Philidor Black is practically forced to give up the center and then we go for the Bf4 O-O-O setup and get a very sharp position.   Here, Black intends to keep the central tension, which is not possible after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  because after  3.d4  Nd7?  4.Bc4!  there are concrete issues with the f7-pawn. The issue with the 1... d6 move order for Black is that we can trade on e5 and get a better endgame, since Black loses some time moving his king back and forth. }
4. dxe5
{ The mainline continues  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  ,  but then Black gets what he wants: a passive but super solid position full of counter-attacking chances. From my vast experience of playing these Philidor guys, the best way to chase them out of their opening, is to play  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  . In the following game they'll switch to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  and then we hit them with  4.f4  .  The game after that they abandon the Philidor and play some other opening which they like less. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black's king lost the right to castle which can be a factor, especially once the position opens up and many pieces stay on the board. }
6. Bc4
{ I once mixed up the move order in a blitz game and played  6.f4?!  I won anyway, but it is apparently really important to only go for f4 after  6.Bc4  Ke8  . After  6.Bc4  Black has three ways to defend.  6...Ke8  ,  6...Be6  and the rare but decent  6...Bb4!? }
6... Bb4
{ A rare move, but a valid attempt to try and hold this slightly worse endgame. }
7. Bxf7
{ We are happy to trade the e4-pawn for the f7-pawn. In the end we keep the better pawn structure. }
7... Rf8 { The same would be  7...Nxe4  8.Nge2  Rf8  9.Bb3  . } 8. Bb3 Nxe4 9.
Ne2 { Now Black shouldn't take the f2-pawn. } 9... Nxf2
{ This doesn't lose material right away, but Black is just massively underdeveloped and will face issues with the king in the center. }
10. Rf1 Ng4 11. Bg5+ { Developing with tempo. } 11... Ke8 12. Rxf8+ Bxf8 13.
O-O-O { White is making all the tempting moves. } 13... Bd6 14. Nb5
{ And White enjoyed a winning advantage already in Korneev-Torres, 1-0 2013. }
