4. dxe5
{ The mainline continues  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  ,  but then Black gets what he wants: a passive but super solid position full of counter-attacking chances. From my vast experience of playing these Philidor guys, the best way to chase them out of their opening, is to play  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq e6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.dxe5  . In the following game they'll switch to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  and then we hit them with  4.f4  .  The game after that they abandon the Philidor and play some other opening which they like less. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black's king lost the right to castle which can be a factor, especially once the position opens up and many pieces stay on the board. }
6. Bc4
{ I once mixed up the move order in a blitz game and played  6.f4?!  I won anyway, but it is apparently really important to only go for f4 after  6.Bc4  Ke8  . After  6.Bc4  Black has three ways to defend.  6...Ke8  ,  6...Be6  and the rare but decent  6...Bb4!? }
6... Ke8
{ This feels like the modern mainline as the old  6...Be6  move started losing followers for a good reason, while the new  6...Bb4  hasn't caught on yet. }
7. f4
{ It is also possible to just develop with Nf3 and so on, but this direct move puts the most pressure on the Black's position. The concept is to try and open up the position, using the fact that we have more space, the better development and the safer king since we kept the rights to castle. }
7... Nbd7
{ This setup is much better after the inclusion of  7...Bb4  8.Bd3  , but we do have to know how to make use of it. }
8. Nf3 Bd6 9. g3
{ It's possible to castle short as well, but the plan with long castling is much more challenging. }
9... c6 { The setup with c6 and Ke7 looks tempting. } 10. a4
{ We stop Black from grabbing queenside space and developing the c8-bishop. }
10... Ke7 11. Be3 { As promised we go for O-O-O. } 11... Re8 12. O-O-O
{ We are way ahead when it comes to development and piece coordination. } 12...
Ng4
{ Black has this strong looking idea, but we have an even stronger antidote. }
13. Bg1 exf4 14. Rxd6
{ Sacrificing an exchange. Even though it's an endgame already, we get a huge attack for it. }
14... Kxd6 15. gxf4
{ We have lots of ways to activate our pieces and Black is in a pretty bad shape here, not being able to develop his queenside and having issues all over the dark squares. }
