[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Scandinavian: 3...Qd6 and Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Scandinavian with 2...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Nf6
{ This system is extremely tricky if you get baited and try to hang on to the d5-pawn. }
3. Nf3
{ I believe this is a very simple solution and a reasonably easy move order for us to try and weather the storm that Black is trying to create. Now  3...Bg4  can be well met with  4.Bb5+!  ,  while recapturing the pawn on d5 is not going to bother us too much.   3.d4  is also a fine move, but then after  3...Bg4  things can get a lot more murky. }
3... Bg4 { Principled, but it doesn't seem to be very good. } 4. Bb5+
{ An important move. We try to make Black lose even more time to regain the d5-pawn. }
4... Nbd7 5. h3
{ A fine inclusion. Starting with  5.Nc3  will lead to the same. } 5... Bh5 6.
Nc3
{ We don't exactly hang on to the pawn on d5 for too long, but we do want to force Black to lose some time regaining it. }
6... a6 7. Be2 { modest, but good here. } 7... Nb6 8. O-O
{ The pawn has to be returned. We just finish our development. } 8... Nfxd5
{ If  8...Nbxd5  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  we have  10.c4  followed by d4 and Qb3, when Black has to answer some questions while still not having developed his kingside. }
9. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ If  9...Qxd5  then  10.a4!  is very nasty, gaining space at the cost of the misplaced b6-knight. }
10. d4 { Now we start grabbing space in the center. } 10... e6 11. c4 Nf6
{ This is an interesting position to understand. On the one hand, Black is about to finish his development rather harmoniously. One may even think Black should feel happy about the outcome of this particular Scandinavian. Yet, what has also happened is that we got rid of our problematic c3-knight, which is an ugly piece in the Scandi, being in the way of our c-pawn. This fact speaks in our favor and is the reason why we should still be happy with the outcome of the opening. }
12. Bf4 { Finishing the development. Qb3 is on the agenda. } 12... Bd6
{ Black offers a trade. } 13. Ne5
{ We are fine with some trades, as we quickly get the rooks into the game as well. }
13... Bxe2 14. Qxe2 { Boys, today, the plan is simple. We just lift our rook. }
14... O-O 15. Rad1 Nd7
{ This happened in Demchenko-Samusenko. Black has played very reasonable chess so far, trying to trade more and more pieces, but in the end White's space advantage and continuing lead in development @@StartBracket@@of rooks!@@EndBracket@@ matters. }
16. c5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qe7 18. Bg5
{ And White won. The material is getting limited, but White dominates with what's left! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Scandinavian: 3...Qd6 and Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Scandinavian with 2...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Nf6
{ This system is extremely tricky if you get baited and try to hang on to the d5-pawn. }
3. Nf3
{ I believe this is a very simple solution and a reasonably easy move order for us to try and weather the storm that Black is trying to create. Now  3...Bg4  can be well met with  4.Bb5+!  ,  while recapturing the pawn on d5 is not going to bother us too much.   3.d4  is also a fine move, but then after  3...Bg4  things can get a lot more murky. }
3... Qxd5
{ This will most likely transpose to one of the 2...Qxd5 lines, but Black has one extra option that we shall address. }
4. Nc3
{ Now Qa5, Qd6 and Qd8 all transpose, but Black has an extra option of Qh5. This is not great objectively, but it is quite important to know about. }
4... Qh5
{ This very direct plan of Bg4, Nc6 and long castle has caused me a lot of headaches in my youth and later on in my blitz and bullet games as well. However, once you find out that it is in fact a bluff, you should be good to go. }
5. Be2 { We first prepare for the Bg4-xf3 threat. } 5... Bg4 6. O-O Nc6
{ This is how they play. Objectively better is to just play  6...c6  and after  7.h3  give up the bishop and hide the queen on c7 via a5 and just be slightly worse. Now, though, we have to find a precise response, as O-O-O is coming. }
7. h3
{ Here Black is sort of claiming that he is going to sacrifice the bishop and checkmate us, but upon closer look it turns out that he actually doesn't. }
7... Bxh3 { This sac doesn't work either. } 8. gxh3 Qxh3 9. d4
{ Black doesn't threaten a perpetual because after  9...Qg4+  10.Kh1  Qh3+  we have  11.Nh2  . }
9... O-O-O 10. Ng5 { Now it's time to force the queen out. } 10... Qh4 11. Kg2
{ followed by Rh1 and it's GG. } 11... Rxd4 12. Rh1
{ White is winning, as we are up a piece. } *

