[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Scandinavian: 3...Qd6 and Early Alternatives"]
[Black "Scandinavian with 2...Nf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Nf6
{ This system is extremely tricky if you get baited and try to hang on to the d5-pawn. }
3. Nf3
{ I believe this is a very simple solution and a reasonably easy move order for us to try and weather the storm that Black is trying to create. Now  3...Bg4  can be well met with  4.Bb5+!  ,  while recapturing the pawn on d5 is not going to bother us too much.   3.d4  is also a fine move, but then after  3...Bg4  things can get a lot more murky. }
3... Nxd5
{ Black takes on d5 with the knight, but this is quite time consuming and the knight later will also get pushed back with c4. }
4. d4
{ This move is obvious, but one should also keep in mind that  4.Be2?!  would be a mistake because of  4...Nf4! }
4... Bg4
{ The pin makes sense here and has been played by Levon Aronian once in a tournament game, though I should add it was a bullet tournament. }
5. c4 { The most energetic. } 5... Nf6
{ This is quite passive. We get a perfect position here, with the c-pawn in front of the c3 knight. }
6. Be2 e6 7. O-O Be7 { By far the most played move. } 8. Qb3
{ Putting an annoying question to the b7-pawn. } 8... Qc8 { A clumsy reply. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 O-O 11. g4
{ We shouldn't fear making a weakness. Black has no chance of setting up any play on the kingside. In fact it will likely be White who will start playing on that wing soon. }
11... Bg6 12. Nh4 { Going after the bishop is logical. } 12... c6 13. Bf4
{ Natural development. } 13... Nbd7 14. Rad1 Rd8 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Bf3
{ We are fully mobilized, Black is crawling on the first three ranks and it is up to us to decide how we will tighten the screws. Kg2 h4-h5 at some point seems like a sensible plan, but we should also keep in mind the possibility of the d5 break in the center, under favorable circumstances. }
