[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... c6
{ This Gambit continuation is not very good, but Black does get some space in the center and we should know how to develop our pieces properly, to neutralize any potential initiative. There is no need to panic. }
3. dxc6 { Of course, we should accept the speculative sacrifice. } 3... Nxc6 4.
Nf3
{ There are many decent move orders for White. We may just as well start with the other knight, and even  4.Bc4!?  has some merit. }
4... e5 5. Nc3
{ The tempting  5.Bb5!?  is good too, but developing the knight first is the most ambitious, keeping the option of putting the bishop on c4 open. }
5... Bc5
{ This is the attempt to make this system somewhat playable, as now the natural  6.Bb5  is met with  6...Nge7!  Instead, I propose to just play the Italian @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Bc5  @@EndBracket@@ with an extra pawn... }
6. Bc4
{ We are playing the Italian with an extra pawn. There's nothing wrong with that. }
6... Nf6 7. d3 O-O 8. O-O
{ We could prevent the somewhat annoying looking Bg4 pin with h3, but frankly there is no need to avoid it. }
8... Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Bg5
{ Getting ready to meet Nd4 with g4! and also intending to give up the bishop and chase away the h5 bishop with a standard Ne4-Ng3 maneuver. }
10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Ne4 Qe7 13. c3
{ Keeping our options open for now. We may want to take the c5-bishop and unpin with Qe2-Qe3, but we also reserve the option of Ng3. }
13... Bb6 14. Ng3 Bg6 15. Re1
{ We are not just a pawn up, but we also have pressure on the e5-pawn, which is typical for Italian positions. Black is not doing great here, as the bishop pair doesn't compensate for all the misery. }
