1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian.  The Gambit  2...c6  is not really correct, but  2...Nf6  is somewhat of a legitimate alternative as we've seen. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qd8
{ This modest move is really not so bad and it's quite popular especially in online play, or at least that's my own experience. Black just wants to get the queen out of harms way and finish his development. We did gain some tempi, though, and so can pose problems to Black if we develop aggressively enough. }
4. d4 { As usual, the moves d4 and Nf3 are no-brainers. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ Black has a few setups here, but each has some flaws. } 5... g6
{ This has become extremely common amongst top rated juniors playing games with quick time controls. We are probably somewhat better if we go for short castle, but fundamentally I feel we should really go for the long castle plan and try to exploit Black's vulnerable kingside defenses with the typical Qd2 Bh6 h4 attacking scheme. }
6. Bf4 { Very similar is  6.Bg5  and Qd2 next. } 6... Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O
{ Black should probably castle anyway. } 8. O-O-O
{ Next we basically want to give checkmate on the kingside with the typical Bh6, h4 ideas. I will give a sample line. }
8... Bf5
{ If  8...Bg4  we can first neatly collect the bishop before going for the attack with  9.Be2  and h3 to follow. }
9. h3
{ The direct  9.Bh6  @@StartBracket@@which is a perfectly fine move@@EndBracket@@ is met with  9...Qd6!  10.h4  Nbd7  10.h5  gxh5  and although we are close to winning there as well, Black is hanging on. Also, I found a very pretty line down this road after 9.h3!? and want to show it. }
9... c6
{ This is somewhat slow, but there wasn't a fast one, which is why we included the clever 9.h3 move. }
10. Bh6 { Now this move seems even stronger. } 10... b5
{ Trying for some counterplay. After  10...Qd6  we can play for example  11.Re1!?  and it's not clear how Black should respond, as  11...Nbd7  12.Bf4!  is suddenly annoying. }
11. Re1
{ The rook is well placed on the e-file as we will see, contributing to the potential attack. }
11... b4
{ Trying to misplace our knight, but now we have the c4-square for the bishop. }
12. Na4 Bxh6 { Distracting us from the b4-pawn. } 13. Qxh6 Nbd7 14. Bc4
{ We are really about to give checkmate with Ng5 and then a finishing blow. Watch how it's done. }
14... Nb6
{ Black is going for his play, hoping he will miraculously survive our mating attack, but he wont. }
15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Re5 { Intending slow domination with Rhe1 and g4. } 16... b5
17. Bb3 Be4
{ The point of Black's play, trying to distabilize our queenside defenses. }
18. Ng5
{ This and our entire previous play only really makes sense in connection with the finishing touch on move 20. }
18... Bd5 19. Bxd5 cxd5 { And here the finishing touch. } 20. Re6
{ The final blow, winning the game. In case of  20...fxe6  21.Nxe6  Black has to either allow mate on g7 or give up the queen. }
*

