1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian is a very common opening on the lower level and also an occasional guest in the practice of the very best. Black right away strikes in the center, brings his queen out in the game, which can be quite intimidating and frankly annoying if you are unprepared, but in essence it's not very healthy. By removing our central pawn from the board this quickly Black gets a very sound pawn structure, but the fact that he spends two tempi moving the queen around in the opening is likely going to cost him.As a logical consequence we have to play very energetically. We are gifted some time to develop aggressively and we should do so to utilize the time factor and turn it into something tangible! }
2. exd5 { Obviously we take. Already Black has a choice. } 2... Qxd5
{ The main-line and the 'proper' Scandinavian.  The Gambit  2...c6  is not really correct, but  2...Nf6  is somewhat of a legitimate alternative as we've seen. }
3. Nc3
{ It is very natural to develop the knight and attack the overexposed queen at the same time, but the full story is not so simple. The knight on c3 is developed towards the center, but is not 100% ideally placed, blocking the c2-pawn.   There is also definitely some merit in starting with  3.Nf3  or  3.d4  , but the problem there would be that Black will use their momentum and we won't be able to get full control of the center, as  3.d4  is just met with  3...e5!  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  allows the  3...Bg4  pin.All in all, 3.Nc3 is the way to go, but we do have to follow it up with some active powerplay! }
3... Qe5+
{ The more reasonable of the queen checks, as the queen intends to hide on c7. However, if White plays energetically enough Black will live to regret this approach. }
4. Be2 c6
{ Hiding the queen on c7. It would all be good fun, but we are not here to play games. The punishment will be brutal. }
5. d4
{ As usual, d4 and Nf3 are neccessary and usually interchangable, though the move d4 is always the more flexible one. }
5... Qc7 6. Nf3 Bf5
{ The most common way of playing, but Black is not in time to complete his development in this variation. }
7. O-O { First we castle. } 7... e6
{ And here Black's position looks solid and indeed it would be, but there is a serious problem. }
8. d5
{ That's why you can't neglect your kingside development. Black gets smashed before he gets his pieces into the game. With White we desperately need to open things up and sacrificing one pawn for it is definitely worth it. }
8... exd5 9. Nd4
{ The pawn sac also freed up an excellent square for the knight, though of course the whole thing only works because of Black's complete lack of development. }
9... Bg6 10. Re1 { Setting up some discoveries. } 10... Be7 11. h4
{ A soldier on the right joins in. } 11... h5
{ Black has to stop the h-pawn advance, but now the g6-bishop gets softened up. }
12. Bd3
{ We get rid of the only properly developed piece and also open the view for our rook. }
12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 { With Nf5 incoming, Black is toast here. } *

