4. d4 { Pawn to d4 and knight to f3 are pretty much the automatic moves. } 4...
Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is a sub-tabiya. Black has a few options and we should know how to respond to each and one of them. }
5... g6
{ This was trendy at some point and it remains a pretty solid system for Black. We once again use the fact that the queen on d6 is somewhat vulnerable in order to establish better control of the center. }
6. Nb5
{ Ideally we want our c2-pawn in front of the c3-knight, so we use the fact that the queen on d6 is misplaced to get that done. }
6... Qb6
{ From here the queen will get further kicked with an eventual Na3-Nc4 maneuver. }
7. a4 a6
{ If  7...c6  we cramp him further with  8.a5!  Qd8  9.Nc3  with a very annoying bind on the queenside. }
8. Na3 { The knight is heading to c4, continuing to harrass the queen. } 8...
Bg7 9. Nc4 Qa7 { There isn't a better square at this point. } 10. Bd3 O-O 11.
O-O
{ Black's queen is awfully placed and he has yet to finish development. Next we follow up with natural moves like Re1 and c3 and then we'll see where we strike. }
