{ It seems that  4.Nf3  will most likely transpose, but this is just a more natural move order. We need to grab space in the center anyway. }
4... c6
{ This is an attempt to be very clever. Black wants to develop the c8-bishop first and only then the g8-knight. In reality, though, it is White who gets good extra options. }
5. Bd2
{ I feel like punishing Black for his inferior move order, but I am sure if we want we can find a way to transpose back into the mainline as well. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...Bf5  just exposes the bishop and transposes to the line 4... Bf5 5. Bd2 c6. }
6. h3
{ This is very rare, but it looks extremely strong. We are punishing Black for delaying the development of the g8-knight for just that one move and now it's hard for Black to develop his c8-bishop. }
6... Bf5 { Is the most common move, but it is just what we were hoping for. }
7. g4
{ After making this move you can look at your opponent with a 'what else did you expect?' face. }
7... Bg6 8. f4 { We are just chasing the bishop, no shame. } 8... e6 9. Qe2
{ A multi-purpose move which is thematic for these lines. We want to both win the bishop with f5, but also just castle long! }
