{ I tried to be smart, but the moves  5.Bd2  as well as  5.Bc4  are well met with the provocative  5...Bg4!  when we have to weaken ourselves with  6.f3  . Even though those lines continue, White is no longer crushing it in the same way as for example @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/q7/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5?!  5.Bd2! }
5... Bf5
{ This, as well as  5...c6  can often transpose, but this move order gives Black an extra option of 6...e6 against our 6.Bd2 setup. }
6. Bd2
{ A major tabiya arises after  6.Ne5!?  c6  7.Bc4  e6  8.g4  Bg6  9.h4  Nbd7  10.Nxd7  Nxd7  11.h5  Be4  12.O-O  Bd5  13.Nxd5  cxd5  @@StartBracket@@all of Black's moves are practically forced@@EndBracket@@. White seems to be better there as well, but I think my recommendation is even better, especially when it comes to the practical aspect of things. The engine likes both moves almost equally, but it doesn't take into account that some positions are easier for us human noobs to play than others. }
6... c6
{ This leads to a major tabiya with thousand of games, but it actually seems quite miserable for Black in the end. }
7. Bc4
{ Our general concept is to castle long after Qe2, but we also have an important idea of Nd5. }
7... e6
{ The most popular move. Black just doesn't care about the  8.Nd5  threat. Wrongly so, as it's actually a big deal here. }
8. Nd5
{ A trick to remember. Now that Black will have to recapture on f6 with a queen or the pawn, we are happy to make this trade. }
8... Qd8 9. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ This is the most popular move. Black may appear to have some play on the kingside, thanks to the open g-file, but in fact it's quite easy to neutralize. Black's king, on the other hand, doesn't have a safe spot in the long term. }
10. O-O Nd7 11. Re1
{ The plan is simple. We want to neutralize any potential kingside play with Bf1 and g3 @@StartBracket@@and if needed Bg2@@EndBracket@@, while on the queenside we will roll with b4, c4 and what not. }
11... Rg8 { Anticipating Nh4. } 12. Bf1 { Now we go ahead with the plan. }
12... Qc7 13. g3 O-O-O 14. Bg2
{ We are extremely safe on the kingside and our play on the queenside should slowly but surely gain us the desired outcome. }
