[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Pirc (1...d6) and Modern (1...g6)"]
[Black "Modern with 3...c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ The Modern Defense is a sibling of the Pirc, and in our case, it will almost certainly transpose to it, given our sophisticated move order trickery. Black is delaying the development of the g8-knight, which can be quite smart especially against the Be3-Qd2-Bh6 ideas, but he does allow a transposition into the King's Indian with  2.d4  Bg7  3.c4  .  For us, as mentioned, it doesn't matter, since we play the solid and sound Be2 system in either case, when Black's best bet is to bring the knight out to f6 anyway. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3
{ We are delaying the move Nc3, not allowing Black to hit us with the early a6-b5 expansion, which is the signature of the Modern.   Now, by far the main move is  3...d6  , but there are also some alternatives. }
3... c5 { This looks like a thing, but it just isn't. } 4. dxc5
{ Somehow Black doesn't get to finish his development in this line. } 4... Qa5+
5. c3 { The right way to defend from the check. } 5... Qxc5 6. Na3
{ It's important to start with this and not  6.Be3?  Qc7  7.Na3  when Black has  7...Nc6!  and suddenly he gets to develop alright. }
6... Nf6
{ Black tries to develop quickly, but it's too late.   If  6...Nc6?!  we go  7.Nc4  with  Be3  coming next. }
7. Nb5 { The most ambitious, threatening Be3. } 7... b6
{ Dealing with the threat of Be3, but now b4! is strong. } 8. b4
{ It is important to get the sequence in the right order, but if we do manage that, Black will be in trouble. }
8... Qc6 9. e5 { Each move is powerful. } 9... Ne4
{ The best attempt as there is no good retreat at this point. } 10. Nfd4 Qb7
11. Bd3 { The e4-knight is in trouble all of a sudden. } 11... a6 12. Qe2
{ We don't need to retreat. } 12... Nc5 13. bxc5 axb5 14. Be4
{ The most powerful. } 14... Nc6 15. Qf3
{ And White wins material. Babic-Chazalette 1-0 corr 2013. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Pirc (1...d6) and Modern (1...g6)"]
[Black "Modern with 3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ The Modern Defense is a sibling of the Pirc, and in our case, it will almost certainly transpose to it, given our sophisticated move order trickery. Black is delaying the development of the g8-knight, which can be quite smart especially against the Be3-Qd2-Bh6 ideas, but he does allow a transposition into the King's Indian with  2.d4  Bg7  3.c4  .  For us, as mentioned, it doesn't matter, since we play the solid and sound Be2 system in either case, when Black's best bet is to bring the knight out to f6 anyway. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3
{ We are delaying the move Nc3, not allowing Black to hit us with the early a6-b5 expansion, which is the signature of the Modern.   Now, by far the main move is  3...d6  , but there are also some alternatives. }
3... d6 4. Be2
{ A highly sophisticated move order, breaking the 'knight before bishops' rule coined by Lasker. That rule is more of a recommendation and it's being broken left and right. In this particular case, we don't hide our modest intentions with Be2 and O-O, while we will only expose our knight to the a6-b5 idea once Black goes Nf6. }
4... Nd7 { The e5 plan is popular but flawed. } 5. O-O e5
{ There is no point in playing the weakening a6-b5 expansion, since our knight is on b1 not on c3 and after a4, the move b4 doesn't gain that tempo and just weakens the pawn. }
6. dxe5 dxe5
{ The combination of having the bishop on g7 and also pushing e5 is more often than not just very bad. Unlike the King's Indian where White would have the pawn on c4, we don't have a weak d4-square here. }
7. Nc3 { We can just develop Nc3, a4, Bc4 in any order. } 7... Ngf6 8. a4
{ The move order doesn't matter. } 8... O-O 9. Bc4
{ With an excellent position. Black will likely play  9...c6  when  10.h3  transposes to a line we look at in Pirc 6...c6 system, which is quite poor for Black. }
*

