[Black "Pirc with 6...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ The Pirc is a major opening, known for being somewhat dubious but at the same time perhaps the most fighting of all the weapons Black has at his disposal against 1. e4. Black gives up the fight for the center for now, thus avoiding complications and any direct clashes, postponing the fight for a murky middlegame.Indeed, if you outclass your opponent by a ton of rating points or if your opponent has no clue about what he is supposed to do, the Pirc @@StartBracket@@or the Modern defense for that matter, which is another move order to get to very similar positions@@EndBracket@@ is an excellent choice. In case of our opponents, however, they are going to be disappointed, as we have prepared a cold shower for them in this chapter. }
4. Nf3
{ I am going for the Be2 and O-O setup. I have played the more aggressive Be3 system a lot myself and I seriously considered building a repertoire based on even more aggressive setups, but after going over all the options and seeing the tree of my recommendations grow exponentially, I realized that this is just not practical. If we'd play a very sharp line, we would give Black exactly what they want, which is a sharp double-edged position. No matter how well you will remember your lines, they are rarely all too clear in the end and Black always has some room for a surprise or a tricky move order to get us confused.Instead, I think my recommendation of Be2 and O-O is not only objectively very challenging, but is also very clever from the psychological viewpoint. We immediately show Black that today is not going to be about fun for him, as there are no attacks or crazy tactics. All Black gets today is a near symmetrical position, but with Black being more passive and having less space. }
4... Bg7
{ There is something to be said for delaying Bg7 in systems where White goes for Be3-Qd2-Bh6 setups, but when we want to go for Be2 and O-O there isn't much point to that.   4...c6  5.Be2  b5  is just outright absurd due to  6.e5!  dxe5  7.Nxe5  when the c6-pawn is terribly weak. }
5. Be2 { Our modest but efficient development scheme, intending short castle. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... Nc6
{ This provocative move is very trendy. The position can also arise from the wacky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nc6  2.Nf3  d6  system-  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  5.Be2  Bg7  6.O-O  O-O  . Black claims that us losing the flexibility of our pawn structure with  7.d5  is worth spending two tempi for. I'm not sure if that's true. }
7. d5
{ Black doesn't have a good square for the knight, so we should go for it. }
7... Ne5
{ This has a reputation of being dubious, but the arising pawn structure is actually quite interesting for Black, and we have to be precise to tame Black's intentions. }
8. Nxe5 dxe5
{ The problem for White is that Black has two ideas here. One is the King's Indian style kingside pawn storm with Ne8-Nd6 f5-f4-g5 etc, but there is also the less aggressive, yet very reasonable e6 break. Preparing for the first would be a move like  9.a4  or  9.Be3  , but then  9...e6  will likely equalize, while preparing for e6 would be @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3Pp3/4P3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bc4  ,  but then Ne8-Nd6 gains in strength. I propose taking the middle road with  9.Qd3!?  ,  anticipating both plans. }
9. Qd3 Ne8 { Let's see what can happen if Black recklessly goes for our king. }
10. a4 { A good way to start grabbing some space on the queenside. } 10... Nd6
{ It's sensible for the knight to complete it's journey. However, it is not eternally stable on d6, as we have the idea c4-c5 in the long run. }
11. b3
{ Intending Ba3 in some cases, in a way also waiting for Black to commit to f5-f4, freeing the c3-knight from having to control the center. }
11... f5 12. f3 f4
{ This is probably wrong, but let's see what happens if Black goes all out. }
13. Nd1
{ Now that Black has given up the attempts to fight for control of the center and switched fully to the kingside, we can decentralize our knight and open the road for the c-pawn. The knight will meanwhile relocate to f2, where it is slowing down the g4 push. }
13... g5
{ Black has just one thing on his mind in this particular sample line. } 14. c4
{ Advancing on the queenside, kicking the knight away from a good square and gaining some space. }
14... h5 15. Nf2 Rf6 { Black just tries to attack, no other thoughts. } 16. c5
Nf7 17. b4 Rg6 18. Ra3 { The rook can be of great use on the third rank. }
18... g4 19. fxg4 hxg4 20. Qd1
{ We have good control of all the key squares and although Black got to push g4, it turns out that there is no real follow up. After  20...Nh6  we can play  21.g3!  and Black has no attack on the kingside at all. }
