{ The most common reply. Black lost two tempi to provoke d4-d5 and we lost some of out flexibility in the center, but the time we gained for development will prove quite valuable. }
8. Be3
{ It's also possible to develop with  8.Re1  or  8.Bg5  ,  but I like this basic development move. We don't need to do anything odd here. Just standard moves should give us a good position, as Black has played rather provocatively in the opening.   Now after  8.Be3  Black has various options, but essentially he has to decide how to undermine our d5-pawn, with either  8...e6  which will be met with  9.dxe6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/3P4/4P3/2N1BN2/PPP1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c6  ,  which will be met with us further solidifying our d5-pawn. }
8... e6
{ A natural pawn break, but now we capture and get a pleasant position. In this Philidor-style pawn structure, the bishop on g7 is not ideally placed, because once it gets traded @@StartBracket@@and most likely it will@@EndBracket@@, after a well timed Qd2-Bh6 operation, Black's king will be very weak with Nd4 and f4-f5 coming in the long run. This is quite a long-term picture, but believe me: before you know it, it's all happening. }
9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Qd2
{ The queen is well placed here, intending Rad1 and eventually Bh6. } 10... Nc6
11. Rad1
