5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is not supposed to be a good move and it isn't, since White has a strong reply here in  7.e5! }
7. e5 Ne8
{ Black's best bet. Now that he hasn't included dxe5 dxe5 after 8. e6 fxe6 his pawns aren't isolated. }
8. Bf4
{ The most played move and the most natural one as well. There are also good alternatives like  8.Bc4!? }
8... c6 { Black can play it slow, but he is just cramped here. } 9. Re1
{ Black is doing very poorly. His knight on e8 is sad and he has less space and nothing in return for it. Our e5-pawn is very well guarded. }
9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Nc7 11. Qc1
{ 11.Qd2  with the same continuation would run into  11...Ne6  12.Bh6?  Nxe5!  13.Nxe5  Qxd2  14.Bxd2  Bxe5  and Black has won a pawn for nothing.  In the same line with 11. Qc1 instead, Black can't exchange queens after 13. Nxe5 and will lose the exchange on f8. }
11... Ne6 12. Bh6 Qa5
{ This all happened in Svidler-Onischuk 2020 online blitz and now White shouldn't have included Bxg7 Kxg7 and gone for a checkmate. }
13. Bc4 Nb6
{ With Bxg7 Kxg7 included this would be playable, but here there is a big problem. }
14. Bxe6 Bxe6 15. Re4 { Black suddenly gets checkmated with Rh4 incoming. } *

