4... Bg7
{ There is something to be said for delaying Bg7 in systems where White goes for Be3-Qd2-Bh6 setups, but when we want to go for Be2 and O-O there isn't much point to that.   4...c6  5.Be2  b5  is just outright absurd due to  6.e5!  dxe5  7.Nxe5  when the c6-pawn is terribly weak. }
5. Be2 { Our modest but efficient development scheme, intending short castle. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... c6
{ This is a hugely popular move, intending to either slowly prepare b5 with c6 b6 a6 Bb7 @@StartBracket@@because White will obviously play  7.a4!  next@@EndBracket@@,  or e5 with Qc7 and/or Nbd7. However, the first plan is too slow, while the second is not a panacea, since the combo of having a pawn on e5 and having the bishop on g7 is not ideal. }
7. a4 Qc7 { A cautious but reasonable way to develop. } 8. h3
{ Maybe  8.Be3  or  8.a5  are more ambitious, but this simple setup is good enough for a clear-cut advantage and I think it fits in the spirit of our approach in this chapter. }
8... e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Bc4
{ The bishop belongs here after the e5 dxe5 dxe5 trade. We could also start with  10.a5!?  , which is even more ambitious. }
10... a5 11. Be3 { Another possible setup would be Qe2!?-Rd1. } 11... Na6 12.
Qd2 Qe7
{ Strong play by Black is needed to stay afloat. Now he wants to bring the knight to c5 and avoid Rad1 Qd6 which was a threat at this point. }
13. Rad1 Nc5 14. Ng5
{ And White is better since  14...h6?  falls for a very dirty trick:  15.Qd6!   Instead,  14...Ne6  would trade a bunch of pieces, but the poor g7-bishop would remain on the board for a while. }
14... h6 15. Qd6 { Black is in huge trouble all of a sudden. } *

