5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... c6
{ This is a hugely popular move, intending to either slowly prepare b5 with c6 b6 a6 Bb7 @@StartBracket@@because White will obviously play  7.a4!  next@@EndBracket@@,  or e5 with Qc7 and/or Nbd7. However, the first plan is too slow, while the second is not a panacea, since the combo of having a pawn on e5 and having the bishop on g7 is not ideal. }
7. a4 Qc7 { A cautious but reasonable way to develop. } 8. h3
{ Maybe  8.Be3  or  8.a5  are more ambitious, but this simple setup is good enough for a clear-cut advantage and I think it fits in the spirit of our approach in this chapter. }
8... Nbd7
{ This slow plan of eventually preparing b6-b5 is pretty, but as is often the case with slow plans, it's too slow. }
9. Be3 { Natural development will work out well for us in the end. } 9... b6
10. Qd2 { Just improving our pieces will prove useful once the action begins. }
10... a6
{ After  10...Bb7  we can go for a transposition with  11.Rfd1  a6  , but we also get the extra option of @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbqnppbp/1ppp1np1/8/P2PP3/2N1BN1P/1PPQBPP1/R4RK1 w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.a5!  The point being that a6 is a threat, bxa5 ruins Black's pawn structure while  11...b5  fails to  12.a6!  Bc8  13.b4!  intending d5, gobbling up the b5-pawn. }
11. Rfd1 { Setting up an exchange operation. } 11... Bb7
{ Black is all set for the planned b6-b5 push. And now we strike. } 12. e5
{ Suddenly all our natural developing moves turn out to be useful. } 12... dxe5
13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxb6
{ Black is left with a worse pawn structure and eventually a bad endgame. }
15... Nd5 16. Bd4 Qxd4 17. Qxd4 Bxd4 18. Rxd4
{ I will continue the line, because we are following some correspondent games and also because we want to make sure this doesn't just peter into a draw. }
18... Nxc3 { The most obvious move. } 19. bxc3
{ The position is incredibly simplified but Black has issues with his weak pawns. }
19... Bc8 20. a5 Be6 21. Rb4 c5 22. Rb6 c4 23. Bf3 Ra7 24. Rd1
{ The a6-pawn is a horrible weakness. Black held one correspondence game and lost the other, which seems like a good representation of his chances in this endgame. }
