{ This is a hugely popular move, intending to either slowly prepare b5 with c6 b6 a6 Bb7 @@StartBracket@@because White will obviously play  7.a4!  next@@EndBracket@@,  or e5 with Qc7 and/or Nbd7. However, the first plan is too slow, while the second is not a panacea, since the combo of having a pawn on e5 and having the bishop on g7 is not ideal. }
7. a4 Nbd7 8. h3
{ Perhaps more principled is to push 8. a5, but I like the fact that the simple, most often played setup also gives us a clear advantage. }
8... e5 { For  8...Qc7  see the line 7...Qc7 8. h3 Nbd7. } 9. dxe5
{ A standard reaction. We make sure the bishop on g7 is staring into the e5-pawn. }
9... Nxe5
{ Trading the knights would help Black somewhat, but we will not oblige. Instead we will apply pressure on the weak d6-pawn. }
10. Bf4 Qe7 11. Qd2
{ We want to double and keep applying pressure on the d6-pawn. } 11... Be6 12.
Rad1 Rfd8 13. Qe3 { The queen moves out of the x-ray. } 13... Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3
{ Black's problem is that he has a weak d6-pawn and just no counterplay ideas. }
14... Ne8 15. Bg5
{ We can provoke another weakness or trade the dark-squared bishops, weakening the black king. }
15... Bf6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Without the dark-squared bishops the pawn on g6 also looks very awkward. }
17. Rd2
{ We can double on the d-file and then, if we want to, slowly push on the kingside, starting with Be2 and f4. }
