5. Be2 { Our modest but efficient development scheme, intending short castle. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... b6 { Is not great of a move. } 7. Re1
{ Also the immediate  7.e5!?  is very promising, but the text move is very simple and strong. }
7... Bb7
{ If you say B@@StartBracket@@6@@EndBracket@@ you say B@@StartBracket@@b7@@EndBracket@@. }
8. e5 { White's position starts to unravel. } 8... dxe5 9. Nxe5
{ Next up is Bf3, opening up the e1-rook. } 9... Nbd7 10. Bf3
{ Now everything from 7. Re1 onwards starts to make sense. } 10... Bxf3 11.
Qxf3 Nxe5
{ Black has traded a bunch, but gets a position with little space and not much prospects. }
12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Bf4 { Bringing everyone in. } 13... Nc5 14. Rad1
{ Immediate h4 is good as well. } 14... Qe8 15. h4
{ Now that AlphaZero has shown us the way, we can totally see the potential behind the h5-h6 threat. Black's g7-bishop is really getting squeezed into a box. }
