{ If  8...dxe5  we can even play  9.Nxe5!?  and follow up with Bf3 with a clear advantage, due to Black's lack of space and a queenside which has been weakened by b6. }
9. Qd3
{ A cool creative idea and one to remember. We hint at Qe4 and prepare Rd1. }
9... dxe5
{ Black can try to go for our e5-pawn, but he is not developed enough to enjoy the arising complications. }
10. dxe5 Nc6
{ Black has to develop the knight, since taking on e5 immediately would lose to a fork with Qe4 in the end. }
11. Rd1
{ Also excellent is  11.e6!?  fxe6  12.Rd1!  where Black gets a very ugly pawn structure while being a pawn up on paper. }
11... Ndxe5 { Black can temporarily win a pawn here. } 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Qe4
{ Black is not losing material, but the black pieces do have to lose coordination now. }
13... Qe8 14. Bh6
{ Now we go for a forced sequence, regaining the material in the end with some dividends. }
14... Bg7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Bf3 { Continuing the sequence. } 16... Bb7 17. Nd5
{ Black has to give back what he has taken. } 17... Qc8 18. Nxe7
{ White can also play for compensation, but bailing out into a thematic endgame is a great idea. Fischer would have done the same! }
18... Nxe7 19. Qxb7 Qxb7 20. Bxb7 Ra7 21. Bf3
{ White has a superior bishop to the knight since the play will be on two flanks. Also, very importantly, the rook on a7 is out of play, while if Black goes for c5, we get to penetrate on d6, and the queenside pawns will start feeling a little uncomfortable. }
