{ There is something to be said for delaying Bg7 in systems where White goes for Be3-Qd2-Bh6 setups, but when we want to go for Be2 and O-O there isn't much point to that.   4...c6  5.Be2  b5  is just outright absurd due to  6.e5!  dxe5  7.Nxe5  when the c6-pawn is terribly weak. }
5. Be2 { Our modest but efficient development scheme, intending short castle. }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we reach a major tabiya. Traditionally the main moves are  6...c6  and  6...a6  ,  hinting at the b5 expansion. Then there is the provocative trendy  6...Nc6  .  Other moves are already more rare, but still all have the right to exist and require attention. Interestingly the move the computer considers the best,  6...e5  ,  is far from popular and for understandable reason: those who play the modern aim for complex play, something we are not going to give them, unless it's a really bad complex play. }
6... a6
{ Looking at the games, I would say this is perhaps the most topical move at the highest level. Black's idea is to include  6...a6  7.a4  and then after  7...Nc6  8.d5  he will have two extra squares to move the knight to: b4 and a7. A clever thought, but White is still better. }
7. a4
{ We 'fall' for it and play the most natural move. Space on the queenside may start to matter at some point. }
7... Nc6
{ Black is generally thrilled to play this move now, ready to meet  8.d5  with  8...Nb4!  ,  but we have other intentions. We want to grab space on the queenside and cramp that side of the board. }
8. a5
{ Now Black can no longer play the nicely flexible b6 move, and the queenside structure is definitely fixed in our favor. }
8... e5
{ The main move and the most logical one. Black has already abandoned his queenside to an extent, as we managed to attain a grip on it with a5!, but Black uses the fact that he got to keep the knight on c6 for one move and offers us to go for a King's Indian type position.Normally I would not recommend entering those positions so easily, but in this particular case, thanks to our queenside expansion, we have a clear plan on how to proceed. I also tried other moves for Black than the almost universally played 8...e5, but I couldn't find much point to them. }
9. d5 Ne7 10. Nd2
{ We prepare the Na4-c4 expansion on the queenside, but also keep the Nc4 f4 idea in mind, in case Black forgets to prepare for it with  10...Nd7  . }
10... Rb8
{ This is a tricky move, preparing to meet  11.Na4  with  11...c6!  Instead, we can switch plans and go for Nc4 f4. }
11. Nc4 { Not the only way to play, but a sensible one. } 11... Nd7 12. f4
{ We get to strike first. It is crucial that after the exf4 trade, we keep control over the e5-square and don't let Black establish a dominant knight there. }
12... exf4 13. Bxf4 f5 14. Qd2 Nf6 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Rae1
{ Black's knights are lacking squares and we will continue restricting the black pieces with moves like h3, Bf3 and so on. White is clearly better. }
