{ We prepare the Na4-c4 expansion on the queenside, but also keep the Nc4 f4 idea in mind, in case Black forgets to prepare for it with  10...Nd7  . }
10... Nd7
{ Black is going for the King's Indian style kingside offense. Luckily, we have clear targets on the queenside. }
11. Na4
{ Black's problem is that the queenside is fixed in a way that favors White, who will go for b4-c4-c5 expansion and later enjoy the weak b6-square, control of which is crucial in these King's Indian type structures. }
11... f5 { Black goes ahead with his plan. } 12. b4
{ Perhaps just a tad more precise than  12.c4  which allows the  12...c5  option. White's plan remains the same, c4-c5. }
12... Nf6 13. c4
{ It's a common theme to allow Black to capture on e4, and later regain that pawn after Nc3. }
13... f4 { The kingside pawn storm is way, way too slow. } 14. c5 g5 15. cxd6
cxd6 16. Nb6
{ We already got almost all we need on the queenside while Black hasn't even started his kingside business. Whenever we need to diffuse Black's kingside play, we will always be able to capture the key light-squared bishop. }
