12... Nf6 13. c4
{ It's a common theme to allow Black to capture on e4, and later regain that pawn after Nc3. }
13... Bh6 { Black wants to at least trade off the bad dark-squared bishop. }
14. Nc3 fxe4
{ Black simplifies into a worse position, but he did hold one correspondence game this way. }
15. Ndxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxc1 17. Rxc1 Nf5
{ Black sends his own knight to a better square as well. } 18. Bg4
{ We won't mind trading this bishop. } 18... Qh4
{ We are following Peet-Sanchez, e-mail 2017. } 19. Re1 Nd4 20. Bxc8 Raxc8 21.
Qd3
{ This all happened in the aforementioned correspondence game. Black eventually held, which isn't too surprising, since his position remains pretty solid, but there is also no doubt that White is clearly better here. Our knight is pretty on e4 and our pawn structure is better, with potential for queenside play with, for example, b5-b6 at some point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Alekhine Defense (1...Nf6)"]
[Black "Alekhine with 2...Ng8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine is a highly provocative and not entirely sound opening, but it remains a regular guest in games accross all levels. Some top players, including Magnus Carlsen employ it every now and then as a surprise weapon and among club players and amateurs as well, you see some fans of this direct approach. Black provokes us to push forward and we don't have to be asked twice to grab more space in the center. }
2. e5 Ng8
{ This is very naughty, but one should not be fooled, as the game is not over. Black is banking on the psychological effect, but if we remain undisturbed and instead grateful for the extra tempi, we should be able to get a great position from the opening. }
3. d4 d6
{ Black should, after all, get his development going and for starters try and undermine our far-advanced e-pawn. }
4. Nf3
{ In the spirit of the Four Pawns Attack would be  4.f4!?  , which is perfectly fine as well, but here Black is so poorly developed that the simple  4.Nf3  can lead to a huge advantage. }
4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 Nd7
{ Now it would be a mistake to back down with the most often played  6.Nf3?!  Instead we can afford to only go forward here. }
6. Qf3 { Also strong is  6.Bf4  , but developing the queen is very forcing. }
6... Nxe5
{ If  6...Ngf6  then after  7.Nc3  and natural development, an eventual O-O-O will leave Black with his back against the wall. }
7. dxe5 c6
{ The ambitious  7...Qd4?  loses to  8.Bb5+!   After  7...c6  Black intends  8.--  Qa5  , but we have a nasty surprise for him. }
8. Qc3
{ A new move. The queen is preventing all of Black's reasonable ideas, stopping Qa5 and also discouraging  8...g6  which is now met with  9.e6! }
8... Bf5 { Trying to develop. } 9. Na3 { The knight is heading towards c4. }
9... e6
{ This is a bad combo with c6, but what else?  9...g6  is always met with  10.e6! }
10. Nc4 { With the hole on d6, Black is busted here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Alekhine Defense (1...Nf6)"]
[Black "Alekhine with 2...Ng8 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine is a highly provocative and not entirely sound opening, but it remains a regular guest in games accross all levels. Some top players, including Magnus Carlsen employ it every now and then as a surprise weapon and among club players and amateurs as well, you see some fans of this direct approach. Black provokes us to push forward and we don't have to be asked twice to grab more space in the center. }
2. e5 Ng8
{ This is very naughty, but one should not be fooled, as the game is not over. Black is banking on the psychological effect, but if we remain undisturbed and instead grateful for the extra tempi, we should be able to get a great position from the opening. }
3. d4 d6
{ Black should, after all, get his development going and for starters try and undermine our far-advanced e-pawn. }
4. Nf3
{ In the spirit of the Four Pawns Attack would be  4.f4!?  , which is perfectly fine as well, but here Black is so poorly developed that the simple  4.Nf3  can lead to a huge advantage. }
4... Bg4
{ Such a pin can be annoying, if you don't know how to deal with it, but in this particular instance it just isn't good. }
5. h3 { Asking Black to determine the future of the g4-bishop. } 5... Bh5
{ If Black instead gives up the bishop, our play is easy: we will just finish our development and enjoy the bishop pair as well as the space advantage. }
6. g4
{ With his provocative play, Black deserves the roughest of punishments. } 6...
Bg6 7. e6
{ A thematic idea that works extremely well here, as Black has lost two tempi in the opening, moving the knight back and forth on move one and two. }
7... fxe6 8. Bc4
{ The most principled, hitting the e6 pawn and forcing a concession from Black. }
8... d5
{ Alternatively  8...Bf7  is met with the obvious  9.Ng5!  When Black's construction is falling apart. }
9. Bb3
{ I have to be honest, this move took me by surprise, but the engine places the bishop on a square where it is not in the way of our other pieces. Also Ba4! is now often an idea, whenever Black places his knight on c6. }
9... Nf6 10. O-O
{ Next we intend Re1 and c4 while Black doesn't have a good way to develop his f8 bishop. }
10... Nc6
{ This allows us to demonstrate the strength of our poor looking b3 bishop. }
11. Ba4
{ Pinning the knight and putting the bishop to good use. With Re1 and Ne5 incoming, Black is basically lost, as his f8 bishop just doesn't get to see the light.Of course, this is just a sample line and Black can probably defend more resiliently, as 2...Ng8 shouldn't be losing by force. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Alekhine Defense (1...Nf6)"]
[Black "Alekhine with 4...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine is a highly provocative and not entirely sound opening, but it remains a regular guest in games accross all levels. Some top players, including Magnus Carlsen employ it every now and then as a surprise weapon and among club players and amateurs as well, you see some fans of this direct approach. Black provokes us to push forward and we don't have to be asked twice to grab more space in the center. }
2. e5 Nd5
{ This is how the Alekhine was meant to be played. On e4 the knight is too vulnerable, while going back to g8 is far too provocative, even for the diehard Alekhine fans. }
3. c4
{ I wasn't able to spot any significant difference between  3.c4  or  3.d4  for us. I believe they call this a 'soft-fail move' on Chessable. Still, I think maaaaybe  3.c4  would be my choice and that for two reasons. First of all, after  3.d4  there is a very odd  3...c6!?  idea, intending to hide the knight on c7. Secondly, and that is important for the bullet fans, there are apparently people who after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  play  3...Ne3??  hoping for a  4.d4  premove. Punishing those players, that is a very satisfying feeling, trust me. }
3... Nb6
{ The only reasonable move, but again, don't premove 4. d4, for the 3...Ne3?? psychos. }
4. d4 { Three of our four pawns are ready for the Four Pawns Attack! } 4... d5
{ This is really quite terrible. Black won't be able to get rid of the bind this easily. I don't know what my good friend Erwin l'Ami had for dinner on 14th January 2018, to end up playing this on the 15th against Harika in Wijk aan Zee B-group. }
5. c5 N6d7 6. Nc3 Nc6
{ If  6...e6  White can just solidify the c5-pawn with  7.b4  b6  8.Rb1  a5  9.a3  when Black is unable to get rid of the bind.   After  6...Nc6  White should avoid falling for  7.Nxd5?  Ndb8!  @@StartBracket@@I hope this is not the cheapo Erwin was playing for, because Harika is far too experienced and strong to fall for it@@EndBracket@@, but White should probably also not go for  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppnpppp/2n5/2PpP3/3P4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e6  that Harika played, as here we have an enormous advantage without the need for any spectacularities. }
7. Bb5
{ Simply stopping b6 and intending to finish kingside development. Black can't undermine our massive grip and will get suffocated. A terrible version of the Advanced French @@StartBracket@@which is incidentally also covered in this course!@@EndBracket@@. }
*

