[White "14) Alekhine Defense (1...Nf6)"]
[Black "Alekhine with 5...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine is a highly provocative and not entirely sound opening, but it remains a regular guest in games accross all levels. Some top players, including Magnus Carlsen employ it every now and then as a surprise weapon and among club players and amateurs as well, you see some fans of this direct approach. Black provokes us to push forward and we don't have to be asked twice to grab more space in the center. }
2. e5 Nd5
{ This is how the Alekhine was meant to be played. On e4 the knight is too vulnerable, while going back to g8 is far too provocative, even for the diehard Alekhine fans. }
3. c4
{ I wasn't able to spot any significant difference between  3.c4  or  3.d4  for us. I believe they call this a 'soft-fail move' on Chessable. Still, I think maaaaybe  3.c4  would be my choice and that for two reasons. First of all, after  3.d4  there is a very odd  3...c6!?  idea, intending to hide the knight on c7. Secondly, and that is important for the bullet fans, there are apparently people who after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  play  3...Ne3??  hoping for a  4.d4  premove. Punishing those players, that is a very satisfying feeling, trust me. }
3... Nb6
{ The only reasonable move, but again, don't premove 4. d4, for the 3...Ne3?? psychos. }
4. d4 { Three of our four pawns are ready for the Four Pawns Attack! } 4... d6
{ Black should start undermining our center before it's too too late. } 5. f4
{ The most principled system. I was never a fan of systems where we overextend ourselves, as some of my favourite games in my childhood were the counterattacking King's Indian defense games by Fischer and Kasparov.However, in this particular instance it appears that the Four Pawns Attack, which definitely leaves an overextended impression, is an overwhelming favorite of the modern engines which dictate the opening trends. After trying to find a way for Black to undermine our pawn structure and get good counterplay, and failing along the way, I came to the conclusion that this system is worthy of recommending.   The old mainline, the simple @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  , is not nearly as challenging and gives Black plenty of ways to get a playable position, exactly what he wants when going for the Alekhine.   After  5.f4  Black generally has two setups, going for Bf5 e6 development  @@StartBracket@@usually after  5...dxe5  @@EndBracket@@ or the  5...g6  plan. }
5... Bf5
{ There can be some point in delaying dxe5, but if Black insists on it for too long, White will also get some extra options. }
6. Nc3 e6 7. Nf3
{ This is the final opportunity for Black to go  7...dxe5  and transpose to the 5...dxe5 line. }
7... Nc6
{ A wrong move order. We can surely try and transpose to dxe5 fxe5 positions, but since we can punish it, why not do so. }
8. exd6
{ Novelty here. It looks weird to give up our beautiful center, which is our pride, but we get the moves d5 and Nd4 with tempo. }
8... cxd6 9. d5 { If you say 'e' you have to say 'd'. } 9... exd5
{ After  9...Nb4  10.Nd4!  Black is facing some concrete issues. } 10. cxd5 Nb4
11. Bb5+ { Developing with tempo. } 11... Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O Be7 14.
Nd4 { Our plan is Nd4, Be3, Qf3, with or without including a3 Na6. } 14... O-O
15. a3 { Immediately  15.Be3  is also perfect. } 15... Na6 16. Be3 Re8 17. Qf3
{ Black is incredibly cramped and his position is worse than it looks, according to my engines. }
*

