3... Nb6
{ The only reasonable move, but again, don't premove 4. d4, for the 3...Ne3?? psychos. }
4. d4 { Three of our four pawns are ready for the Four Pawns Attack! } 4... d6
{ Black should start undermining our center before it's too too late. } 5. f4
{ The most principled system. I was never a fan of systems where we overextend ourselves, as some of my favourite games in my childhood were the counterattacking King's Indian defense games by Fischer and Kasparov.However, in this particular instance it appears that the Four Pawns Attack, which definitely leaves an overextended impression, is an overwhelming favorite of the modern engines which dictate the opening trends. After trying to find a way for Black to undermine our pawn structure and get good counterplay, and failing along the way, I came to the conclusion that this system is worthy of recommending.   The old mainline, the simple @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  d6  4.Nf3  , is not nearly as challenging and gives Black plenty of ways to get a playable position, exactly what he wants when going for the Alekhine.   After  5.f4  Black generally has two setups, going for Bf5 e6 development  @@StartBracket@@usually after  5...dxe5  @@EndBracket@@ or the  5...g6  plan. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6
{ The most popular move order, but Black can also start with 6...Bf5 which in most cases leads to the same tabiya. }
7. Be3
{ Here it's important to start with the bishop move, as  7.Nf3  allows the pin with  7...Bg4  . It is quite logical, so shouldn't be that hard to remember. }
7... Bf5
{ Black's only way to develop sensibly here. Next they want to go e6 and develop the f8 bishop as well. }
8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ It's also possible is to start with  9.Be2  ,  but I don't see the reason to be this subtle here as ...Bg4 now comes with a loss of a tempo, having developed itself to f5 first. In this major tabiya Black's main plan is  9...Be7  followed by f6, but we should also know how to deal with the less conventional alternatives. }
9... Be7
{ The mainline of the entire Four Pawns Attack. Black is not trying to do anything weird, but wants to castle and break our center apart with f6. }
10. Be2
{ A few decades ago there was a trend of going for a mess with 10. d5, but the modern computers have established that Black is fine there, while in the simple 10.Be2 line he just gets a worse position. }
10... O-O 11. O-O f6
{ This is a neccessary idea to deal with our strong pawn center, but the problem Black now gets is the weak e6-pawn, as well as the awkward knight on b6 of course. }
12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2
{ White has to make sure the d4-pawn is under control. That is the key in this position, otherwise we are just slightly better thanks to our better pawn structure and the terrible knight on b6. }
13... h6
{ This is a rare but reasonable move order, keeping the queen on d8 flexible. Black wants to go for a Qe8 setup and defends against the strong Bg5! response. }
14. Rad1 Qe8 15. Bf4
{ The direct way to deal with the potential pressure along the d-file, as we intend to go Qe3 next. Black's position is not hopeless, as he will try to simplify with an eventual e5 push, but in the end, the b6 knight will remain a bad piece and White will have an advantage. }
