[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ This system really doesn't make all too much sense against us, as we are fine with all the transpositions that can eventually arise. }
2. Nf3
{ There is no need to get provoked. Also,  2.d4  d5  is actually not such a bad system for Black.   After  2.Nf3  if Black goes  2...e5  we can play our Italian @@StartBracket@@or a Spanish or Scotch if that's what you prefer@@EndBracket@@ and so in this chapter we should look at other options. }
2... d5
{ This can transpose to a shady Scandinavian, but there is one independent line @@StartBracket@@which is even more shady@@EndBracket@@. }
3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5 5. Bb5
{ This is the easiest, distracting Black from his Bg4 plans. } 5... Bd7 6. d4
{ Gaining some ground in the center right away is the most accurate. } 6... a6
{ If Black castles long first, White has many good options - for example  6...O-O-O  7.d5  . }
7. Bc4 { Again, the most accurate, as per the all-knowing computer. } 7...
O-O-O 8. h3
{ Taking the time to stop the Bg4 pin. If e5 we always have d5! in response. Black is in poor shape here. }
8... Nf6 9. O-O e5 10. d5
{ The way to go. Our pieces are ready to back up the far advanced d-pawn. }
10... Be6 11. Bg5
{ Our d5-pawn somehow survives and it is Black who is losing material in the end. }
