2. Nf3
{ There is no need to get provoked. Also,  2.d4  d5  is actually not such a bad system for Black.   After  2.Nf3  if Black goes  2...e5  we can play our Italian @@StartBracket@@or a Spanish or Scotch if that's what you prefer@@EndBracket@@ and so in this chapter we should look at other options. }
2... e6 { This is a terrible French defense. } 3. d4 d5 4. e5
{ This setup although poor, does some sense, if Black goes for f6 break next. }
4... f6 5. c3
{ Less obvious than the logical  5.Bb5  , but very strong. We replace our e5 pawn with our d4 pawn and keep the space advantage. }
5... fxe5 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5
{ White has a much easier development, due to the extra space. } 7... Bc5
{ An attempt to develop harmoniously. } 8. Qh5+
{ Provoking g6, weakening the dark square complex on the kingside. } 8... g6 9.
Qh3
{ Black's position is very weakened and we will finish our development with Bd3 and Nd2-Nf3, when eventually the dark square weaknesses will tell. }
