2. Nf3
{ There is no need to get provoked. Also,  2.d4  d5  is actually not such a bad system for Black.   After  2.Nf3  if Black goes  2...e5  we can play our Italian @@StartBracket@@or a Spanish or Scotch if that's what you prefer@@EndBracket@@ and so in this chapter we should look at other options. }
2... d6
{ This move order makes a lot of sense against people who play systems without Nf3 against the Pirc, but against the Pirc we are playing the Nf3 Be2 system, so we don't care that the knight came out so early to c6. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O
{ Now after  6...O-O  we transpose to the Pirc with 6...Nc6, which, by the way, is quite dubious for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Black's Early Alternatives: 1...b6"]
[Black "1...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ This system is played occasionally, especially in online chess, I feel. Black wants to gain space on the queenside and fianchetto the bishop. However, he commits his queenside pawns too early and neglects the development. The punishment will be swift. }
2. d4 { Of course. } 2... b5
{ Objectively better is to switch to the French with  2...e6  .  For those positions see the French Chapter. }
3. a4
{ Right away targetting the weak pawns and defining the pawn structure. Starting with  3.Nd2!?  and 4. a4! next leads to the same. }
3... b4
{ The often played  3...Bb7  leads to the same thing after  4.Nd2!  b4  . } 4.
Nd2 Bb7 5. Bd3 { We can delay the development of the g1-knight for now. } 5...
e6 6. Nb3
{ There are really many ways to develop initiative here: the natural  6.Ngf3  of course, but also a move like  6.Nh3!?  I like the move I am recommending a lot as well. The knight sits pretty on b3. }
6... Nf6 7. Qe2 { We are developed very harmoniously. } 7... d6 8. Nf3
{ Black has no counterplay on the queenside, as after the standard  8...c5  we can just take  9.dxc5  dxc5  and enjoy a hole on c4. }
8... a5 { Black has to take care of the Na5!? idea. } 9. h4
{ 9.O-O  is also fantastic for White, but this creative idea is pretty. } 9...
Nbd7 10. Rh3 { The rook lift is effective. } 10... Be7 { A short sample line. }
11. e5 { Time to strike. } 11... Nd5 12. Rg3 g6 13. h5
{ Black is worse left, right and in the center. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Black's Early Alternatives: 1...b6"]
[Black "1... b6 with 3...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... Nf6 { This is played a lot, followed by Nc6 with some Nb4 ideas. } 4. Qe2
Nc6 { Alternatively  4...e6  will transpose to 3...e6. } 5. c3
{ We have to watch out for Nb4 here, which is a strong positional threat. }
5... e5
{ This is somewhat of a bluff. Black pretends he wants to go exd4 cxd4 Nb4. }
6. Nf3 { In fact exd4 is not good. } 6... exd4
{ Here it's important not to go for the automatic recapture. } 7. O-O
{ With the king in the center, Black will not survive this position. e5 is coming. }
*

