[Black "1... b6 with 3...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... Nf6 { This is played a lot, followed by Nc6 with some Nb4 ideas. } 4. Qe2
Nc6 { Alternatively  4...e6  will transpose to 3...e6. } 5. c3
{ We have to watch out for Nb4 here, which is a strong positional threat. }
5... e5
{ This is somewhat of a bluff. Black pretends he wants to go exd4 cxd4 Nb4. }
6. Nf3 { In fact exd4 is not good. } 6... d6
{ Black just continues playing, but after d4-d5 Black gets an awful King's Indian. }
7. d5 { We can close the position before castling, keeping more options open. }
7... Nb8 8. c4 g6
{ Black plays the King's Indian, but having played b6 Bb7 was counterproductive. }
9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Bg5
{ Castling short and playing on the queenside with b4 is a very fine way to proceed, but I like the more aggressive approach since we can afford it. }
10... O-O 11. h4
{ We can do some damage on the kingside here and just castle long. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Black's Early Alternatives: 1...b6"]
[Black "1... b6 with 3...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... f5
{ This is the most 'logical' follow up to Black's play, but it just doesn't work as we can sac the rook on h1 and go for checkmate. }
4. exf5 Bxg2 5. Qh5+ g6 6. fxg6 Bg7
{ Black's point. He avoids the immediate checkmate, but we are not impressed. }
7. gxh7+ Kf8 8. Nf3 { Also crushing is  8.Nh3! } 8... Nf6
{ Black wins a piece for a moment, but we are going to win it back quickly.  8...Bxh1  9.Ne5!  is just lights out. }
9. Qg6 Bxf3
{ If Black grabs the rook, it's just checkmate:  9...Bxh1  10.Bh6  Rxh7  11.Ng5  . }
10. Rg1 Rxh7 11. Qg3
{ The cleanest. Now we just regain the piece and end up with a winning position at no material deficit. }
11... Be4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qf3+
{ Black loses the knight and will be a pawn down, but mainly his king is doomed, with no pawn shelter. }
*

