[White "16) Black's Early Alternatives: 1...b6"]
[Black "1... b6 with 3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... d6 { Some decent players have played this indecent system. } 4. Nf3
{ There are many ways to get a large positional advantage. For instance,  4.c4  leads to some kind of a great King's Indian, because after the eventual e5 d5 structure change the bishop on b7 will be misplaced. }
4... Nd7 5. O-O e5
{ This is how they play it. Now, everything is good, but I like a little positional idea on the queenside. }
6. a4 { Intending a5, tickling Black on the queenside. } 6... a6
{ This standard response is bad here, because we don't have our knight on c3 yet. }
7. a5 b5 8. c4 { Undermining the queenside pawns. } 8... b4 9. Bc2
{ With a very unpleasant threat of Ba4. Black is already doing really badly. }
*

