1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... e6 { The most popular continuation. } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 6. Qe2 f5
{ Best, as after  6...d5  we can try to trap the knight with O-O Ne1 ideas, or simply exchange it off with Nbd2 getting an overwhelming positional advantage in the spirit of the Advanced French. }
7. Nbd2 Nxd2 8. Bxd2
{ We will crush after long castle as Rhg1 g4 will happen. } *

