1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... e6 { The most popular continuation. } 4. Nf3 d6
{ Radjabov played this a couple of times online, but it's really not a good setup. }
5. O-O Nd7 6. a4 a6 7. Re1 Ngf6
{ So far Carlsen played it quite precisely, but here he could have gone for more than just a big advantage with his modest Nbd2-Nf1-Ng3 maneuver. }
8. a5 { Also very strong is first  8.c4!?  and then a5. } 8... b5 9. c4
{ Blasting the queenside open. } 9... bxc4 10. Bxc4 Be7 11. d5
{ We gain a huge edge on the queenside with those powerful pawn moves. } 11...
e5
{ This position only looks closed. Better is  11...exd5  12.exd5  ,  but it's also quite bad for Black and very easy to play with White, with an eventual b4-b5 breakthrough to come. }
12. Nc3 O-O 13. b4 { With an eventual b5 break to decide the matters. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Black's Early Alternatives: 1...b6"]
[Black "1... b6 with 3...e6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... e6 { The most popular continuation. } 4. Nf3 d5
{ Apparently, Lawrence Trent recommends this in his 1...b6 Chessable course @@StartBracket@@as an ambassador for Chessable, may I know why we have a 1...b6 course and why nobody asked for my permission??@@EndBracket@@. Even this ingenious invention of Lawrence isn't able to make 1...b6 a great weapon. }
5. exd5 Qxd5
{ Taking on d5 with the bishop leads to the same thing. Now we gain a lot of time on the queen on d5 with  6.c4  .  I feel the best way to utilize our huge lead in development is to go for the kill with a long castle plan. }
6. c4 { Gaining space in the center and kicking the queen away with tempo. }
6... Qd8 { The best square for the queen as  6...Qh5  is met with  7.Be2! } 7.
Nc3 { I propose to delay short castle and go for the more ambitious setup. }
7... Nf6 8. Qe2 { Making our intentions clear. } 8... Nbd7
{ After  8...Be7  , for example, we can go  9.Bf4  ,  followed by long castle and a kingside attack, which involves ideas like h4, Rh3, Ne5 and what not. }
9. Bc2
{ A clever idea of the computer. We wait for Black to develop their bishop first before deciding where to place our c1-bishop. }
9... Bb4 10. Bd2
{ The most human, not allowing Black to damage our queenside pawn structure. Next, we want to castle long and start an attack on the kingside. }
*

