1. e4 b6
{ The queenside fianchetto is not a great opening, since White gets to enjoy the full control of the center. Still, it's good to know how to proceed and make use of all that central control that is given to us. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ The most natural way to defend the e4-pawn, not fearing  3...f5?  which is a losing mistake. }
3... e6 { The most popular continuation. } 4. Nf3 c5
{ The alternatives are not great either.  4...Nf6  allows  5.e5!  when there is no good square for the knight, while  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pbpp1ppp/1p2p3/8/3PP3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d6  trying to build a hippo is bad because after we castle and play Re1 we will go for a4 and a6 will be met with a5 b5 c4!, all because we delayed the development of the knight to c3. }
5. d5
{ The major tabiya after  5.c3  is also quite bad for Black, but this is the most powerful continuation, not letting Black get out of the opening alive. }
5... exd5 6. exd5 Bxd5 7. Nc3
{ We get a lot of tempi and a huge lead in development for just one pawn. }
7... Be6 8. Bf4 { Black is facing concrete issues. } 8... Nf6
{ If  8...Nc6  there is  9.Ba6!  and if @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/p2p1ppp/1p2b3/2p5/5B2/2NB1N2/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a6  9.Be4! }
9. Nb5 { A very unpleasant question for Black. } 9... Nd5 10. Bg5
{ The strongest. } 10... Be7 { Is also not going to do it for Black. } 11. Be4
{ A strong forcing sequence ensues. } 11... Nc6 12. Bxd5 Bxg5 13. Bxe6 fxe6
{ And now we have a very powerful maneuver. } 14. Qd6
{ Threatening Nc7 and enticing Rc8. } 14... Rc8 15. Qg3
{ A double attack of sorts. Black has no defense to both Qxg5 and Nd6+, since  15...Be7  loses the g7-pawn. }
